{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}} {{Christianity and sexual orientation}} The [[law of chastity]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) states that "sexual relations are proper only between a man and a woman who are legally and lawfully wedded as husband and wife."<ref>[//www.lds.org/topics/same-sex-marriage "Same-Sex Marriage"], lds.org, accessed June 17, 2016.</ref> In principle, this commandment forbids all same-sex sexual behavior (whether intra-marriage or extramarital). Homosexuality-related violations of the law of chastity may result in [[disciplinary council|church discipline]].
Members of the church who experience homosexual attractions, including those who [[Coming out|self-identify as gay, lesbian, or bisexual]], may remain in good standing in the church if they abstain from sexual relations (outside opposite-sex marriage).<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /><ref name="hinckley98">{{citation |last= Hinckley |first= Gordon B. |author-link= Gordon B. Hinckley |title= What Are People Asking about Us? |url= //www.lds.org/ensign/1998/11/what-are-people-asking-about-us |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= November 1998 |publisher= LDS Church}}</ref> Although no one, including those participating in same-sex sexual behavior, is forbidden from LDS Church Sunday worship services,<ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.mormon.org/worship#what-to-expect |title= Worship with Us: What to Expect |work= mormon.org |publisher= LDS Church |accessdate= July 2, 2014}}</ref> acquiring and maintaining membership in the church and receiving a [[temple recommend]] is dependent upon observing the law of chastity's prohibition of sexual relationships outside a marital relationship between husband and wife.<ref>{{citation |url= //www.lds.org/topics/temples |title= Gospel Topics: Temples |work= lds.org |publisher= LDS Church |accessdate= July 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url= //www.lds.org/topics/church-disciplinary-councils |title= Gospel Topics: Church Disciplinary Councils |work= lds.org |publisher= [[LDS Church]] |accessdate= July 2, 2014}}</ref>
The LDS Church previously taught that [[homosexuality]] is a curable condition,<ref name=Curable /><ref name="Counselling" /> but now states that "individuals do not choose to have such attractions"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mormonsandgays.org/ |work=Mormons and Gays |title=Love One Another: A Discussion on Same-Sex Attraction |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref> and that [[Conversion therapy|therapy]] focusing on "a change in sexual orientation" is "unethical."<ref name="Seeking Professional Help">{{cite web|title=Seeking Professional Help|url=//mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/seeking-professional-help|website=mormonandgay.lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 2016}}</ref> The church teaches that regardless of the cause of [[same sex attraction]], "immoral relationships" must be abjured,<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007">{{cite interview |first= Dallin H. |last= Oaks |subjectlink= Dallin H. Oaks |first2= Lance B. |last2= Wickman |subjectlink2= Lance B. Wickman |interviewer= LDS Church Public Affairs staffers |title= Same-Gender Attraction |url= http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/interview-oaks-wickman-same-gender-attraction |type=Interview: Transcript |work= Newsroom |publisher=LDS Church |location= Salt Lake City, Utah |date= September 2006}} See also the Salt Lake Tribune archived transcript [http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=4275317&itype=NGPSID here].</ref><ref>{{citation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220063131/http://speeches.byu.edu/reader/reader.php?id=7014|archive-date=20 February 2012|url=http://speeches.byu.edu/reader/reader.php?id=7014|title=Free Agency and Freedom|last=Oaks|first=Dallin|location=Brigham Young University|date=11 October 1987}}</ref> leaving homosexual members with the option of attempting to [[Sexual orientation change efforts|change their sexual orientation]], entering a [[Mixed-orientation marriage|mixed-orientation opposite-sex marriage]], or living a [[Celibacy|celibate]] lifestyle without any sexual expression (including [[Masturbation and The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|masturbation]]).<ref name="Conservative Christian Identity">{{cite book|last1=Phillips|first1=Rick|title=Conservative Christian Identity & Same-Sex Orientation: The Case of Gay Mormons|date=2005|publisher=Peter Lang Publishing|location=Frankfurt, Germany|isbn=0820474800|url=https://www.uvu.edu/religiousstudies/docs/msc_philips_conservative.pdf|accessdate=31 May 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418092803/https://www.uvu.edu/religiousstudies/docs/msc_philips_conservative.pdf|archivedate=April 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>{{rp|11}}<ref name="Examination">{{cite journal|last1=Cook|first1=Bryce|title=What Do We Know of God's Will for His LGBT Children? An Examination of the LDS Church's Current Position on Homosexuality|journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|date=Summer 2017|volume=50|issue=2|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/archive/dialogue-premium-content/premium-digital-articles-vol-50-num-2-summer-2017/}}</ref>{{rp|20–21}}
[[File:SLC Temple Rainbow Flag.jpg|thumb|right|An LGBT pride flag in front of the Salt Lake City LDS temple]] The LDS Church has campaigned against government recognition of [[same-sex marriage]],<ref name="LDS Church 2004" /> and the issue of same-sex marriage has been one of the church's foremost political concerns since the 1990s. For example, church members represented as much as 80 to 90 percent of the early volunteers petitioning voters door-to-door and 50 percent of the campaign funds in support of [[California Proposition 8 (2008)]].<ref>{{Citation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/us/politics/15marriage.html?_r=2&pagewanted=1&hp&oref=slogin|title=Mormons Tipped Scale in Ban on Gay Marriage|date=November 14, 2008|accessdate=August 26, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|first1=Jesse|last1=McKinley|first2=Kirk|last2=Johnson}}</ref> The church supported a Salt Lake City ordinance protecting members of the [[gay community|LGBT community]] against discrimination in employment and housing while at the same time allowing religious institutions to exercise their religious beliefs while hiring or providing university accommodations, stating it remained "unequivocally committed to defending the bedrock foundation of marriage between a man and a woman."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705343558/Mormon-Church-backs-protection-of-gay-rights-in-Salt-Lake-City.html|title=Mormon Church backs protection of gay rights in Salt Lake City|newspaper=Deseret News|first=Scott|last=Taylor|date=November 10, 2009}}</ref>
In November 2015, the church updated its policies regarding those in legal same-sex unions, stating that such couples are apostates from the church.<ref>{{citation |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/11/05/mormon-church-to-exclude-children-of-same-sex-couples-from-getting-blessed-and-baptized-until-they-are-18/ |title=Mormon Church to exclude children of same-sex couples from getting blessed and baptized until they are 18 |date=November 6, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=June 9, 2016 }}</ref> Its new policies also bar such couples' children—either adopted or biological—from being baptized, confirmed, ordained, or participating in mission service until reaching adulthood and obtaining permission from the [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]].<ref name="2015developments">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/07/us/mormons-gay-marriage.html?_r=0|title=Mormons Reinforce Stand on Same-Sex Marriage|work=New York Times|date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> The church's policies and treatment of LGBT people has long been a source of controversy both within and outside the church<ref name="archive.sltrib.com">{{cite news|last1=Winters|first1=Rosemary|title=Mormon apostle's words about gays spark protest|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/sltrib/home/50434583-76/gay-church-packer-protest.html.csp|accessdate=16 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=19 October 2010}}</ref><ref name="The Washington Post">{{cite news|last1=Bailey|first1=Sarah Pulliam|title=Mormon Church to exclude children of same-sex couples from getting blessed and baptized until they are 18|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/11/05/mormon-church-to-exclude-children-of-same-sex-couples-from-getting-blessed-and-baptized-until-they-are-18/|accessdate=12 November 2016|publisher=The Washington Post|date=11 Nov 2016}}</ref> and a significant cause of disagreement and disaffection by members.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Caryle|title=Most U.S. Christian groups grow more accepting of homosexuality|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/12/18/most-u-s-christian-groups-grow-more-accepting-of-homosexuality/|website=pewresearch.org|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref><ref name="theguardian.com">{{cite journal|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|title='I'm not a Mormon': fresh 'mass resignation’ over anti-LGBT beliefs|journal=The Guardian|date=15 August 2016|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/aug/15/mormon-church-lgbt-mass-resignation-protest-utah|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hatch|first1=Heidi|title=Millennial Mormons leaving faith at higher rate than previous generations|url=http://kutv.com/news/local/millennial-mormons-leaving-faith-more-than-previous-generations-are-more-republican|agency=KUTV|publisher=CBS Television Sinclair Broadcast Group|date=13 April 2016}}</ref> {{TOC limit|2}}
==History and background== {{see also|Christianity and homosexuality|Homosexual behavior and Judaism|The Bible and homosexuality|Homosexuality in the Hebrew Bible|Homosexuality in the New Testament|Leviticus 18|Abomination (Bible)}} [[File:Slc mormon tempel.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Joseph Smith introduced "the new and everlasting covenant" as a temple marriage.]]
The entire body of LDS canonized [[scripture]] (including the [[Book of Mormon]], [[Pearl of Great Price (Mormonism)|Pearl of Great Price]] and [[Doctrine and Covenants]]) is silent on same-sex sexual activity except for the Bible.<ref name="Prophets and Preference">{{cite journal|last1=Phillips|first1=Richard|title=Prophets and Preference: Constructing and Maintaining a Homosexual Identity in the Mormon Church|journal=All Graduate Theses and Dissertations: Utah State University|date=1 January 1993|issue=Paper 2513|url=http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3518&context=etd|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|114}} However, sexual immorality (coupled with forsaking a ministry) was described in the Book of Mormon as the "most abominable above all sins save it be the shedding of innocent blood or denying the Holy Ghost."<ref>{{lds|Alma|alma|39|5}}</ref><ref>{{lds|2 Nephi|2-ne|13|9}}</ref> The LDS Church teaches that the [[Bible]] [[The Bible and homosexuality|forbids homosexuality]].<ref name="SOCE3" /><ref name="Harold">{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Clyde J.|title=The Teachings of Harold B. Lee|date=1996|publisher=Bookcraft Inc.|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=1570084831|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Teachings_of_Harold_B_Lee.html?id=H0JzlwEACAAJ}}</ref>{{rp|230}}<ref>{{citation|last=Faulconer|first=James E.|authorlink=James E. Faulconer|year=1999|chapter=Verses 24–32|chapter-url=http://maxwellinstitute.byu.edu/publications/books/?bookid=97&chapid=1031|title=Romans 1: Notes and Reflections|location=Provo, Utah|publisher=[[Foundation for Ancient Research and Mormon Studies|FARMS]], [[Brigham Young University]]|isbn=0-934893-44-6|oclc=42580110 }}</ref>
Historian [[D. Michael Quinn]] has suggested that early church leaders had a more tolerant view of homosexuality, but leaders like then [[Apostle (Latter Day Saints)|apostle]] [[Gordon B. Hinckley|Gordon Hinckley]] have stated that LDS leaders have always considered homosexual behavior a grievous sin.<ref name="Reverance">{{Citation |last= Hinckley |first= Gordon B. |author-link= Gordon B. Hinckley |title= Reverence and Morality |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= May 1987 |page= 45 |url= http://www.lds.org/ensign/1987/05/reverence-and-morality }}</ref> The first recorded instance of a Church leader using the term "homosexuality" in a public discourse was [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] member [[J. Reuben Clark]] in a 1952 General Conference,<ref>{{citation journal|last=Clark|first=J. Reuben|author-link=J. Reuben Clark|title=Home and the Building of Home Life|journal=[[Relief Society Magazine]] |volume=39|issue=12|date=December 1952|pages=793–794|url=https://atom.lib.byu.edu/rsmag/7426/}}</ref> though, the term had been in use in the US since 1892.<ref name="Dynamics">{{cite book|last1=Quinn|first1=D. Michael|title=Same-Sex Dynamics among Nineteenth-Century Americans: A Mormon Example|date=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0252022050|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UXVj398JvnsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|422}} It appears that by the 1940s church leaders had a greater awareness of homosexual behavior in Utah since apostle [[Charles A. Callis|Charles Callis]] had been assigned to cases of church members involved in homosexuality sometime before 1947<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mohrman|first1=K.|title=Queering the LDS Archive|journal=Radical History Review|date=May 2015|issue=122|url=http://rhr.dukejournals.org/content/2015/122/143.full.pdf+html|page=154|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref><ref name="Bookcraft" />{{rp|271}} and surveillance had been organized in 1945 to stop male-male sexual activity in the church's (now-demolished) Deseret Gymnasium steam room.<ref name="Hierarchy" />{{rp|307}} Callis was succeeded in the appointment over homosexual cases by apostle [[Spencer W. Kimball|Spencer Kimball]] in 1947.<ref name="Bookcraft">{{cite book|last1=Kimball|first1=Edward L.|last2=Kimball|first2=Andrew E.|title=Spencer W. Kimball: Twelfth President of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|date=1977|isbn=0884943305|publisher=Bookcraft|location=Salt Lake City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qKDtAAAAMAAJ}} Also available at [https://archive.org/details/spencerwkimballt00kimb archive.org]</ref>{{rp|271}}<ref name="The birth of Mormon homophobia">{{cite news|url=http://gaysaltlake.com/news/2011/09/01/lambda-lore-the-birth-of-mormon-homophobia/|title=Lamba Lore: The birth of Mormon homophobia|last1=Williams|first1=Ben|date=1 Sep 2011|work=|accessdate=23 February 2017|agency=Q Salt Lake Magazine}}</ref> Kimball later shared this role with apostle [[Mark E. Petersen|Mark Petersen]] in 1959.<ref name="Bookcraft" />{{rp|381}}<ref name="Hierarchy" />{{rp|307}}<ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|147}}
===Changes in teachings=== Since the first recorded mentions of homosexuality by general church leaders, teachings and policies around the topics of the [[Homosexuality|nature]], [[Homosexuality#Causes|etiology]], [[Sexual orientation change efforts|mutability]], and [[Sexual identity|identity]] around same-sex [[Romantic orientation|romantic]] and [[Sexual orientation|physical attractions]] have seen many changes through the decades,<ref name="Women" />{{rp|45–46}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrison|first1=Mette Ivie|title=Mormons and Gays: Where Are We Now?|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mette-ivie-harrison/mormons-and-gays-where-ar_b_9477504.html|accessdate=23 June 2017|work=Huffington Post|agency=Oath Inc.|date=18 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|13–21}} including a softening in rhetoric over time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schow|first1=Ron|last2=Schow|first2=Wayne|last3=Raynes|first3=Marybeth|title=Peculiar People: Mormons and Same-Sex Orientation|date=June 1991|publisher=Signature Books|isbn=1-56085-046-9|pages=xxiv-xxvii|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xz4mAQAAIAAJ&source=gbs_ViewAPI|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="Obscurity">{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Neil J.|title=Out of Obscurity: Mormonism Since 1945|date=1 July 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0199358222|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcySDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref>{{rp|169–170}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Mormon stance on gays softening|url=http://www.richmond.com/news/mormon-stance-on-gays-softening/article_0ba3ef35-4728-5041-b727-01b8388c1169.html|accessdate=26 May 2017|agency=Richmond Times-Dispatch|date=9 October 2013}}</ref> In reference to the harsh rhetoric on homosexuality of the past, the apostle [[D. Todd Christofferson|Todd Christofferson]] stated in a 2015 interview, "I think we can express things better." Regarding this subject, apostle [[Dallin H. Oaks|Dallin Oaks]] said, "I know that the history of the church is not to seek apologies or to give them. We sometimes look back on issues and say, 'Maybe that was counterproductive for what we wish to achieve,' but we look forward and not backward."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher Stack|first1=Peggy|title=We all can be more civil on LGBT issues, Mormon leader says|url=http://www.sltrib.com/lifestyle/faith/2108746-155/we-all-can-be-more-civil?fullpage=1|accessdate=31 July 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=30 January 2015}}</ref> A table summarizing some of the major shifts in official dialogue is found below. {|class="wikitable" style="text-align: center; vertical-align: center" |+ Summary of changes in teachings on homosexuality ! Topic ! Earlier teachings ! Transitional teachings ! Current teachings |- !Inborn | No <ref>{{citation|last=Packer |first=Boyd K. |authorlink=Boyd K. Packer |title=To Young Men Only |year=1976 |publisher=LDS Church |url=https://www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/english/pdf/language-materials/33382_eng.pdf |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311171249/https://www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/english/pdf/language-materials/33382_eng.pdf |archivedate=March 11, 2016 |df=mdy-all|quote=There is a falsehood that some are born with an attraction to their own kind.... That is a malicious and destructive lie.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Faust|first1=James E.|title=Serving the Lord and Resisting the Devil|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/1995/09/serving-the-lord-and-resisting-the-devil|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=16 November 2016|quote=The false belief of inborn homosexual orientation denies to repentant souls the opportunity to change and will ultimately lead to discouragement, disappointment, and despair.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Understanding and Changing Homosexual Orientation Problems|date=1981|page=4|publisher=LDS Church|quote=Because man does have moral free agency it is inconsistent to believe that a person's homosexual orientation is inborn or locked in, and there is no real hope of change.|url=https://search.lib.byu.edu/byu/record/lee.2255698}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Homosexuality|date=1981|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, UT|url=https://search.lib.byu.edu/byu/record/lee.786190?holding=ey812d1gmuud6iry|page=2|quote=It is inconceivable that—as some involved in homosexual behavior claim—[the Lord] would permit his children to be born with desires and inclinations which would require behavior contrary to his plan.}} Also quoted in [http://www.newsweek.com/masturbation-gay-leaked-mormon-church-lgtb-religion-sex-748201 this 'Newsweek' article].</ref> | Maybe<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oaks|first1=Dallin|title=Same-Gender Attraction|url=https://www.lds.org/ensign/1995/10/same-gender-attraction?lang=eng&_r=1|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 1995|quote=Perhaps such susceptibilities are inborn or acquired without personal choice ... [and] may have some relationship to inheritance.}}</ref> | No position<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview With Elder Dallin H. Oaks and Elder Lance B. Wickman: "Same-Gender Attraction"|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/interview-oaks-wickman-same-gender-attraction|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|date=September 2006|quote=The Church does not have a position on the causes of any of ... same-gender attraction. Those are scientific questions ....}}</ref> |- !Causes | Addiction,<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Rector, Hartman Jr. |date=April 1981 |title=Turning the Hearts |trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K2KLpASKc2A#t=6m47s |access-date= |format= |time=6:47 |location=Salt Lake City, Utah |publisher=LDS Church |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote=[T]o be homosexual ... I am sure is an acquired addiction, just as drugs, alcohol and pornography are.}} Video also available at [https://www.lds.org/general-conference/1981/04/turning-the-hearts?lang=eng lds.org]</ref> masturbation,<ref name="KimballOnMorality">{{Cita