e= |url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/2112602-155/tomorrow-at-115-pm-lds-apostles |access-date= |format= |time=17:32 |location=Salt Lake City, Utah |publisher=The Salt Lake Tribune |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote=We definitely do not recommend marriage as a solution for same-gender feelings. No, it’s not a therapy. In times past, decades ago, there were some practices to that effect. We have eradicated them in the Church now. |ref= }}</ref> |}
Some changes have seemed abrupt and contradictory as was the case in September 1995 when a First Presidency member affirmed in the Ensign that an inborn homosexual orientation was a false belief with no scientific evidence and that if homosexuality were inborn it would frustrate God's plan.<ref name="Faust" /> In the next month's edition of the Ensign,<ref name="SGA" /> however, an Apostle refuted this without referring to it directly by stating that there is some evidence that inheritance plays a role in a homosexual orientation.<ref name="Hierarchy">{{cite book|last1=Quinn|first1=D. Michael|title=The Mormon Hierarchy: Extensions of Power|date=15 January 1997|publisher=Signature Books|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=1560850604|edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Mormon_Hierarchy.html?id=VnbZAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|58}}
===Early instances=== [[File:Joseph Fielding Smith (presiding patriarch).jpg|right|thumbnail|100px|[[Joseph Fielding Smith (presiding patriarch)|Patriarch Smith]] was released amidst accusations of homosexual affairs]] There were several known or alleged instances of same-sex sexual activity by church members in the 19th century and early 20th century. These include the young man George Naylor,<ref name="Heritage">{{cite book|last1=Stewart|first1=Chuck|title=Proud Heritage: People, Issues, and Documents of the LGBT Experience|date=16 December 2014|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1610693981|edition=3rd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8r2aBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1200&lpg=PA1200#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|1200}} the actress [[Ada Dwyer Russell|Ada Russell]],<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|427–428}} and the researcher [[Mildred J. Berryman|Mildred Berryman]].<ref name="Invisible">{{cite book|last1=McHugh|first1=Kathleen A.|last2=Johnson-Grau|first2=Brenda|last3=Sher|first3=Ben Raphael|title=Making Invisible Histories Visible|date=2014|publisher=University of California, Los Angeles Center for the Study of Women|location=Los Angeles|isbn=9780615990842|page=68|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107060544/http://csw.pre.ss.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/35/2015/10/MakingInvisibleHistoriesVisiblePartII.pdf|archive-date=7 November 2017|url=https://csw.ucla.edu/publications/making-invisible-histories-visible-2/}} Also hosted online at [https://escholarship.org/uc/item/5k44b4tk escholarship.org]</ref><ref name="Mildred">{{cite web|last1=Wood|first1=Stacy|last2=Cubé|first2=Caroline|title=Mildred Berryman papers 1918-1990|url=http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/c87s7qx2/entire_text/|website=oac.cdlib.org|publisher=University of California, Los Angeles}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|226–228}} During the early days of the church, when same-sex sexual activity by a member was suspected, the accused was sometimes disfellowshipped or excommunicated. The first known instance of church discipline related this was in 1841 around the alleged bisexual behavior of church leader [[John C. Bennett|John Bennett]], allegedly with [[Francis M. Higbee|Francis Higbee]].<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|266–267}} [[Valeen Tippetts Avery|Valeen Avery]] has suggested that [[Joseph Smith]]'s son, [[David Hyrum Smith]] (1844–1904), may have been gay.<ref>{{citation|first=Valeen Tippetts|last=Avery|author-link=Valeen Tippetts Avery|title=From Mission to Madness: Last Son of the Mormon Prophet|publisher=[[University of Illinois Press]]|year=1998|chapter=Chapter 12: David and Charley|pages=232–243|isbn=0-252-02399-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DNJeoNhTp10C&lpg=PP1&pg=PA242#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
One of the more prominent instances of homosexual activity by a Mormon man in the early 20th century was [[presiding patriarch]] [[Joseph Fielding Smith (presiding patriarch)|Joseph Fielding Smith]]. He served in the position only four years before being released by church president [[George Albert Smith]] for reasons of "ill health."<ref>{{cite journal|title=Patriarch to the Church: Released from Duties|journal=The Improvement Era|date=November 1946|volume=49|issue=11|pages=685, 708|url=https://dcms.lds.org/delivery/StreamGate?is_mobile=false&is_rtl=false&dps_dvs=1523831269524~886&dps_pid=FL1178828}}</ref> It is reported that he had been involved in several [[Homosexuality|gay]] affairs with at least three men<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|369–371}}<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Donovan |first1=Connell |last2=Quinn |first2=D. Michael |title=Chronology of Events on Patriarch Joseph Fielding Smith’s Homosexuality |url=http://www.affirmation.org/memorial/joseph_fielding_smith.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122080551/http://www.affirmation.org/memorial/joseph_fielding_smith.shtml |archivedate=January 22, 2010 |website=affirmation.org |publisher=Affirmation |accessdate=23 February 2017 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Bates|first1=Irene M.|title=Lost legacy: The Mormon Office of Presiding Patriarch|date=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Champaign, IL|isbn=0252021630|edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Lost_Legacy.html?id=34LZAAAAMAAJ|pages=195–196, 200}}</ref> After being released, Smith took his wife and children to [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]].<ref name="The birth of Mormon homophobia"/>
===As a curable illness=== In 1959, in response to a rash of arrests of gay men in Utah and Idaho, [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|church president]] [[David O. McKay]] had apostles [[Spencer W. Kimball]] and [[Mark E. Petersen]] focus their assignment on curing gay members.<ref name="Bookcraft" />{{rp|381}} At the time, the [[American Psychiatric Association]]'s ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]]'' classified homosexuality as a mental illness, and Kimball was adamant that it could be cured. Speaking to church educators and LDS psychiatrists in 1965, Kimball said, citing a ''[[Medical World News]]'' article, that "[w]e know such a disease is curable," and that [[ex-gay]] Mormons had emerged from the church's counseling programs cured, although the cure was "like the cure for alcoholism subject to continued vigilance."<ref name=Kimball-1965 /> In 1970, Kimball was involved in creating an LDS publication for church leaders to "assist them to effect a cure and ... become normal again."<ref name=KimballPetersen1970 /> The pamphlet taught that church leaders may assist gay members by reciting scripture; appealing to their reason; encouraging them to abandon gay lovers and associates; praying with them; and encouraging them to replace any sexual expression of their homosexual feelings with heterosexual expressions like opposite-sex dating.<ref name="Hope" />{{rp|2–6}} The pamphlet emphasized that "[h]omosexuality CAN be cured."<ref name="Hope" />{{rp|7}} In 1973 the [[American Psychiatric Association]]’s removed homosexuality from the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]]<ref>{{citation |last= Haldeman |first= Douglas C. |date= April 1994 |title= The practice and ethics of sexual orientation conversion therapy |journal= [[Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology]] |volume= 62 |issue= 2 |pages= 221–227 |doi= 10.1037/0022-006X.62.2.221}}</ref> and in 1990 the [[World Health Organization]] removed homosexuality from the list of disorders classified in the tenth edition of the [[International Classification of Diseases]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cochran|first1=Susan D.|title=Proposed declassification of disease categories related to sexual orientation in the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (ICD-11)|url=http://www.who.int/bulletin/volumes/92/9/14-135541/en/|website=Bulletin of the World Health Organization|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chhiber|first1=Ashley|title=World Health Organization told to declassify sexual orientation as basis of mental disorders|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/07/03/world-health-organization-told-to-declassify-sexual-orientation-as-basis-of-mental-disorders/|accessdate=4 February 2017|agency=Pink News|date=3 July 2014}}</ref>
===As a tendency=== In 1992 the church produced a booklet for leaders entitled ''Understanding and Helping Those With Homosexual Problems'',<ref name="lds92" >{{cite book|title=Understanding and Helping Those Who Have Homosexual Problems|date=1992|publisher=LDS Church|url=http://www.qrd.org/qrd/religion/judeochristian/protestantism/mormon/mormon-homosexuality|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref> which removed all reference to homosexuality as a disease, instead framing it as "sinful behavior" that "should be eliminated" as well as "thoughts and feelings" which "should be overcome." LDS leaders have referenced contemporary scientific research, but have explained that this should not be taken as an official church position on "scientific questions," such as the causes of homosexuality.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" />
===As a confusion of gender=== {{Main|Gender minorities and the LDS church}} On several occasions spanning the 70's to the early 2000's while discussing homosexuality, church leaders have alluded to their belief that the homosexual feeling may stem from a confusion over one's [[gender identity]] or [[gender roles]].<ref name="Lord" />{{rp|341}} Since then the church has acknowledged differences between gender identity and sexual orientation.<ref name="Frequently Asked Questions">{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions|url=https://mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/frequently-asked-questions|website=Mormon and Gay|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 2016}}</ref><ref name="youtube.com">{{cite news|title=Trib Talk: LDS leaders Oaks, Christofferson will appear on Trib Talk to discuss religious freedom|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UIJ6gL_xc-M?t=14m9s|accessdate=21 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="slate.com">{{cite news|last1=Petrey|first1=Taylor G.|title=A Mormon Leader Signals New Openness on Transgender Issues. This Could Be Huge.|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2015/02/13/mormons_and_transgender_elder_dallin_h_oaks_says_the_lds_church_is_open.html|accessdate=21 November 2016|agency=Slate|date=13 February 2015}}</ref>
===Proposed historical tolerance=== Former LDS historian [[D. Michael Quinn]] has suggested that early church leaders had a more tolerant view of homosexuality given that during the 19th century, the Church (like American society as a whole) was relatively tolerant of same-sex [[intimate relationship]]s. However, at the time, many such relationships had no sexual component, and among those that did, the evidence is usually circumstantial.<ref name="Dynamics" /> Quinn also states that several active and prominent members of the church in Utah were not disciplined after publicizing that they were living in romantic relationships with their same-sex domestic partners, although there is no clear evidence these relationships involved sex.<ref name="Dynamics" /> These included [[Evan Stephens]], who had been director of the [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] until 1916 and is the author of numerous standard church hymns, who remained single but had intimate relationships and shared the same bed with a series of male domestic partners and traveling companions.<ref>{{Cite article|last=Quinn|first=D. Michael|author-link=D. Michael Quinn|title=Male-Male Intimacy among Nineteenth-century Mormons—a Case Study|journal=[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]|volume=28|issue=4|pages=105–28|date=Winter 1995|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V28N04_119.pdf}}</ref> Some of these relationships were described under a [[pseudonym]] in ''[[The Children's Friend (LDS magazine)|The Children's Friend]]''.<ref>{{Citation|author=Anonymous|date=October 1919|title=Evan Bach: A True Story for Little Folk, by a Pioneer|periodical=[[The Children's Friend (LDS magazine)|The Children's Friend]]|editor1=[[May Anderson]]|editor2=[[Primary (LDS Church)|Primary Association]]|publisher=The Deseret News|volume=18|page=386|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jSorAAAAYAAJ&dq=editions%3AHARVARD32044100172170&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=evan+bach}}</ref> Also notable were [[Louise B. Felt]] and [[May Anderson]], the church's first two general presidents of the [[Primary (LDS Church)|Primary]], who lived together in the same bedroom for decades and were referred to by Primary leaders as the "[[David and Jonathan]]" of Primary.<ref name="Dynamics" /> Quinn's interpretations of previous leaders' views and the nature of the relationships of Evan Stephens, and Felt and Anderson have been challenged as a distortion of history.<ref name="QuinnResponse" >{{Cite article|last1=James|first1=Rhett S.|author1-link=Rhett S. James|last2=Mitton|first2=George L.|year=1998|title=A Response to D. Michael Quinn's Homosexual Distortion of Latter-day Saint History|periodical=[[FARMS Review of Books]]|volume=10|issue=1|pages=141–263|url=http://maxwellinstitute.byu.edu/publications/review/?vol=10&num=1&id=280}}</ref> [[Kimball Young]] has cited the early church's practice of [[Law of adoption (Mormonism)|sealing men to each other]] as evidence of latent homosexuality.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Ben|date=18 August 2004|title=Same-Sex Temple Sealings: Did the Early LDS Church Embrace Homosexual Relationships?|url=https://issuu.com/qsaltlake/docs/metro1_09/18|journal=Salt Lake Metro|volume=1|issue=9|page=21|pages=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928131756/http://qsaltlake.com/2004/9/feature.shtml|archive-date=28 September 2011|via=}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|136–138}}
==Current theology and policy==
In 1999, [[Gordon B. Hinckley]], president of the church, officially welcomed gay people in the church,<ref name=Why>{{Citation |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |first= Gordon B. |last= Hinckley |title= Why We Do Some of the Things We Do |date= November 1999 |url= http://www.lds.org/ensign/1999/11/why-we-do-some-of-the-things-we-do |quote= Our hearts reach out to those who refer to themselves as gays and lesbians. We love and honor them as sons and daughters of God. They are welcome in the Church.}}</ref> and in an interview affirmed them as "good people": "Now we have gays in the church. Good people. We take no action against such people—provided they don't become involved in transgression, sexual transgression. If they do, we do with them exactly what we'd do with heterosexuals who transgress."<ref name=Lattin1997>{{Citation|last=Lattin |first=Don |title=Musings of the Main Mormon: Gordon B. Hinckley, "president, prophet, seer and revelator: of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, sits at the top of one of the world's fastest-growing religions |date=April 13, 1997 |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/1997/04/13/SC36289.DTL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517004945/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F1997%2F04%2F13%2FSC36289.DTL |archivedate=May 17, 2012 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The church teaches that homosexual problems can be overcome "through faith in God, sincere repentance, and persistent effort."<ref name="lds92" /> "Homosexual relations" is included on the church's list of "serious transgressions" that may result in a [[disciplinary council]] and, if the person does not desist, [[excommunication]].<ref name="LDS Church 1998">{{cite book|title=Church Handbook of Instructions|date=1998|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah}}</ref>{{rp|95}} The church defines "serious transgressions" to include "murder, rape, forcible sexual abuse, spouse abuse, intentional serious physical injury of others, adultery, fornication, homosexual relations (especially sexual cohabitation),<ref>The phrase in parentheses was added in November 2015: Daniel Woodruff, [http://kutv.com/news/local/lds-church-to-exclude-children-of-same-sex-couples-from-membership "LDS church to exclude children of same-sex couples from membership"], kutv.com, 6 November 2015.</ref> deliberate abandonment of family responsibilities, robbery, burglary, theft, embezzlement, sale of illegal drugs, fraud, perjury, and false swearing."<ref name="LDS Church 1998" />
In November 2015, the church clarified that its members who are in a [[same-sex marriage]] are in apostasy and would be subject to church discipline.<ref name="2015developments"/><ref name = 2015policy>Cimaron Neugebauer, [http://kutv.com/news/local/lds-church-issues-update-on-what-is-considered-apostasy "LDS Church adds same-sex marriage to definition of apostasy"], kutv.com, November 6, 2015.</ref> Prior to this, local leadership had more discretion in whether or how far to pursue church disciplinary action for members in same-sex marriages. Local church leaders still have discretion for same-sex couples who are cohabiting but not married. While explicitly including same-sex marriage in the church's definition of apostasy, the November 2015 update also addressed children of same-sex couples. In the updated policy, children living in a same-sex household may not [[Naming and blessing of children|receive a name and a blessing]], nor be baptized until at least 18 years of age, and must disavow same-sex marriage and no longer be living with a parent who is, or has been, in a same-sex relationship.<ref name=Christofferson-explains>{{cite web |last=Walch |first=Tad |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865640934/Elder-Christofferson-explains-updated-LDS-Church-policies-on-same-sex-marriage-and-children.html?pg=all |title=Elder Christofferson explains updated LDS Church policies on same-sex marriage and children |date=November 6, 2015 |work=Deseret News |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name="policy clarification">{{cite news | author=Tad Walch | title=LDS Church provides additional information on handbook policies about same-sex couples and their children | work=Deseret News | date=November 13, 2015 | url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865641430/LDS-Church-provides-additional-information-on-handbook-policies-about-same-sex-couples-and-their.html?pg=all | accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>
===Terminology used by the church=== Although there is no official policy to this effect, some church leaders have stated that "homosexual", "lesbian", and "gay" should be used as adjectives to describe thoughts, feelings, or behaviors, and never as nouns to describe people.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /><ref name="2the1" /><ref name="oaks95" >{{cite web|last1=Oaks|first1=Dallin|title=Same-Gender Attraction|url=https://www.lds.org/ensign/1995/10/same-gender-attraction?lang=eng&_r=1|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 1995}}</ref> Not all leaders adhere to this approach. For example, Hinckley once stated in a public interview that "we have gays in the church."<ref name=Lattin1997 /> Those leaders who adopt this position argue that using these words to denote a person rather than a feeling would imply a person has no choice in regards to their sexual behavior.<ref name="oaks95" /> Church leaders and organizations have made reference to homosexuality as a sexual orientation<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /><ref name="honorcode">{{Citation|author=Church Educational System|author-link=Church Educational System|title=Church Educational System Honor Code|publisher=[[Brigham Young University]]|place=Provo, Utah|url=http://saas.byu.edu/catalog/2011-2012ucat/GeneralInfo/HonorCode.php|year=2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822023539/http://saas.byu.edu/catalog/2011-2012ucat/GeneralInfo/HonorCode.php|archivedate=August 22, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and have only begun directly addressing [[bisexuality|bisexual]] members since October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Same-Sex Attraction|url=https://www.lds.org/topics/same-sex-attraction?lang=eng|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026171626/https://www.lds.org/topics/same-sex-attraction?lang=eng|archive-date=October 26, 2016|website=lds.org/topics|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=11 June 2017|deadurl=yes|df=mdy-all}} Compare to the archived page from the previous month .</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Sexual Orientation|url=https://mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/about-sexual-orientation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025174921/https://mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/about-sexual-orientation|archive-date=2016-10-25|website=mormonandgay.lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 2016}} Compare to an archive of the original version of this website from a few days before [https://web.archive.org/web/20161022053954/http://mormonsandgays.org/ here].</ref> According to [[apostle (Latter Day Saints)|apostle]] [[Dallin H. Oaks]], church references condemning homosexuality are to be interpreted as a condemnation of sexual behavior, not of the people who have certain sexual feelings.<ref name=Oaks-1984>{{citation|last=Oaks|first=Dallin|title=Principles to govern possible public statement on legislation affecting rights of homosexuals|date=August 7, 1984|quote=Thus, the First Presidency's letters condemning homosexuality are, by their explicit terms, directed at the practices of homosexuality.}} Reprinted at [https://web.archive.org/web/20131126062717/http://affirmation.org:80/pdf/oaks_paper_02.pdf affirmation.org] and quoted at [https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030629/https://illinoislawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Eskridge.pdf illinoislawreview.org].</ref>
"Homosexual problems", according to popular church vernacular, are defined as "homoerotic thoughts, feelings, or behaviors."<ref name="lds92" /> In describing people with homosexual feelings, the church and its members will often refer to [[Same-sex attraction|"same-gender attractions"]]. This is used in contrast to people who have problems with opposite-gender attraction.<ref>{{cite interview|last=Nelson|first=Russell M.|subjectlink=Russell M. Nelson|last2=Wickman|first2=Lance B.|subjectlink2=Lance B. Wickman|interviewer=Robert Ruby|title=In Focus: Mormonism in Modern America|url=http://pewforum.org/events/?EventID=143|type=Interview: Transcript|work=[[Pew Research Center|Pew Forum on Religion & Public Life]]|date=May 16, 2007|quote=Some have challenges with same-sex attraction, some have problems with opposite-gender attraction that have to be controlled.}}</ref> "Marriage" is defined by the church as being between a man and a woman. To many in the church, same-sex marriages are not considered a legitimate form of marriage, and the church supports the notion of an amendment to the U.S. Constitution to define marriage as being between a man and a woman.<ref name="LDS Church 2004" >{{cite news|title=First Presidency Statement on Same-Gender Marriage|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/first-presidency-statement-on-same-gender-marriage|accessdate=January 23, 2015|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 20, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Jarvik|first=Elaine|date=May 27, 2006|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/635210773/LDS-to-push-marriage-amendment.html|title=LDS to push marriage amendment|newspaper=Deseret Morning News}}</ref>
[[File:Ary Scheffer - The Temptation of Christ (1854).jpg|thumb|left|150px|The church uses the example of [[Jesus Christ]] being tempted as an example of how homosexuals can avoid sin.]]
===Homosexual inclinations===
The church does not condemn what it calls "susceptibilities," "inclinations", or "temptations" of any type that are not acted upon, pointing to the example of the [[temptation of Christ]].<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> Members with homosexual "inclinations" can participate as all other members of the church<ref name="hinckley98" /> and if they remain celibate or heterosexually married, they can participate in the religion to the same extent as straight members. Heterosexual marriage is considered a sacred covenant which should generally not be pursued if homosexual feelings are not under control.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> Those with same-gender attractions are encouraged to talk to their ecclesiastical leader.<ref name="SbT:Chastity">{{citation|title=Gospel Topics: Chastity|url=//www.lds.org/topics/chastity?lang=eng|work=lds.org|publisher=[[LDS Church]]|accessdate=July 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name="FSY">{{cite book|title=For the Strength of Youth |publisher=LDS Church |location=Salt Lake City, Utah |page=36 |edition=9 |url=https://www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/english/pdf/ForTheStrengthOfYouth-eng.pdf?lang=eng |year=2011}}</ref> They are encouraged not to let their sexual feelings be the sole defining factor in their lives, but to see the whole person, extending their horizons beyond their sexual orientation.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> They are advised that they should be careful not to blame their parents.
However, church leaders recognize the loneliness and difficulty that those with homosexual inclinations may have and encourage other members to reach out to them.<ref name="LDS Church 2004" /><ref name="Reverance" /> Oaks has said, “All should understand that persons (and their family members) struggling with the burden of same-sex attraction are in special need of the love and encouragement that is a clear responsibility of church members, who have signified by covenant their willingness to bear one another's burden and so fulfill the law of Christ.<ref name="oaks95" />
The church does not participate in debate on whether homosexual susceptibilities develop from "nature" or "nurture", suggesting that such debates are better left to science.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> Oaks has admitted that "perhaps such susceptibilities are inborn or acquired without personal choice" and "may have some relationship to inheritance," citing some scientific research.<ref name="oaks95" /> However, the church teaches that these inclinations will not continue beyond death<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> and that gender and gender roles are an eternal and essential characteristic of a soul.<ref name="Proclamation">{{citation |url= http://www.lds.org/family/proclamation |title= The Family: A Proclamation to the World |year= 1995 |publisher= LDS Church }}</ref>
=== Homosexual thoughts === The church teaches that all members should take responsibility in bridling their thoughts, attitudes, feelings, desires, and passions. All members are taught to avoid any talk or activity that may arouse immoral sexual feelings.<ref name="SbT:Chastity" /> Members are taught to "let virtue garnish [their] thoughts unceasingly."<ref>{{lds|Doctrine and Covenants|dc|121|45}}</ref> Apostle [[Richard G. Scott]] has taught that through the [[atonement of Jesus Christ]], all desire to sin can be changed and individuals can experience lasting peace.<ref>{{citation |last= Scott |first= Richard G. |author-link= Richard G. Scott |url= http://www.lds.org/ensign/2006/11/the-atonement-can-secure-your-peace-and-happiness |title= The Atonement Can Secure Your Peace and Happiness |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= November 2006}}</ref>
For those with same-gender attractions, church leaders counsel that "the line of prudence is between the susceptibility and the feelings."<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> The church teaches that everyone has feelings they did not choose,<ref name="oaks95" /> and homosexual feelings can be powerful and difficult to control<ref name="hinckley98" /> but "regardless of the causes, these problems can be controlled and eventually overcome."<ref name="lds92" /> Even though there is no church discipline for homosexual thoughts or feelings,<ref name="oaks95" /> the church teaches they should learn to accept responsibility for homosexual feelings<ref name="lds92" /> and cite examples of how those born with inclinations to alcoholism, anger, or other undesirable traits have been able to control their thoughts and actions.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> With better understanding of moral law, they teach these problems will be able to be fixed "routinely."<ref name="2the1" />
The church teaches that members should not indulge in activities that will intensify homosexual feelings, such as viewing pornography, masturbating, or participating in homosexual behavior.<ref name="lds92" /><ref name="Miracle">{{Citation|last=Kimball|first=Spencer W.|author-link=Spencer W. Kimball|title=[[The Miracle of Forgiveness]]|year=1969|publisher=[[Bookcraft]]|isbn=978-0-88494-192-7}}</ref><ref name="TYMO" /> "Unhealthy" relationships, such as those with people that encourage homosexual behavior, should be cut off, and the very appearance of evil should be avoided.<ref name="lds92" /><ref name="2the1" /> [[Bishop (Latter Day Saints)|Bishops]] of the church are counseled to be careful to avoid creating circumstances in which those with homosexual problems are exposed to temptations.<ref name="lds92" />
===Homosexual behavior=== {{multiple image | align = vertical | total_width = 200 | width1 = 683 | height1 = 754 | image1 = Female homosexuality symbol.svg | width2 = 696 | height2 = 605 | image2 = Male homosexuality symbol.svg | footer = Symbols for female and male homosexuality }} In 1991, the church issued a statement that read:<blockquote> Sexual relations are proper only between husband and wife appropriately expressed within the bonds of marriage. Any other sexual contact, including fornication, adultery, and homosexual and lesbian behavior is sinful .... We plead with those involved in such behavior to forsake it.<ref name="lds92" /></blockquote>
The church has also taught that homosexual behavior distorts loving relationships,<ref name="SbT:Chastity" /> undermines the divinely created institution of the family<ref name="LDS Church 2004" /> and can become an addiction.<ref name="2the1" /> Church discipline for homosexual activity is similar to that for members involved in heterosexual activity. For example, pre-marital sex of either kind may permanently bar a person from serving as a church [[Mormon missionary|missionary]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher |first=Peggy |url=http://www.sltrib.com/ci_2890646 |title=Utah Local News - Salt Lake City News, Sports, Archive - The Salt Lake Tribune |publisher=Sltrib.com |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>
The church teaches that homosexual behavior has always been a grievous sin.<ref name="Reverance" /> In 1976, apostle [[Boyd K. Packer]] taught: <blockquote> There is a falsehood that some are born with an attraction to their own kind, with nothing they can do about it. They are just "that way" and can only yield to those desires. It is a malicious and destructive lie. While it is a convincing idea to some, it is of the devil. No one is locked into that kind of life ... Boys are to become men—masculine, manly men—ultimately to become husbands and fathers.<ref name="TYMO" /> </blockquote>
Although church leaders condemn the sin of homosexual behavior, they teach love for the men and women who experience homosexual attraction, including for those who pursue some form of homosexual lifestyle: "We should reach out with kindness and comfort to the afflicted, ministering to their needs and assisting them with their problems."<ref name="Reverance" /> Church leaders have spoken out against "[[gay-bashing]]" and other physical or verbal attacks on those involved in homosexual behavior.<ref name="oaks95" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Church Responds to HRC Petition: Statement on Same-Sex Attraction|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-mormon-responds-to-human-rights-campaign-petition-same-sex-attraction|accessdate=January 23, 2015|date=October 12, 2010|publisher=LDS Church|quote=Sexual activity should only occur between a man and a woman who are married. However, that should never be used as justification for unkindness}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Oaks|first1=Dallin H.|last2=D. Todd|first2=D. Todd Christofferson|title=Love One Another: A Discussion on Same-Sex Attraction|url=http://mormonsandgays.org/|website=mormonsandgays.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=January 23, 2015}}</ref>
Church president [[Spencer W. Kimball]] stated that he finds it hard to believe that one would choose to be homosexual by a conscious decision; instead, he suggested that it might be a spiritual disorder—with its roots in selfishness—resulting in feelings that must be overcome or suppressed.<ref name="2the1" /> Kimball emphasized that the behavior is changeable,<ref name="2the1" /> and if not repented of, may result in church discipline including excommunication under the direction of the bishop.<ref name="lds92" /> Kimball maintained that the cure comes through following the basic rules for moral and spiritual health for a long period of time with undeviating determination.<ref name="2the1" />
===Homosexuality after death=== On several occasions from 2006–2009 multiple top leaders taught that attractions to those of the same sex won't exist after death, stating "it must be true"<ref name="Hafen Speaks">{{cite web|title=Elder Bruce C. Hafen Speaks on Same-Sex Attraction|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/elder-bruce-c-hafen-speaks-on-same-sex-attraction|website=Mormon Newsroom|date=19 September 2009}}</ref> that "gay or lesbian inclinations" will "not exist post-mortality",<ref name="pbs.org">{{cite web|title=The Mormons: Jeffrey Holland Interview|url=https://www.pbs.org/mormons/interviews/holland.html|website=pbs.org|publisher=PBS|date=4 March 2006}}</ref> but only occur "right now in mortality."<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> The 2007 official church publication "[[God Loveth His Children]] states that, "others may not be free of this challenge [of same-gender attraction] in this life" but that "our bodies, feelings, and desires will be perfected in the next life so that every one of God’s children may find joy in a family."<ref name="Women"/>{{rp|46}}<ref name="God Loveth"/>{{rp|4}}<ref name="Universe Timeline" />
==Treatment and views of LGBT people== The church has occasionally addressed the treatment and views of LGBT+ members. In 2000 the apostle Packer addressed gay and lesbian youth stating that church leaders don't reject, but rather them, and that they sometimes must extend tough love through teaching and discipline.<ref>{{citation |last= Packer |first= Boyd K. |author-link= Boyd K. Packer |title= Ye Are the Temple of God |url= http://www.lds.org/ensign/2000/11/ye-are-the-temple-of-god |journal= Ensign |date= November 2000 |publisher= LDS Church}}</ref> Additionally, the 2007 church pamphlet "[[God Loveth His Children]]" acknowledged that some gay members have felt rejection by other members. It criticized those who did not show love and challenged gay members to show love and kindness to help other members change their attitudes.<ref name="God Loveth" />
There are many current and former members of the LDS church who are attracted to people of the same sex, and they have had a variety of positive and negative experiences with leaders and other members. For example, one gay Mormon man who dates men reported never having problems with his local leaders, while another who was a Church employee described how his stake president denied his temple recommend resulting in him getting fired simply because of his friendship with other gay men and his involvement in a charity bingo for [[Utah Pride Center|Utah Pride]] in a 2011 article.<ref name="Living gay in the Mormon Church">{{cite news|last1=Bracken|first1=Seth|title=Living gay in the Mormon Church|url=http://gaysaltlake.com/news/2011/04/14/living-gay-in-the-church/|agency=Q Salt Lake|date=14 April 2011}}</ref> One former LDS bishop and temple sealer [[Antonio A. Feliz]] said that his Peruvian mission was directed in the early 1960s<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8dlXAAAAYAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=knew+to+be+homosexual|title=Out of the Bishop's Closet: A Call to Heal Ourselves, Each Other, and Our World|last1=Feliz|first1=Antonio A.|date=11 April 2011|publisher=Alamo Square Press|year=|isbn=9780962475177|edition=2|location=|page=24|pages=}}</ref> by South American area authorities to not teach known homosexuals.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bouldrey|first1=Brian|title=Wrestling with the Angel: Faith and Religion in the Lives of Gay Men|date=1 May 1996|publisher=Riverhead Trade|isbn=1573225452|page=298|edition=Reprint|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Wrestling_with_the_Angel.html?id=wqGLGQAACAAJ}}</ref> A 1997 poll at BYU found that 1/3 of male students would avoid befriending a gay student and 42% of all students believed that even celibate, honor-code-following gay members should not be allowed to attend BYU.<ref name="Clayton" /><ref name="Ban">{{cite news|last1=Smart|first1=Michael|title=BYU Student Poll: Ban Gay Students|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/288698514/5E2B8153F7E84354PQ/1?accountid=4488|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=22 March 1997|via=ProQuest Newsstand|quote=As part of a project for their English class, Sam Clayton, Dale Franklin and Melanie Dinger conducted the school-approved survey to 420 students in randomly selected classes on campus. ... [Clayton] feels the results show a substantial amount of intolerance and prejudice among students towards same-sex oriented people. Clayton, who says he is gay, points to the 42 percent of students who are ignorant of or opposed to the school's policy. He also said that while 91 percent of those surveyed said they were familiar with the church's stance, only a third actually were.}}</ref> Several church employees have been fired<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fruhwirth|first1=Jesse|title=Man Fired from LDS Church For Refusing to Give Up Gay Friends|url=https://www.cityweekly.net/utah/man-fired-from-lds-church-for-refusing-to-give-up-gay-friends/Content?oid=2153419|work=Salt Lake City Weekly|date=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name="Celibate">{{cite news|last1=Shire|first1=Emily|title=Mormon U. Forces Gays to Be Celibate|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/mormon-u-forces-gays-to-be-celibate|accessdate=20 June 2017|work=The Daily Beast|date=13 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Openly gay BYU producer, filmmaker fired|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=52947893&itype=CMSID|accessdate=10 August 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=19 November 2011}}</ref> or pressured to leave for being celibate but gay,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haddock|first1=Sharon M.|title=Homosexual Professor Planning to Leave BYU|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/444030/HOMOSEXUAL-PROFESSOR-PLANNING-TO-LEAVE-BYU.html|work=Deseret News|publisher=LDS Church|date=10 October 1995}}</ref><ref name="Lord">{{cite book|last1=Waterman|first1=Bryan|last2=Kagel|first2=Brian|title=The Lord’s University: Freedom and Authority at BYU|date=1998|publisher=Signature books|isbn=1-56085-117-1|url=http://signaturebookslibrary.org/the-lords-university/}}</ref>{{rp|162–163}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gay Professor Leaves University|journal=Sunstone Magazine|date=December 1996|page=74|url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/pdf/104-67-77.pdf#page=8}}</ref> or for supporting LGBT rights.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hollingshead|first1=Todd|title=BYU fires teacher over op-ed stance|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3934360&itype=NGPSID|accessdate=11 August 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=14 June 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Samantha|title=Mormon university instructor fired after Facebook post supporting LGBT rights, she says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/07/19/mormon-university-instructor-fired-after-facebook-post-supporting-lgbt-rights-she-says/|accessdate=19 July 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=19 July 2017}}</ref> In a 2007 US poll, 24% of Mormons agreed that "homosexuality is a way of life that should be accepted," less than any other major religious group in the survey except for Jehovah's Witnesses.<ref>{{cite book|title=U.S.Religious Landscape Survey: Religious Beliefs and Practices: Diverse and Politically Relevant|date=June 2008|publisher=Pew Forum on Religion & Public Life|page=92|url=http://assets.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/11/2008/06/report2-religious-landscape-study-full.pdf|quote=Three-quarters of Jehovah’s Witnesses (76%), about six-in-ten Muslims (61%) and roughly two-thirds of Mormons (68%) and members of evangelical churches (64%) say homosexuality ought to be discouraged.}} Data also shown [http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/mormon/#views-about-homosexuality here].</ref> In a similar poll seven years later, 36% said homosexuality should be accepted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Views about homosexuality|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/views-about-homosexuality/#religious-tradition-trend|website=pewforum.org|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=2014}}</ref>
==Views on gender diversity and identity== {{Main|Gender minorities and the LDS church}}
Expressions and [[Gender identity|identities]] for sexuality and gender are "separate, but related" aspects of a person<ref>{{cite web|title=Resolution on Gender and Sexual Orientation Diversity in Children and Adolescents in Schools|url=http://www.apa.org/about/policy/orientation-diversity.aspx|website=American Psychological Association|publisher=APA|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> and stem from similar biological origins.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bao|first1=Ai-Min|last2=Swaab|first2=Dick F.|title=Sexual differentiation of the human brain: Relation to gender identity, sexual orientation and neuropsychiatric disorders|journal=Frontiers in Neuroendocrinology|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0091302211000252|date=April 2011|volume=32|issue=2|pages=214–226|accessdate=9 December 2016|doi=10.1016/j.yfrne.2011.02.007}}</ref> In relation to [[transgender]] and other [[Genderqueer|gender diverse]] individuals church spokesman Eric Hawkins stated in March 2016 that LDS bishops recognize that "each case is different" and "difficult and sensitive" and that they recognize the "emotional pain" many gender minorities feel. He also reaffirmed the church's views that "gender is part of our eternal God-given identity and purpose" and stated that the Church does not baptize "those who are planning trans-sexual operations" and that undergoing a "trans-sexual operation" may imperil the membership of a church member.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Samantha|title=Mormon Man Risks Excommunication By Sharing His Transition|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/03/16/mormon-man-risks-excommunication-by-sharing-his-transition.html|accessdate=9 December 2016|agency=The Daily Beast|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="Guardian">{{cite journal|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|title=Transgender and Mormon: keeping the faith while asking the church to change|journal=The Guardian|date=28 March 2016|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/28/transgender-mormon-lgbt-rights-emmett-claren|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>
According to current church policy, members who have undergone an “elective transsexual operation” are banned from temple rites or receiving priesthood authority. Additionally, a trangender individual who has undergone [[sex reassignment surgery|gender-confirming surgery]] may be baptized only with First Presidency approval, and those considering it are barred from baptism.<ref name="slate.com" /> The church has acknowledged differences between gender identity and sexual orientation stating that they have "unfinished business in teaching on [transgender situations]."<ref name="youtube.com"/><ref name="slate.com"/> The official website on homosexuality states that "same-sex attraction and [[gender dysphoria]] are very different ... those who experience gender dysphoria may or may not also experience same-sex attraction, and the majority of those who experience same-sex attraction do not desire to change their gender. From a psychological and ministerial perspective, the two are different."<ref name="Frequently Asked Questions"/>
==Criticism and controversies== {{main|Criticism of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints}}
The church's policies and treatment of LGBT people has long been a source of controversy both inside and outside the church<ref name="archive.sltrib.com"/><ref name="A Survey of LGBT Americans">{{cite web|title=A Survey of LGBT Americans|url=http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/2013/06/13/a-survey-of-lgbt-americans/|website=Pew Social Trends|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> and a significant cause of disagreement and disaffection by members.<ref name="Religion News Foundation">{{cite news|last1=Riess|first1=Jana|title=Are Mormons in their 20s and 30s leaving the LDS Church?|url=http://religionnews.com/2016/04/14/mormons-20s-30s-leaving-lds-church/|agency=Religion News Service|publisher=Religion News Foundation|date=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="washingtonpost.com">{{cite news|last1=Moyer|first1=Justin|title=1,500 Mormons quit church over new anti-gay-marriage policy, organizer says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/11/16/organizer-at-mass-resignation-event-1500-mormons-quit-church-over-new-anti-gay-policy/|accessdate=19 November 2016|agency=The Washington Post|date=16 November 2015}}</ref><ref name="theguardian.com"/>
===Among members=== A 2011 online survey of over 3,000 individuals who no longer believe church truth claims found that around ten percent would consider returning if (among several changes) LGBT persons were accepted and treated equally.<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding Mormon Disbelief|url=http://www.whymormonsquestion.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Survey-Results_Understanding-Mormon-Disbelief-Mar20121.pdf|website=whymormonsquestion.org|publisher=Open Stories Foundation}}</ref>
===Among the public=== The controversial policies for LGBT persons has made an impression on the general public. A 2003 nationwide [[Pew Research Center]] survey of over 1,000 LGBT Americans found that 83% of them said the LDS church was "generally unfriendly towards lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender people" surpassed only by "the Muslim religion" at 84%.<ref name="A Survey of LGBT Americans"/> Additionally, in May 2008 a [[Georgia Tech]] gay-rights manual referred to the LDS Church as "anti-gay." After two students sued the school for discrimination, a judge ordered that the material be removed.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.wctv.tv/news/APNews/headlines/18465389.html |title= Judge Rules Georgia Tech Gay Rights Manual Biased |agency= Associated Press |publisher= [[WCTV]] |date= May 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Court: Georgia Tech "Safe Space" program not safe from Constitution|url=https://www.adflegal.org/detailspages/press-release-details/court---georgia-tech--safe-space--program-not-safe-from-constitution|date=May 1, 2008|publisher=[[Alliance Defense Fund]]}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Judge Rules Bias in University’s Manual on Gay Tolerance|archive-date=3 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215200/http://www.wctv.tv/news/APNews/headlines/18465389.html|url=https://www.ue.org/inactivepages/liability-alerts/08-08-05/Judge_Rules_Bias_in_University%E2%80%99s_Manual_on_Gay_Tolerance.aspx|work=Liability Alerts|publisher=United Educators}}</ref>
===Teachings on homosexuality changeability and origins=== Past leaders' teachings on reparative therapy and the origins of homosexuality have been criticized. In the late 90s psychiatrist Jeffery R. Jensen, a University of Utah almnus,<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Jeffery Jensen MD|url=https://health.usnews.com/doctors/jeffery-jensen-465921|website=health.usnews.com|publisher=U.S. News & World Report L.P.}}</ref> criticized church reparative therapy modalities and etiological theories around homosexuality in multiple presentations as lacking scientific integrity as he believed they were dictated from top church leaders rather than drawn from actual empirical observation by trained professionals. He also stated that current church publications on the subject were condescending, dehumanizing pontifications using caricatures and stereotypes of gay men and lesbians to distort knowledge and facts in order to justify oppressive standards and norms. He continued asserting that "far too many of our lesbian and gay youths kill themselves because of what you say about them" since gay men and lesbians cannot be made heterosexual, and "those who believe your false promises and remain celibate in the hopes of eventual 'cure' are consigned to a misery."<ref name="Heterosexualization">{{cite speech |last=Jensen |first=Jeffrey R. |title=We See What We Believe: The Heterosexualization of Gay Men and Lesbians in the LDS Church |event=Sunstone Symposium |date=1997 |location=Washington D.C. |publisher=Sunstone Education Foundation, Inc. |url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/we-see-what-we-believe-the-heterosexualization-of-gay-men-and-lesbians-in-the-lds-church/ }} Transcript available [https://web.archive.org/web/20071005211209/http://www.lds-mormon.com:80/wswwb.shtml here].</ref><ref name="Psychiatrist">{{cite speech |last=Jensen |first=Jeffrey R. |title=Homosexuality: A Psychiatrist's Response to LDS Social Services |event=Sunstone Symposium |date=1996 |publisher=Sunstone Education Foundation, Inc. |url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/homosexuality-a-psychiatrists-response-to-lds-social-services-and-the-biological-basis-of-sexual-orientation/ }} Transcript at [https://web.archive.org/web/20060109013306/http://www.affirmation.org:80/learning/homosexuality_a_psychiatrists_response.asp affirmation.org].</ref> Soon after, The American Psychiatric Association disavowed therapy trying to change sexual orientation as ineffective and destructive.<ref name="Rebukes">{{cite web|title=American Psychiatric Association Rebukes Reparative Therapy|url=https://sciencesources.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/1998-12/APA-APAR-141298.php|website=sciencesources.eurekalert.org|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS)|date=14 December 1998}}</ref>
===Packer's address=== [[File:ToYoungMenOnly.png|thumb|right|150px|Packer's conference address published here has been criticized of condoning anti-gay violence.<ref name="Multiply">{{cite book|last1=Corcoran|first1=Brent|last2=O'Donovan|first2=Rocky|title=Multiply and Replenish: Mormon Essays on Sex and Family|date=1994|publisher=Signature Books|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=1560850507|url=http://signaturebookslibrary.org/the-abominable-and-detestable-crime-against-nature/|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref>{{rp|150}}<ref name="Criticism" >Hilary Groutage Smith, "Mormon Pamphlets on Gays Criticized", ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]'', 2000-08-06, p. B2</ref><ref name="BYU Dismissal" />]] One general conference address later distributed as a pamphlet that generated controversy was [[Boyd K. Packer|Packer's]] "[[To Young Men Only]]" which condones an example of a male [[Mormon missionary|missionary]] who punched his missionary companion for making romantic advances with Packer stating, "Well, thanks. Somebody had to do it ...."<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Message to Young Men (To Young Men Only) |url=https://www.lds.org/general-conference/1976/10/media/session_5_talk_1/2680671857001?lang=eng |website=lds.org |publisher=LDS Church |date=2 October 1976 |time=10:30}} Alternative [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8JBCOqlcH0U&t=11m6s youtube.com] link.</ref><ref name=TYMO>{{citation|last=Packer |first=Boyd K. |authorlink=Boyd K. Packer |title=To Young Men Only |year=1976 |publisher=LDS Church |url=https://www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/english/pdf/language-materials/33382_eng.pdf |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311171249/https://www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/english/pdf/language-materials/33382_eng.pdf |archivedate=March 11, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Historians Michael Quinn and Rocky O'Donovan have argued these comments "essentially advocated [[gay bashing|anti-Gay violence]]",<ref name="Multiply" /> and that the church itself endorsed such behavior by continuing to publish Packer's speech in pamphlet form.<ref name="Prelude" />{{rp|38–39}} Former bishop David Hardy also condemned this pamphlet and other publications as promoting violence against gay people and providing outdated misinformation on the nature of his once-suicidal gay son.<ref name="Criticism" /><ref name="BYU Dismissal">{{cite news|last1=Hardy|first1=David E.|title=BYU's Dismissal of Gay Students Continues Confusion for Gays, Parents|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=15 April 2001|page=AA3}} Reprinted [here http://www.lds-mormon.com/hardy1.shtml]</ref> In 1995, Oaks said, "Our doctrines obviously condemn those who engage in so-called 'gay bashing'—physical or verbal attacks on persons thought to be involved in homosexual or lesbian behavior"<ref name="oaks95" /> and in 2016, the church ceased publication of the pamphlet and it was removed from the church's website.<ref name = 2016retired/>
===Protests=== The policies and treatment of LGBTQ individuals have prompted several protests and mass resignations including the following: * '''2 November 2008''' – Hundreds of people gathered at the Salt Lake City library in a protest of Prop 8 organized by LDS mothers of gay children.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rally against Prop. 8 held in Salt Lake |url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=4689399 |work=KSL |publisher=LDS Church |date=2 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LDS Moms Hold Anti-Prop 8 Vigil |url=https://qsaltlake.com/news/2008/11/03/lds-moms-hold-anti-prop-8-vigil/ |work=QSaltLake |date=3 November 2008}}</ref> * '''6 November 2008''' – In Los Angeles over two thousand people protested at the LDS temple over the LDS church's heavy involvement in the recent passing of California's [[Prop 8]] banning same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gay marriage supporters take to California streets|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/11/08/same.sex.protests/index.html?_s=PM:US|agency=CNN|date=8 Nov 2008}}</ref> * '''7 November 2008''' – Three days after Prop 8 passed nearly five thousand protesters gathered at the [[Salt Lake Temple]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands of Prop. 8 opponents protest LDS Church at Temple Square|url=http://www.ksl.com/?nid=148&sid=4728411|agency=KSL|date=7 Nov 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bates|first1=Karen Grigsby|title=Gay-Marriage Ban Protesters Target Mormon Church|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=96756702|agency=NPR|date=7 Nov 2008}}</ref> That evening a candlelight vigil by about 600 mothers of LGBT children was also held at the Salt Lake Temple.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eskridge Jr.|first1=William N.|title=Latter-Day Constitutionalism: Sexuality, Gender, and Mormons|journal=Illinois Law Review|date=Sep 2016|volume=4|page=1269|url=https://illinoislawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Eskridge.pdf#page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= LDS moms hold vigil against Prop. 8 |first= Budy |last= Blankenfeld |publisher= ABC4 |url= http://www.abc4.com/content/news/top%20stories/story/LDS-moms-hold-vigil-against-Prop-8/E81cQC526UaEWdX1G9N40A.cspx |accessdate= 2008-12-24 |date= 2008-11-02 }}</ref> * '''7 October 2010''' – Thousands of individuals surrounded [[Temple Square]] in protest of Boyd Packer's "Cleansing the Inner Vessel" conference address in which he characterized same-sex physical attractions as impure and unnatural tendencies that could be overcome.<ref name="archive.sltrib.com"/><ref name="deseretnews.com">{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Scott|title=2,000-3,000 protest for gay rights outside Mormon church offices in Salt Lake City|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700071914/2000-3000-protest-for-gay-rights-outside-Mormon-church-offices-in-Salt-Lake-City.html?pg=all|accessdate=16 November 2016|agency=Deseret News}}</ref> * '''14 November 2015''' – In response to a policy change on members in same-sex marriages and their children, 1,500 members gathered across from the church's offices to submit their resignation letters,<ref name="washingtonpost.com"/><ref name="nytimes.com">{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Jack|title=Mormon Resignations Put Support for Gays Over Fealty to Faith|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/16/us/mormon-resignations-put-support-for-gays-over-fealty-to-faith.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&clickSource=story-heading&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news&_r=0|accessdate=19 November 2016|agency=The New York Times|date=15 November 2016}}</ref> with thousands more resigning online in the weeks after.<ref name="good4utah.com">{{cite news|last1=Vazquez|first1=Aldo|title=Thousands file resignation letters from the LDS Church|url=http://www.good4utah.com/news/local-news/thousands-file-resignation-letters-from-the-lds-church|accessdate=11 December 2016|agency=ABC 4 Utah KTVX|date=14 November 2015}}</ref><ref name="theguardian.com"/> In early November, top church leaders updated the [[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]] banning a "child of a parent living in a same-gender relationship" from [[Naming and blessing of children|baby blessings]], [[Baptism in Mormonism|baptism]], [[Confirmation (Latter Day Saints)|confirmation]], [[Priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood ordination]], and [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary service]] until the child had moved out, was "of legal age", "disavow[ed] the practice of same-gender cohabitation and marriage", and received approval from the Office of the First Presidency. The policy update also added entering a same-sex marriage as a type of "apostasy" mandating a [[disciplinary council]].<ref name="ReferenceC">{{cite news|last1=Shill|first1=Aaron|title=LDS Church reaffirms doctrine of marriage, updates policies on families in same-sex marriages|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865640835/Church-updates-policies-on-families-in-same-sex-marriages.html?pg=all|accessdate=12 November 2016|agency=Deseret News|date=5 Nov 2015}}</ref><ref name="The Washington Post"/> However, according to a November 2016 study, the vast majority of active members supported the new policy on same-sex parents and their children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Riess|first1=Jana|title=Commentary: Most U.S. Mormons approve of church's policy on gay couples, study shows|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/4532402-155/commentary-most-us-mormons-approve-of|accessdate=19 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=1 November 2016}}</ref>
==Mixed-orientation marriage== {{further|Mixed-orientation marriage}} [[File:Weddingring-JH.jpg|thumb|right|LDS leaders have stated that opposite-sex marriage should not be viewed as a therapeutic step for members physically attracted to those of the same sex.<ref name="solution" /><ref name="marriage" />]] Many gay and lesbian members of the LDS Church have felt that they should get marry someone of the opposite sex because of the church's emphasis on [[Marriage in The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|marriage]]. [[Evergreen International|Evergreen]] director David Pruden was quoted as stating in 2002 that 40% of the approximately 150 callers requesting help each month on their hotline were Mormon men married to women, and distressed about their homosexual attractions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schow |first1=Ron |title=Homosexual Attraction and LDS Marriage Decision |journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought |date=Fall 2005 |volume=38 |issue=3 |page=133 |url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V38N03_145.pdf |quote=The extent of the problem is seen in the fact that Evergreen receives over 150 requests for help each month from those with homosexual attractions; 40 percent of these requests come from men who are married. Only 10 percent of the calls come from women. The remaining 50 percent are from single men. This pattern indicates a great deal of social pressure on LDS men with homosexual attractions to marry heterosexually, with unfortunate outcomes for many of them and their spouses and children.}}</ref> Additionally, a 2004 publication quoted LDS Family Services statistics which showed that about half of the approximately 400 gay Mormon men they had seen as clients for over a year during the past 30 years were married, though only half of those were able to stay married.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schow |first1=Ron |title=Homosexual Attraction and LDS Marriage Decision |journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought |date=Fall 2005 |volume=38 |issue=3 |page=135 |url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V38N03_145.pdf |quote=An LDS Family Services therapist who spoke to us about his clinical experience likely has had the most extensive experience in working with single and married homosexual Latter-day Saint men—approximately eight hundred men in more than thirty years. Approximately half of these clients left counseling after one or two sessions; the other half, who were in therapy for one to three years, include roughly two hundred single men and two hundred married men. Among the two hundred single men, only 10 percent were able to marry. Almost all of them (nineteen of twenty) identified themselves as bisexual. Of the two hundred married males (a large portion of whom, it is probably safe to speculate, were likely bisexual), only half were able to stay in their marriages, although there is no information as to what kinds of accommodations they had to make to do so, nor how many of these marriages will ultimately endure.}} A copy of ''The Persistence of Same Sex Attraction in Latter-day Saints Who Undergo Counseling or Change Therapy'' (2004) can be found [https://web.archive.org/web/20111211020508/http://www.ldsresources.info:80/professionals/persistence.shtml here].</ref>
The church teaches that heterosexual marriage is one of several requirements for afterlife entry into the "[[exaltation (Latter Day Saints)|highest degree of glory]]" in the [[celestial kingdom]]. Church leaders previously encouraged this with one former church employee stating in 1986 that he had experienced pressure to marry at the age of 24 in the belief that it would change his homosexual feelings later resulting in a divorce.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lindsey|first1=Robert|title=Utah Now Facing Problem of AIDS: Disease Is Occurring Despite Strict Mormon Teachings About Sexual Conduct|work=The New York Times|date=30 October 1986|page=A19|quote='A lot of men are forced to marry, and they play around on the side,' said Davyd Daniels, a former Mormon ... William Blevins, 40, a former librarian at the Mormon Church's genealogical center, said the church put pressure on him to marry at 24 in belief 'it would cure me' of homosexual leanings. It did not, he said, adding that 'I still had my feelings' and that after he fathered four children the church discharged him, then excommunicated him and forced him to disclose the identities of several other employees at the church's headquarters with whom he had had sexual relations. He said his wife left him and remarried and he no longer has custody of the children.}}</ref> Leaders have stated that those who do not have an opportunity to be married in this life have been promised that they will have an opportunity to do so in the afterlife<ref>{{citation|title=none|first=Lorenzo|last=Snow|author-link=Lorenzo Snow|newspaper=[[Millennial Star]]|date=August 31, 1899|page=547}}</ref><ref>{{citation|first=Dallin H.|last=Oaks|author-link=Dallin H. Oaks|title=Pure in Heart|location=Salt Lake City|publisher=Bookcraft|year=1988|pages=61–62|isbn=978-0-88494-650-2}}</ref><ref name="oaks95" /> Leaders have said that homosexual attractions will not continue past death, and that if the individual is faithful in this life, they will receive every blessing in the eternities, including [[Celestial marriage|eternal marriage]].<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" />
The most recent statement by a general church leader as of 2015 was when the apostle Oaks stated that leaders "definitely do not recommend marriage as a solution for same-gender feelings. No, it’s not a therapy. In times past, decades ago, there were some practices to that effect. We have eradicated them in the Church now."<ref name="solution" /> Another current mention is in the church website on homosexuality which features a gay man married to a straight woman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth's Story: Ricardo's Wife|url=https://mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/elizabeths-story?pa=16386810402623334046|website=mormonandgay.lds.org|publisher=LDS church|date=October 2016}}</ref>
Other teachings include when in 1984 Hinckley (then in the First Presidency) had stated that "marriage should not be viewed as a therapeutic step to solve problems such as homosexual inclinations or practices ...."<ref name="Reverance" /> Oaks had also previously stated in 2007 that marriages should not be entered under false pretenses<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> and that doing so can damage the lives of others.<ref name="lds92" /> Church leaders are warned that encouraging members to cultivate heterosexual feelings generally leads to frustration and discouragement.<ref name="lds92" /> Previously, The church had taught that it was possible to overcome same-sex feelings<ref name="2the1" /> and that heterosexual feelings can emerge once an individual ceases any same-sex sexual activity.<ref name="lds92" /> Oaks did state in 2007, however, that marriage would be appropriate for a man attracted to men who had "shown their ability to deal with these feelings or inclinations and put them in the background, and feel a great attraction for a daughter of God and therefore desire to enter marriage and have children and enjoy the blessings of eternity."<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> Several gay LDS men reported being able to maintain a heterosexual marriage in 2007.<ref name="Moore 2007-03-30">{{citation|last=Moore|first=Carrie A.|url=http://deseretnews.com/dn/view/0,1249,660207378,00.html|title=Gay LDS men detail challenges|date=March 30, 2007|newspaper=Deseret Morning News}}</ref>
===Research=== Several surveys have been done on the topic of LGBT Mormons and opposite-sex marriages. A 1997 study by members of the BYU Family Studies Department found that of over 200 single LDS women of diverse ages polled, 33% would be willing to seriously date and consider marriage with a hypothetical LDS college grad who had been sexually active with other men 3 years ago.<ref name="BYU Poll">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher Stack|first1=Peggy|title=42 Percent At BYU Want Gays Kept Out; Gays Unwelcome, Say Many at BYU|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=9 November 1997|via=ProQuest Newsstand|quote=Respondents then were asked four questions: 1. Would they gracefully decline or accept the request to work with him for one year? 2. After one year, he is romantic and sexually attracted to you, but he still has same-sex attraction. He promises never to engage in any sex outside marriage. Would you accept or decline? 3. You continue your friendship and he works hard until you are convinced he has only a weak same-sex attraction. He is romantically and sexually attracted to you. Would you accept or decline? 4. Would your response change if he had never been sexually active?Researchers found that 33 percent answered yes to question 1; 11 percent to question 2; 23 percent to question 3; and 33 percent to question 4.}}</ref> A 2015 study found that 51% of the 1,612 LGBT Mormon respondents who had entered a mixed-orientation marriage ended up divorcing,<ref name="Psychosocial">{{cite journal|last1=Galliher|first1=Renee|last2=Bradshaw|first2=William|last3=Dehlin|first3=John|last4=Crowelle|first4=Katherine|title=Psychosocial Correlates of Religious Approaches to Same-Sex Attraction: A Mormon Perspective|journal=Journal of Gay & Lesbian Mental Health|date=25 April 2014|volume=18|issue=3|doi=10.1080/19359705.2014.912970|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/19359705.2014.912970}}</ref>{{rp|301}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher Stack|first1=Peggy|title=Study Reveals What Really Happens When Gay Mormon Men Marry Straight Women|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/01/13/gay-mormon-men-marriage_n_6464848.html|work=The Huffington Post|date=14 January 2015}}</ref> and projected that 69% of all these marriages would ultimately end in divorce.<ref name="SOCE">{{cite journal|last1=Dehlin|first1=John P.|title=Sexual Orientation Change Efforts, Identity Conflict, and Psychosocial Health Amongst Same-Sex Attracted Mormons|journal=Utah State University: All Graduate Theses and Dissertations|date=2015|url=https://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=5314&context=etd}}</ref>{{rp|108}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher Stack|first1=Peggy|title=If a gay Mormon man marries a woman, divorce is likely, study finds|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=2050536&itype=CMSID|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=29 January 2015|quote=The study found that: Between 51 percent and 69 percent of mixed-orientation Mormon marriages end in divorce, well above the roughly 25 percent of LDS couples who split up.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ring|first1=Trudy|title=Study: Mixed-Orientation Mormon Marriages Likely to Fail|url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/religion/2015/01/13/study-mixed-orientation-mormon-marriages-likely-fail|work=Advocate|date=13 January 2015}}</ref> The study also found that engaging in mixed-orientation marriages and involvement in the LDS church were correlated with higher rates of depression and a lower quality of life for LGBT people.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Galliher|first1=Renee|last2=Bradshaw|first2=William|last3=Dehlin|first3=John|last4=Crowelle|first4=Katherine|title=Psychosocial Correlates of Religious Approaches to Same-Sex Attraction: A Mormon Perspective|journal=Journal of Gay & Lesbian Mental Health|page=301,304|date=25 April 2014|volume=18|issue=3|doi=10.1080/19359705.2014.912970|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/19359705.2014.912970|quote=The major findings from the study are that non-biologically based views regarding the etiology of SSA [same-sex attraction], remaining active in the LDS church, remaining single, and engaging in mixed-orientation marriages were all associated with higher reported levels of internalized homophobia, sexual identity distress, and depression, and lower levels of self-esteem and quality of life. ... This study does affirm and extend the existing literature by suggesting that psychosocially based beliefs about SSA etiology active participation in non-LGBT-affirming churches, being single and celibate, and mixed-orientation marriage—all of which are common beliefs and/or practices within modern, active LDS culture—are associated with poorer psychosocial health, well-being, and quality of life for LGBT Mormons. Conversely, biological beliefs about SSA etiology, complete disaffiliation from the LDS church, legal same-sex marriage, and sexual activity are all associated with higher levels of psychosocial health, well-being, and quality of life for LGBT Mormons.}}</ref>
==Political involvement around LGBT rights== {{See also|The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and politics in the United States}} [[File:Flags at SLC Mormon Temple.jpg|thumb|150px|right|The LDS church has held notable political influence on laws around LGBT individuals in the United States, especially in the state of Utah.]] The LDS church has been involved with many pieces of legislation relating to LGBT discrimination and same-sex marriage. Leaders have stated that it will become involved in political matters if it perceives that there is a moral issue at stake and wields considerable influence on a national level<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ayers|first1=Michael D.|title=When Mormons Go to Washington|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2012/10/mormon-politicians-lds-church-romney|agency=Vanity Fair|date=15 Oct 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Jane|title=There Is a Dark Side to Mormonism|url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/01/30/what-is-it-about-mormons/there-is-a-dark-side-to-mormonism|agency=The New York Times|date=1 Feb 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Grant|first1=Tobin|title=Five things you should know about Mormon politics|url=http://religionnews.com/2015/04/27/five-things-know-mormon-politics/|agency=Religion News|publisher=Religion News Foundation|date=27 April 2015}}</ref> with over a dozen members of congress having membership in the church in the early 2000s,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mansfield|first1=Stephen|title=The Mormonizing of America|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/stephen-mansfield/the-mormonizing-of-americ_b_2083125.html|agency=The Huffington Post|date=6 Nov 2012}}</ref> and about 80% of Utah state lawmakers identifying as Mormon.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrison|first1=Peter|title=The LDS Church and Utah Politics|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/peter-harrison/the-lds-church-and-utah-p_b_9278128.html|agency=The Huffington Post|date=22 Feb 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davidson|first1=Lee|title=How Utah's Capitol marches to a Mormon beat|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/sltrib/home3/53709967-200/lds-church-says-position.html.csp|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Canham|first1=Matt|title=Mormon political clout in Utah: Republicans say it’s about right, but Dems say LDS faith has too much|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/lds/2421049-155/mormon-political-clout-in-utah-republicans|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=17 Feb 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bernick|first1=Bob|title=How Much Influence Does the LDS Church Have on the Legislature? Depends on Who You Ask|url=http://utahpolicy.com/index.php/features/today-at-utah-policy/5430-how-much-influence-does-the-lds-church-have-on-the-legislature-depends-on-who-you-ask|website=utahpolicy.com}}</ref>
===Views on discrimination laws=== In February 2003, the LDS Church said it did not oppose a hate-crimes bill, which included sexual orientation, then under consideration in the Utah state legislature.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/590037091/Debate-shifts-to-LDS-over-crime-bill.html|title=Debate shifts to LDS over crime bill|first=Joe|last=Bauman|date=January 19, 2004|publisher=[[Deseret News]] }}</ref> The church opposes same-sex marriage, but does not object to rights regarding [[hospitalization]] and [[medical care]], [[fair housing]] and [[Labour law|employment rights]], or [[probate|probate rights]], so long as these do not infringe on the integrity of the family or the constitutional rights of churches and their adherents to administer and practice their religion free from government interference.<ref name=DivineMarriage>{{cite news|title=The Divine Institution of Marriage|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/the-divine-institution-of-marriage|accessdate=January 23, 2015|publisher=LDS Church}}</ref> Following two months of negotiations between top Utah gay rights leaders and mid-level church leaders,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_13758070|title=Salt Lake City adopts pro-gay statutes -- with LDS Church support|newspaper=[[Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=November 10, 2009|first1=Matt|last1=Canham|first2=Derek P.|last2=Jensen|first3=Rosemary|last3=Winters}}</ref> the church supported a gay rights bill in Salt Lake City which bans discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation and gender identity in housing and employment, calling them "common-sense rights." The law does not apply to housing or employment provided by religious organizations.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/12/us/12utah.html|title=Mormon Support of Gay Rights Statute Draws Praise|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 11, 2009|first=Kirk|last=Johnson }}</ref><ref>{{citation |contribution-url= http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/statement-given-to-salt-lake-city-council-on-nondiscrimination-ordinances |contribution= Statement Given to Salt Lake City Council on Nondiscrimination Ordinances |title= News Story |date= January 1, 2009 |publisher= LDS Church}}</ref> Apostle [[Jeffrey R. Holland|Holland]] stated that it could be a model for the rest of the state.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_13766464|title=LDS apostle: SLC gay-rights measures could work for state|date=November 11, 2009|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|first1=Rosemary|last1=Winters|first2=Peggy Fletcher|last2=Stack|author2-link=Peggy Fletcher Stack}}</ref> The LDS Church has not taken a position on [[Employment Non-Discrimination Act|ENDA]].<ref>{{citation |contribution-url= http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-responds-to-inquiries-on-enda--same-sex-marriage |contribution= Church Responds to Inquiries on ENDA, Same-Sex Marriage |date= November 7, 2013 |title= News Release |publisher= LDS Church}}</ref>
A 2017 Public Religion Research Institute survey found that over half (53%) of all Mormon adults believed small private business should be able to deny products and services to gay or lesbian people for religious reasons (compared to 33% of the 40,000+ American adults surveyed),<ref name="Consensus" />{{rp|15,23}} and 24% of all Mormon adults oppose laws that protect LGBT Americans against discrimination in employment, housing, and public accommodations.<ref name="Fading">{{cite news|last1=Mims|first1=Bob|title=Most Mormons remain against gay marriage, new poll shows, but that opposition is fading fast; younger LDS support it|url=https://www.sltrib.com/religion/2018/05/01/most-mormons-remain-against-gay-marriage-new-poll-shows-but-that-opposition-is-fading-fast-younger-lds-support-it/|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref name="Consensus">{{cite web|last1=Fisch-Friedman|first1=Molly|last2=Vandermaas-Peeler|first2=Alex|last3=Griffin|first3=Rob|last4=Cox|first4=Daniel|last5=Jones|first5=Robert P.|title=Emerging Consensus on LGBT Issues: Findings From the 2017 American Values Atlas|url=https://www.prri.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/AVA-2017-FINAL.pdf|website=prri.org|publisher=Public Religion Research Institute|date=2018}}</ref>{{rp|20}}
===Opposition to same-sex marriage legislation=== {{See also|California Proposition 8 (2008)|The Divine Institution of Marriage|Protests against Proposition 8 supporters}} [[File:Prop8templeProtest.jpg|thumb|left|Protesters in front of the [[Newport Beach California Temple]] voicing their opposition to the church's support of [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Prop 8]]]] In reference to church involvement with legislation around LGBT people and marriage the apostle [[M. Russell Ballard]] has said the church is "locked in" if anything interferes with the principle of marriage being between a man and a woman, and stated that a very careful evaluation is made to determine what action is appropriate.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99175018&ps=rs|title=New Mormon Temple: Sacred Or Secret?|first=Howard|last=Berkes|date=January 9, 2009|work=[[All Things Considered]]|publisher=[[NPR]] }}</ref> Beginning in the mid-1990s, the LDS Church began to focus its attention on the issue of same-sex marriages with one scholar citing the church's views of God's male-female union plan, their sense of responsibility in publicly protecting traditional morality, and a fear of government encroachment in church performed marriages as the motivations for this opposition.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Payne|first1=Seth R.|title=Mormonism and Same-Sex Marriage: Theological Underpinnings and New Perspectives|journal=Journal of Catholic Legal Studies|date=February 2017|volume=51|issue=41|page=50|url=http://scholarship.law.stjohns.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1033&context=jcls}}</ref> In 1993, the Supreme Court of Hawaii held that discrimination against same-sex couples in the granting of marriage licenses violated the Hawaiian constitution. In response, the church's [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] issued a statement on February 13, 1994 declaring their opposition to same-sex marriage, and urging members to support efforts to outlaw it. With the lobbying of the LDS Church and several other religious organizations, the Hawaii legislature enacted a bill in 1994 outlawing same-sex marriages.
In response to Hawaii's same-sex marriage passage, the LDS Church released the 1995 "[[The Family: A Proclamation to the World]]" reaffirming its stance that marriage is between one man and one woman.<ref name = HRC>{{cite web|last=Jeppson|first=Buckley|title=Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (Mormons)|url=http://www.hrc.org/issues/religion/4988.htm|work=HRC website|publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]]|accessdate=April 8, 2011}}</ref> However, this monogamous stance has been strongly criticized as hypocritical given the Church's historical disagreement with this legal definition which bars [[Mormonism and polygamy|polygamy]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Feldman|first1=Noah R.|title=The Oxford Handbook of Mormonism: Mormonism in the American Political Domain|date=1 October 2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0199778361|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Es4fCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA618&lpg=PA618&#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=12 June 2017|ref=Handbook of Mormonism}}</ref>{{rp|618}}
In 2004, the Church officially endorsed an [[Federal Marriage Amendment|federal amendment]] to the [[United States Constitution]] as well as [[Utah Constitutional Amendment 3]] banning any marriages not between one man and one woman and announced its opposition to political measures that "confer legal status on any other sexual relationship" than "a man and a woman lawfully wedded as husband and wife."<ref name="LDS Church 2004" /> This statement seemed to also oppose [[civil union]]s, [[common-law marriage]]s, [[plural marriage]]s, or other family arrangements. This political involvement elicited the criticism of California Senator [[Mark Leno]] who questioned whether the Church's tax-exempt status should be revoked.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,700226242,00.html |title=LDS Church expresses disappointment in California gay marriage decision |date=May 15, 2008 |first=Carrie |last=Moore |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601193325/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/1%2C5143%2C700226242%2C00.html |archivedate=June 1, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>
[[File:YesOnProp8YardSign.png|thumb|right|150px|The church distributed hundreds of thousands of these [[ProtectMarriage.com|Protect Marriage Coalition]] lawn signs during their involvement with the pro-[[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Prop 8]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karger|first1=Fred|title=Mormon Church Bleeding Members Over Gay Marriage|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/fred-karger/mormon-church-bleeding-me_b_8299882.html|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=Huffington Post|agency=HuffPost MultiCultural News|date=15 October 2016}}</ref>]] On August 13, 2008, the Church released a letter explaining why it believed that same-sex marriage would be detrimental to society and encouraging California members to support [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Prop 8]]<ref name=DivineMarriage /> which would bar anything but opposite-sex marriages. The letter asked members to donate time and money towards the initiative. Church members would account for 80 to 90 percent of volunteers who campaigned door-to-door and as much as half of the nearly $40 million raised during the campaign.<ref>{{Citation|title=Mormons Tipped Scale in Ban on Gay Marriage|author=Jesse McKinley and Kirk Johnson|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 14, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/15/us/politics/15marriage.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=February 14, 2012 }}</ref> In November 2008, the day after California voters approved [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]], the LDS Church stated that it does not object to [[domestic partnership]] or [[civil union]] legislation as long as these do not infringe on the integrity of the traditional family or the constitutional rights of churches.<ref>{{Citation|title=California's Prop 8: LDS leader calls for healing the gay-marriage rift|author=Brooke Adams |work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=November 5, 2008|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/printfriendly.php?id=10907306&itype=ngpsid|accessdate=December 20, 2013 }}</ref> Soon after, top leader [[Whitney Clayton]] stated that members who opposed Prop. 8 may be subject to discipline from local church leaders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Carrie A.|title=California's Prop. 8|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705260852/LDS-official-lauds-work-for-Californias-Prop-8.html|work=Deseret News|publisher=LDS church|date=6 November 2008|quote=When asked about whether Latter-day Saints who publicly opposed Prop. 8 would be subject to some kind of church discipline, Elder Clayton said those judgments are left up to local bishops and stake presidents and the particular circumstances involved.}}</ref> The Church's political involvement in Prop 8 and stance on homosexuality was denounced by the 2010 documentary film ''[[8: The Mormon Proposition]]''. In a special meeting for some Oakland, California members it was reported that church historian and Seventy [[Marlin K. Jensen|Marlin Jensen]] apologized to straight and gay members for their pain from the Proposition 8 campaign and some other church actions around homosexuality.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brooks|first1=Joanna|title=Mormon Leader: ‘I’m Sorry’ For Hurtful Legacy of Prop. 8|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604154837/http://www.religiondispatches.org/archive/sexandgender/3437/|url=http://www.religiondispatches.org/archive/sexandgender/3437/|archive-date=4 June 2014|work=Religion Dispatches|publisher=University of Southern California Annenberg|date=28 September 2010|quote=During the one-hour meeting, thirteen gay and straight Mormons came to the microphone. ... Gay Mormons recalled years of prayer and fasting, attempted heterosexual marriages promising to 'cure' them, and Church-prescribed aversion therapy. Gay and straight Mormons spoke of how their families and neighborhoods had been divided by the Yes on 8 campaign. ... According to attendee Carol Lynn Pearson, a Mormon author and longtime advocate of LGBT concerns, Elder Jensen said, 'To the full extent of my capacity, I say that I am sorry... I know that many very good people have been deeply hurt, and I know that the Lord expects better of us.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher Stack|first1=Peggy|title=Mormon leadership bids farewell to peacemaking progressive|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=55011521&itype=cmsid|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=8 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Welker|first1=Holly|title=LDS Elder Marlin Jensen’s Prop 8 ‘Apology’: We Need Clarification|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/holly-welker/elder-jensen-prop-8-apology_b_739609.html|work=Huffington Post|date=27 September 2010}}</ref> [[File:Wedding rings.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Identical [[wedding ring]]s]]
On December 20, 2013, the topic of same-sex marriage and the LDS church was raised again when U.S. District Judge [[Robert J. Shelby]] struck down the Utah ban on same-sex marriage, saying it violated the U.S. Constitution's [[Equal Protection Clause]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Adams|first=Brooke|title=Federal judge strikes down Utah ban on same-sex marriage|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/57291925-78/marriage-utah-sex-state.html.csp|accessdate=January 21, 2014|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=December 20, 2013}}</ref> In response, the Church released instructions to leaders regarding [[same-sex marriage in Utah]].<ref name="Walch">{{cite news|last=Walch|first=Tad|title=LDS Church issues instructions to leaders on same-sex marriage|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865593905/LDS-Church-issues-instructions-to-leaders-on-same-sex-marriage.html|accessdate=January 21, 2014|newspaper=Deseret News|date=January 10, 2014}}</ref> These included the stance that, while the church disagrees with the court ruling, those who obtain same-sex marriage should not be treated disrespectfully.<ref name="Walch"/> Additionally, it stated that church leaders were prohibited from employing their authority to perform marriages, and that any church property could not be used for same-sex marriages or receptions.<ref name="Walch"/>
In November 2015, a new policy was released stating that members who are in a [[same-sex marriage]] are considered apostates and may be subject to church discipline.<ref name = 2015policy/> Additionally, the children of parents who are in same-sex relationships must wait until they are 18 years old and then disavow homosexual relationships before they can be baptized.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brady McCombs |url=https://news.yahoo.com/mormon-rule-changes-aimed-gays-send-advocates-reeling-190218232.html |title=Mormon church issues rules aimed at gay members, their kids - Yahoo News |publisher=News.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>
A 2017 Public Religion Research Institute survey found that over half (52%) of Mormon young adults (18–29) supported same-sex marriage while less than a third (32%) of Mormon seniors (65+) did the same.<ref name="Consensus" />{{rp|11}}<ref name="Fading" />
==LGBT students at Brigham Young University== {{main|Brigham Young University LGBT history}} {{see also|Church Educational System Honor Code}}
[[File:LGBT Flag on BYU Sign.jpg|thumb|200px|right|BYU has been ranked as the worst large US university for LGBT persons.<ref name="Ranking Categories: Demographics">{{citation |url= http://www.princetonreview.com/schoollist.aspx?type=r&id=677 |title= Ranking Categories: Demographics |work= Princeton Review College Ranking |publisher= ''The Princeton Review'' |accessdate= April 9, 2012 }}</ref><ref name="https">{{cite journal|last1=Knox|first1=Annie|title=BYU, other Christian schools ranked among the least LGBT-friendly campuses|journal=The Washington Post|date=11 August 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/religion/byu-other-christian-schools-ranked-among-the-least-lgbt-friendly-campuses/2015/08/11/874381c0-4058-11e5-b2c4-af4c6183b8b4_story.html|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>]]
[[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) is the largest religious university in North America and is the flagship institution of the LDS Church's [[Church Educational System|educational system]]. A BYU study from 1950 to 1972 showed that 10% of BYU men and 2% of BYU women indicated having had a "homosexual experience."<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=Wilford E.|title=Mormon Sex Standards on College Campuses, or Deal Us Out of the Sexual Revolution!|journal=Dialogue|date=Fall 1976|volume=10|issue=2|pages=76–77|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/archive/issue-details/?in=38|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Prelude">{{cite journal|last1=Quinn|first1=D. Michael|title=Prelude to the National 'Defense of Marriage' Campaign: Civil Discrimination Against Feared or Despised Minorities|journal=Dialogue|date=Fall 2000|volume=33|issue=3|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V33N03_13.pdf|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref>{{rp|45}} Several LGBT rights organizations have criticized BYU's [[Brigham Young University Honor Code|Honor Code]] as it relates to LGBT students and [[The Princeton Review]] has regularly ranked BYU among the most LGBT-unfriendly schools in the United States.<ref name="Ranking Categories: Demographics"/><ref name="https"/><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.soulforce.org/article/936|title=Brigham Young University|work=The Equality Ride: School Policies of Religious Schools|publisher=[[Soulforce (organization)|Soulforce]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204225310/http://www.soulforce.org/article/936|archivedate=February 4, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> BYU campus currently offers no official LGBT-specific resources.<ref name="USA Today">{{cite news|last1=Gleeson|first1=Scott|title=Could BYU's LGBT policies really deter Big 12 move?|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/big12/2016/08/09/byu-usga-lgbt-big-12-conference-expansion/88446494/|accessdate=12 January 2017|agency=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=10 August 2016}}</ref>
[[File:USGA_at_BYU.jpg|thumb|left|LGBT BYU students at a [[Understanding Same-Gender Attraction|USGA]] meeting in 2017]] BYU has seen many changes in policies around its LGBT student population. In 1962 a ban on students known to have a homosexual orientation was enacted by [[Ernest L. Wilkinson|Ernest Wilkinson]], but softened a decade later by his successor [[Dallin Oaks|Dallin H. Oaks]] in 1973 to only ban "overt and active homosexuals."<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|375}}<ref>{{cite book|title=BYU Board Meeting Minutes|date=19 April 1973|publisher=BYU|location=BYU Library Special Collections|pages=6–7|url=http://files.lib.byu.edu/ead/XML/UA1085.xml}}</ref><ref name="Pain">{{cite speech|title=Private pain, public purges: a history of homosexuality at Brigham Young University|first=Rocky Connell|last=O'Donovan|location=University of California Santa Cruz|date=28 April 1997|url=http://churchhistorycatalog.lds.org/primo_library/libweb/action/dlDisplay.do?vid=CHL_PUBLIC&docId=ALEPH-PCHD001934095&fromSitemap=1&afterPDS=true}} Reprinted [http://exmormon.org/d6/drupal/byuhis here].</ref> Under Oaks a system of surveillance and searches of dorms of problem students including suspected homosexuals was implemented<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bergera|first1=James|last2=Priddis|first2=Ronald|title=Brigham Young University: A House of Faith|date=1985|publisher=Signature Books|isbn=0941214346|page=126|url=http://signaturebookslibrary.org/standards-the-honor-code/|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Oaks Supports Security's Police Powers|agency=Daily Universe|publisher=BYU|date=18 Sep 1979}}</ref> including stake outs by BYU security looking for license plates of BYU students at gay bars in Salt Lake City and fake contact advertisements placed in gay publications attempting to ensnare BYU students.<ref name="newspapers.com">{{cite news|last1=Moes|first1=Garry J.|title=Ex-BYU Security Officer Tells of Intrigue, Spying|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/12707305/|agency=Salt Lake Tribune|date=22 Mar 1975}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|442}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alberty|first1=Erin|title=Longtime Utah LGBT advocates recount brutal history|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/oct/10/longtime-utah-lgbt-advocates-recall-brutal-history/|agency=Washington Times|date=10 Oct 2014}}</ref> In the late 1990s a reference to "homosexual conduct" was added to the BYU Honor Code,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wilson|first1=John K.|title=Patriotic Correctness: Academic Freedom and Its Enemies|date=1 August 2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1594511943|page=146}}</ref> and there was a ban on coming out for lesbian, gay, or bisexual students.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mormonism: "Do Ask, Do Tell" at BYU|url=http://www.newsweek.com/mormonism-do-ask-do-tell-byu-98007?rx=us|accessdate=5 February 2017|agency=Newsweek|date=29 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=BYU clarifies code on homosexuality: Homosexual orientation no longer a violation|url=https://www.christiancentury.org/article/2007-05/byu-clarifies-code-homosexuality-0|journal=The Christian Century|date=29 May 2007|volume=124|issue=11|page=15|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Kirsten|title=BYU Brass Suspend Two Gays|accessdate=15 January 2017|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/281319012/C98204FE1C804BD8PQ|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=29 March 2001}}</ref> In 2007, BYU changed the honor code to read that stating one's sexual orientation was not an honor code issue.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lyon|first1=Julia|title=BYU changes honor code text about gay students|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/news/ci_5684555|accessdate=15 January 2017|agency=Salt Lake Tribune|date=17 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Walch|first1=Tad|title=BYU clarifies Honor Code about gay orientation|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/660212820/-BYU-clarifies-Honor-Code-about-gay-orientation.html|accessdate=15 January 2017|agency=Deseret News|publisher=LDS Church|date=18 April 2007}}</ref> This allowed for the formation of a group called [[Understanding Same-Gender Attraction|USGA]] (Understanding Same-Gender Attraction) consisting of BYU students and other members of the [[Provo, Utah|Provo]] community which began meeting on campus in 2010 to discuss issues relating to homosexuality and the LDS Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://extras.sltrib.com/PDFs/studentreview.pdf|title=Understanding Same-Gender Attraction|publisher=Student Review|date=September 19, 2011|page=16}}</ref> By December 2012 they were no longer allowed to hold meetings on campus.<ref name="05.13.148:45 AM ET">{{cite web|author=05.13.148:45 AM ET |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/05/13/g-a-y-at-b-y-u.html |title=Mormon U. Forces Gays to Be Celibate |publisher=The Daily Beast |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2015}}</ref>
==Sexual orientation change efforts==
[[File:Turn It Off Conversion Therapy Light Switch.png|thumb|right|150px|Church leaders taught for decades that members could and should try to change their sexual orientation,<ref name="SOCE3" /> with a 2011 Broadway play satirizing these teachings with a gay Mormon missionary stating that he could "turn it off like a light switch" in reference to eliminating his gay feelings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Glitz|first1=Michael|title='The Book Of Mormon'—Why Aren’t More People Offended?|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-giltz/the-book-of-mormon----why_b_886419.html|work=Huffington Post|date=28 June 2011|quote=What about 'Turn It Off?' In this show-stopper for Tony-nominated supporting actor Rory O’Malley as Elder McKinley, some missionaries share their approach to confusing thoughts or bad feelings. ... [W]hen you have gay thoughts for your best friend, well, 'Turn it off!' Non-believers hear hypocrisy and an absurdly simplistic solution to difficult issues: 'Turn it off/ Like a light switch/ Just go flick/ It’s our nifty little Mormon trick.' ... It’s not an official approach by any faith, as such, but numerous fundamentalist faiths acknowledge that some men are inherently gay. They want those men to simply tamp down these bad feelings and marry a woman anyway, because with prayer and the proper spouse and God’s love you can be alright.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Atkinson|first1=Sally|title=Clark Johnsen: From Mormon Missionary to Broadway in The Book of Mormon|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/clark-johnsen-from-mormon-missionary-to-broadway-in-the-book-of-mormon|work=The Daily Beast|date=7 June 2011|quote=On the show-stopper 'Turn It Off,' sung by a closeted missionary struggling with his sexuality. 'I'm one of the few missionaries who actually was out to myself as a gay person on my mission and out to some of my mission companions—the ones who asked. [The Book of Mormon song] 'Turn It Off' is such an insightful view into the psychology of a gay missionary in particular, but also into all Mormons. In the church, you don't say you're gay, you say you have homosexual tendencies, because 'gay' is this label they want you to hopefully outgrow, which I tried to do. It didn't work.}}</ref>]] In the past the LDS church (like Orthodox Judaism, evangelical Christianity, and Catholicism) encouraged its LGBTQ members to attempt to change their sexual orientation, and continued to communicate into 2015 that changing one's sexual orientation was possible through personal righteousness, prayer, faith in Christ, psychotherapy, and group therapy and retreats.<ref name="SOCE3">{{cite journal|last1=Galliher|first1=Renee|last2=Bradshaw|first2=William|last3=Hyde|first3=Daniel|last4=Dehlin|first4=John|last5=Crowell|first5=Katherine|title=Sexual orientation change efforts among current or former LDS church members|journal=Journal of Counseling Psychology|page=96|date=April 2015|volume=62|issue=2|url=http://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fcou0000011|doi=10.1037/cou0000011|quote=The LDS church claims the Holy Bible as scripture and, through traditional Biblical interpretations, has historically both condemned same-sex sexuality as sinful and explicitly encouraged its lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ) members to attempt sexual orientation change. While the LDS church has somewhat softened its stance toward LGBTQ individuals in recent years, it continues to communicate to its LGBTQ members that sexual orientation change is possible through various means including prayer, personal righteousness, faith in Jesus Christ, psychotherapy, group therapy, and group retreats. In these respects, the LDS church’s approach to SSA has closely paralleled other religious traditions including Orthodox Judaism, evangelical Christianity, and Roman Catholicism.}}</ref> Stances softened over the years, however.<ref name="SOCE3" /> In the 60s and 70s Church leaders taught that homosexuality was a curable disease and they encouraged self-help attempts by homosexual members to change their sexual orientation and cultivate heterosexual feelings.<ref name="Paradigm">{{cite web|last1=Prince|first1=Gregory A.|title=Science vs. Dogma: Biology Challenges the LDS Paradigm of Homosexuality|url=https://thc.utah.edu/lectures-programs/mcmurrin-lecture/PRINCE-MCMURRIN%20LECTURE-protected.pdf|website=thc.utah.edu|publisher=University of Utah Tanner Humanities Center|date=27 September 2017}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gssnz1WZ3dU Video] of the presentation.</ref>{{rp|13–19}} To assist in this, leaders developed an aversion therapy program on BYU campus for gay adolescents and adults from '59<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|379}} to '83<ref name="Conservative Christian Identity" />{{rp|65}} since simply being attracted to people of the same sex was an excommunicable sin under church president [[Spencer W. Kimball|Kimball]].<ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|2}} Teachings later changed as it became clear these self-help and aversive techniques were not working and, thus, from the 80s to the 2000s reparative therapy (also called [[conversion therapy]]) became the dominant treatment method. It was often recommended by [[Evergreen International|Evergreen]] in an attempt to help homosexual members unchoose and unlearn their attractions.
In a 2010 survey of 625 Utah individuals 55% of Mormons believed sexual orientation could be changed,<ref name="Overcome">{{cite news|title=Many Utahns Think Homosexuality Can Be Overcome|url=https://newspapers.lib.utah.edu/details?id=22605024|work=Park Record|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Swift Communications, Inc.|date=13 November 2010}}</ref> and a 2015 survey of 1,612 LGBT Mormons and former Mormons found that 73% of men and 43% of women had attempted sexual orientation change, usually through multiple methods across many years.<ref name="SOCE2">{{cite journal|last1=Galliher|first1=Renee|last2=Bradshaw|first2=William|last3=Hyde|first3=Daniel|last4=Dehlin|first4=John|last5=Crowell|first5=Katherine|title=Sexual orientation change efforts among current or former LDS church members|journal=Journal of Counseling Psychology|date=April 2015|volume=62|issue=2|url=http://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fcou0000011|doi=10.1037/cou0000011}}</ref>{{rp|5}} Counselor-led [[sexual orientation change efforts]] dwindled among members around 2015<ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|17–20}} as church teachings evolved with leaders explicitly stating in 2012 that same-sex sexual attractions were not a choice<ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|21}} and affirming in 2016 that therapy focusing on a change in sexual orientation was unethical.<ref name="Professional Help" /><ref name="Weeds" />
===Aversion therapy at BYU=== {{main|Brigham Young University LGBT history#Aversion therapy at BYU}} [[File:BYU_Honor_Code_Office.png|thumb|125px|right|BYU's Honor Code office required some students reported for homosexual behavior to undergo electroshock and vomit aversion therapies in the 1970s<ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|155}}]] In 1959 BYU began administering "[[aversion therapy]]" to "cure," "repair," or "reorient" homosexual feelings or behavior among Mormon males.<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|377,379}} The on-campus program lasted through the 60s and 70s, and faded out around 1983.<ref name="Conservative Christian Identity" />{{rp|64–65}}<ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|155,157}} BYU mental health counselors, LDS bishops, stake presidents, mission presidents, general authorities, and the BYU Standards Office (equivalent to today's Honor Code Office) all referred young men to the BYU program.<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|377–379}} Gerald J. Dye, who was over the University Standards Office from 1971 to 1980<ref>{{cite web|title=Brigham Young University. University Standards Office|url=https://sites.lib.byu.edu/byuorg/index.php/Brigham_Young_University._University_Standards_Office|website=BYU Library|publisher=BYU|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref> (renamed the Honor Code Office in 1991), stated that part of the "set process" for homosexual BYU students referred to his office for "less serious" offenses was to require that they undergo therapy to remain at BYU and that in special cases this included "electroshock and vomiting aversion therapies."<ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|155}} From 1975 to 1976 Max Ford McBride, a student at BYU, conducted electroshock aversion therapy on 17 men (with 14 completing the treatment) and published a dissertation on the use of electrical aversive techniques to treat [[ego-dystonic homosexuality]].<ref name="McBrideDissertation">{{Cite thesis|last=McBride|first=Max Ford|title=Effect of Visual Stimuli in Electric Aversion Therapy|publisher=Department of Psychology of Brigham Young University|year=1976|degree=Ph.D.|oclc=82836025|url=https://archive.org/stream/BYUaversionTherapy/McBride%20Effect%20of%20Visual%20Stimuli%20in%20Electric%20Aversion%20Therapy%20BYU%20Dissertation%20Aug%201976#page/n0/mode/2up}}</ref> Participant in the 1975-76 BYU study Don Harryman wrote that he experienced "burns on [his] arms and ... emotional trauma."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schow|first1=Ron|last2=Schow|first2=Wayne|last3=Raynes|first3=Marybeth|last4=Bennion|first4=Lowell L.|title=Peculiar People: Mormons and Same-Sex Orientation|date=15 Jun 1991|publisher=Signature Books|isbn=1560850469|pages=26–28}}</ref><ref name="one">{{Citation|url=http://www.affirmation.org/therapy/with_all_thy_getting.shtml |publisher=Affirmation: Gay & Lesbian Mormons |title=With All Thy Getting, Get Understanding |first=Don D. |last=Harryman |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021171348/http://www.affirmation.org/therapy/with_all_thy_getting.shtml |archivedate=October 21, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2011 BYU admitted to the past use of electroshock therapy.<ref name=mormon-gay-cures>{{citation |url= http://abcnews.go.com/Health/mormon-gay-cures-reparative-therapies-shock-today/story?id=13240700&singlePage=true |title= Mormon 'Gay Cure' Study Used Electric Shocks Against Homosexual Feelings |work= [[Good Morning America]] |publisher= [[ABC News]] |first= Susan Donaldson |last= James |date= March 30, 2011 |accessdate= July 2, 2014 }}</ref>
===Conversion therapy=== {{see also|Brigham Young University LGBT history#Conversion therapy at BYU}} LDS church leaders explicitly promoted non-aversive therapy attempts to change sexual orientation in the past, but have recently shifted away from those previous views.<ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|17–20}} Some events and publications on LDS reparative or conversion therapy are shown below:
* '''1986''' – BYU published a study by BYU professor and area Church Welfare Services director Victor Brown Jr.<ref name="ldsfaq.byu.edu">{{cite web|last1=Brown Jr.|first1=Victor|title=Can the gospel of Jesus Christ help people to overcome serious problems of intimacy?|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104224629/http://ldsfaq.byu.edu:80/viewQuestion.aspx?view=a4ee6072-4902-405e-8aba-a4decc1b8c83|website=ldsfaq.byu.edu|publisher=BYU|archive-date=4 January 2009|url=http://ldsfaq.byu.edu:80/viewQuestion.aspx?view=a4ee6072-4902-405e-8aba-a4decc1b8c83}}</ref> stating that people can eliminate homosexual feelings.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brown Jr.|first1=Victor|title=Healing Problems of Intimacy by Clients' Use of Gospel-Based Values and Role Definitions|journal=BYU Studies Quarterly|date=1 January 1986|pages=7, 23–24|volume=26|issue=1|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?&article=2419&context=byusq|quote=Recognition of inadequate treatment regimens regimes regimens may account for erroneous but widespread beliefs such as that male homosexuality is not changeable. ... Change was embedded in an accepting evaluative and loving non-erotic social milieu that provided expectations ideology and actual interpersonal experiences leading to the extinction of homosexual impulses and behaviors. ... Warren was discovering that he was not the odd man out he had believed all his life and as his gender security increased his homosexual desires decreased.}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|last1=Brown Jr.|first1=Victor L.|title=What is the Latter-day Saint position on homosexuality?|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104224711/http://ldsfaq.byu.edu:80/viewQuestion.aspx?view=f06c6c0a-864d-48e4-a6d5-985e548726fb|website=ldsfaq.byu.edu|publisher=BYU|archive-date=4 January 2009|url=http://ldsfaq.byu.edu:80/viewQuestion.aspx?view=f06c6c0a-864d-48e4-a6d5-985e548726fb}}</ref> * '''1993''' – A poll of over 400 BYU students found that 41% believed the church only accepted same-sex oriented individuals as long as they changed their sexual orientation and 10% believed the church would excommunicate them regardless of sexual behavior.<ref name="Poll">{{cite news|last1=Smart|first1=Michael|title=BYU Student Poll: Ban Gay Students|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/288698514/5E2B8153F7E84354PQ/1?accountid=4488|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=22 March 1997|via=ProQuest Newsstand|quote=As part of a project for their English class, Sam Clayton, Dale Franklin and Melanie Dinger conducted the school-approved survey to 420 students in randomly selected classes on campus. Respondents had four choices to answer the question 'What statement do you think best describes the church's stand?' Thirty-three percent chose 1. 'Accepts in full fellowship homosexually-oriented persons who live the Church's law of chastity.' Forty-one percent chose 2. 'Accepts homosexually-oriented persons as long as they change their sexual orientation?' Ten percent believe 3. The LDS Church excommunicates homosexuals regardless of sexual activity, and 10 percent marked 4. 'other.'}}</ref> * '''1993''' – BYU faculty reported that church leaders supported church-employed counselors in using a reparative therapy approach which assumed homosexuality could change.<ref name="Reparative" /> * '''Mid-1990s''' – Gay Mormon Josh Weed went through reparative therapy administered by LDS Family Services.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Morgan|title=The Weeds' story is one of many stories of LGBT Latter-day Saints that continue to be written|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900009667/the-weeds-story-is-one-of-many-stories-of-lgbt-latter-day-saints-that-continue-to-be-written.html|work=Deseret News|publisher=LDS Church|date=7 February 2018|quote=Josh Weed came out to his LDS bishop for the first time when he was 16-years-old during the mid-1990s. He recalls his feelings being quickly dismissed as 'confusion' or 'admiration for other men.' From there he said he went to LDS Family Services where he began undergoing reparative therapy.}}</ref> * '''1996''' – In a 1996 and 1997 presentation psychiatrist Jeffery Jensen criticized church reparative therapy efforts as lacking scientific integrity, saying gay men and lesbians cannot be made heterosexual. He also stated "far too many of our lesbian and gay youths kill themselves because of what you say about them," and "those who believe your false promises and remain celibate in the hopes of eventual 'cure' are consigned to a misery."<ref name="Psychiatrist" /><ref name="Heterosexualization" /> * '''Late 90s''' – [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] journalist Andrew Evans was required to undergo conversion therapy in order to continue as a student at an LDS school.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Evans: Travel Journalist and TV Host|url=https://events.nationalgeographic.com/speakers-bureau/speaker/andrew-evans|website=nationalgeographic.com|publisher=National Geographic|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Evans|first1=Andrew E.|title=Rise and shout, the Cougars are out: Gay former student says BYU forced him into reparative therapy|url=http://www.outsports.com/2017/6/8/15746614/byu-gay-mormon-therapy|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=Out Sports|agency=SB Nation|publisher=[[Vox Media, Inc.]]|date=8 June 2017}}</ref> * '''1998''' – Church leaders discouraged participation in therapy groups that "challenge religious and moral values," "foster physical contact among participants," or "encourage open confession or disclosure of personal information normally discussed only in confidential settings."<ref name="LDS Church 1998" />{{rp|156}} The handbook also explained that "although participants may experience temporary emotional relief or exhilaration, old problems often return, leading to added disappointment and despair."<ref name="LDS Church 1998" />{{rp|155}} * '''1999''' – The American Psychiatric Association disavowed therapy trying to change sexual orientation as ineffective and destructive.<ref name="Rebukes" /> * '''1999''' – A study by church employees of the effects of [[Joseph Nicolosi|Nicolosi]]-influenced reparative therapy on six Mormon individuals with homosexual feelings, was printed in a church university journal stating that "change from same-sex to opposite-sex attraction is possible."<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Byrd|first1=Dean|last2=Chamberlain|first2=Mark|title=Dealing with Issues of Homosexuality: A Qualitative Study of Six Mormons|journal=Religion, Mental Health, and the Latter-day Saints|date=199|page=179|url=https://rsc.byu.edu/archived/religion-mental-health-and-latter-day-saints/10-dealing-issues-homosexuality-qualitative|publisher=BYU}}</ref> * '''1999''' – The church publishes an article in its ''[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]'' on the effectiveness of changing sexual orientation through therapy. The article, written by BYU professor and [[Evergreen International|Evergreen]] Board of Trustees member [[A. Dean Byrd|Dean Byrd]], posited that "homosexuality is not innate and unchangeable", but is caused by "temperament, personality traits, sexual abuse, familial factors, and treatment by one’s peers." The church article further asserted that individuals can "diminish homosexual attraction" and that "when homosexual difficulties have been fully resolved, heterosexual feelings can emerge." In support of this Byrd stated "many individuals who have experienced homosexual difficulties have" had their "burdens" or "trial" "lifted through the Lord’s grace." The article continued acknowledging that those who desire to diminish their "homosexual urgings" may "experience extreme pain because of the extensive changes that are required" including "changing one’s thoughts ... friendships ... or even clothing styles."<ref name="LDS Church">{{cite web|last1=Byrd|first1=A. Dean|title=When a Loved One Struggles with Same-Sex Attraction|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/1999/09/when-a-loved-one-struggles-with-same-sex-attraction|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2000''' – LDS Family Services surveyed 381 of their clients who were homosexual and wanted to change their attractions, and 71% reported significant progress in their sexual orientation change therapy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harris |first1=Jerry |title=Understanding Homosexuality |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925204241/http://ce.byu.edu:80/cw/fuf/archives/2001/harris.pdf |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926071056/http://ce.byu.edu/cw/fuf/archives/ |website=byu.edu |publisher=Brigham Young Unviersity |archive-date=25 September 2011 |date=4 October 2001 |quote=In the year 2000 LDS Family Services surveyed 381 clients desiring change from homosexual thoughts, feelings and behavior. 72% reported 'significant progress' in therapy.}} </ref> * '''2004''' – Jeff Robinson published interviews with seven Mormon men married to women who had been through conversion therapy and previously identified as gay. The seven men believed they had a spiritual transformation and that their orientation was changed. Robinson found that their change came from a new understanding that prior same-sex attractions did not require them to "be" gay.<ref>{{Citation|publisher=[[American Psychological Association]] |journal=Professional Psychology: Research and Practice |title=Initial empirical and clinical findings concerning the change process for ex-gays |url=http://www.drthrockmorton.com/article.asp?id=1 |date=June 2002 |volume=33 |pages=242–248 |last=Throckmorton |first=Warren |doi=10.1037/0735-7028.33.3.242 |issue=3 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504130831/http://www.drthrockmorton.com/article.asp?id=1 |archivedate=May 4, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> * '''2004''' – Researchers published the experience of 50 Mormon men undergoing conversion therapy.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://tcp.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/32/5/651|title=Mormon Clients' Experiences of Conversion Therapy|last1=Beckstead|first1=A. Lee|last2=Morrow|first2=Susan L.|year=2004|volume=32|pages=651–690|doi=10.1177/0011000004267555|journal=The Counseling Psychologist|issue=5}}</ref> * '''2004''' – Michael Ferguson spent seven years undergoing conversion therapy beginning at the recommendation of his BYU bishop in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Lorena|title=I Spent Seven Years in Gay Conversion Therapy Programs Before Breaking Free|url=http://www.esquire.com/news-politics/news/a47144/gay-conversion-therapy-gop-2016/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=Esquire Magazine|agency=Hearst Communications, Inc.|date=28 July 2016|quote=It began his junior year at Brigham Young University in Provo, Utah: Michael Ferguson wanted desperately to rid himself of the sexual feelings he had toward men. His Mormon faith and his loving family would never understand. So he began to try to pray the gay away. Thus began a seven-year journey through nine gay conversion therapy programs, also called reparative therapy, which included hypnotherapy, physical psychotherapy, evangelical spiritual groups, and a 12-step addiction recovery program. Such treatments were designed to "cure" homosexuality by changing a person's sexual orientation or gender identity. ... [W]hile enrolled at Brigham Young University, a bishop advised me to begin conversion therapy with a professional psychologist at the university's counseling center. ... I started in 2004 at BYU and was involved in various conversion therapy attempts through 2011.}}</ref> * '''2004''' – Los Angeles bishop [[Robert A. Rees|Robert Rees]] stated in an academic presentation that of the 50 homosexual Mormons with whom he'd had a close relationship over the past two decades, not a single one "was able to change or alter his or her sexual orientation," and that he hadn't "met a single homosexual Latter-day Saint who had not tried valiantly, generally over a long period of time, to change his or her orientation."<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schow |first1=Ron |title=Homosexual Attraction and LDS Marriage Decision |journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought |date=Fall 2005 |volume=38 |issue=3 |page=142 |url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V38N03_145.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Persistence of Same Sex Attraction in Latter-day Saints |url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/the-persistence-of-same-sex-attraction-in-latter-day-saints-who-undergo-counseling-or-change-therapy/ |website=sunstonemagazine.com |publisher=The Sunstone Education Foundation |date=2004}}</ref> * '''2005''' – In a presentation at BYU's Families Under Fire Conference BYU professor<ref>{{cite web|title=Brigham Young University's School of Social Work Annual Newsletter 2015–2016|url=http://socialwork.byu.edu/Content/Documents/Documents/Newsletters/Winter%202016%20Newsletter.pdf|website=socialwork.byu.edu|publisher=BYU|page=7}}</ref> Shirley Cox stated that homosexual attractions can be diminished and that the treatment of unwanted same-sex attraction has a history of being successful.<ref>{{cite speech |last=Cox |first=Shirley E. |title=Same-Sex Attraction |event=Families Under Fire Conference |date=3 October 2005 |location=Provo, Utah |publisher=BYU }} Presentation outline available at [https://web.archive.org/web/20090307010110/http://ce.byu.edu/cw/fuf/archives/2005/Shirley.Cox.pdf byu.edu].</ref> * '''2006''' – When asked the church's position on [[conversion therapy]] in 2006, Seventy [[Lance B. Wickman|Lance Wickman]] responded that it may be appropriate and the Church doesn't council against it. Oaks also stated that "[t]he Church rarely takes a position on which treatment techniques are appropriate." Wickman and Oaks cautioned against abusive practices, such as [[aversion therapy]].<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> * '''2007''' – In the official church pamphlet "[[God Loveth His Children]]" leaders stated that "many Latter-day Saints, through individual effort, the exercise of faith, and reliance upon the enabling power of the Atonement, overcome same-gender attraction in mortality," and that "we still have the power to resist and reform our feelings (as needed) and to assure that they do not lead us to entertain inappropriate thoughts."<ref name="Women"/>{{rp|46}}<ref name="God Loveth"/>{{rp|3–4,6}}<ref name="Universe Timeline" /> * '''2009''' – A BYU website on LDS FAQ continued to cite a 1986 study stating that through the gospel of Jesus Christ and reparative therapy that homosexual people can "overcome" their sexual orientation through self-mastery by choosing proper role models, developing appropriate relationship skills, clarifying the importance of sexuality, and reassessing gender roles.<ref name="ldsfaq.byu.edu"/><ref name="ReferenceA"/> * '''2009''' – A book authored by mostly BYU professors states that homosexual attractions can be eradicated through therapy.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reid|first1=Kimberly W.|title=Review: Understanding Same-Sex Attraction: Where to Turn and How to Help|journal=BYU Studies|date=2010|volume=49|issue=1|pages=189–190|url=https://byustudies.byu.edu/file/9818/download?token=JF9zBOb0|quote=Instead, the authors of this book assert the unpopular opinion, backed by scientific research, that same-sex attraction can be lessened or eradicated in those who desire change and are willing to try. Readers who empathize with the Church’s position on homosexuality will likely find hope and useful ideas in this five-hundred-page compilation ... Here essayists recount how they emerged from homosexual lifestyles to find satisfaction in rejoining the Church mainstream, some even finding success in heterosexual marriages ... As some professional and state organizations frown on therapists who believe in reorientation therapy—seeking to ban their practice, in some cases—this book fills a void.}}</ref> The book continues to be sold in church-owned bookstores as of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding Same-Sex Attraction: Where to Turn and How to Help (LDS Edition)|url=https://deseretbook.com/p/understanding-same-sex-attraction-where-turn-how-help-lds-edition-various-70458?variant_id=29431-paperback|website=deseretbook.com|publisher=LDS church}}</ref> * '''2010''' – In a survey of 625 Utah individuals, 55% of Mormons believed sexual orientation could be changed.<ref name="Overcome" /> * '''2012''' – Leaders explicitly stated that same-sex sexual attractions were not a choice.<ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|21}} * '''2015''' – A church spokesperson stated that LDS Family Services no longer offers any sexual-orientation change efforts, but are willing to help clients reconcile their attractions and religious beliefs. He also stated that their neutral stance on independent SOCE programs like [[People Can Change|Journey Into Manhood]] should not be taken as an endorsement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fletcher Stack |first1=Peggy |title=Conversion therapies don’t work, experts say, so why do gay Mormons still seek them out? |url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/mormon/2015/10/03/conversion-therapies-dont-work-experts-say-so-why-do-gay-mormons-still-seek-them-out/ |work=The Salt Lake Tribune |date=3 October 2015}}</ref> * '''2015''' – An event hosted by BYU-Idaho faculty member<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Williams|url=https://web.byui.edu/Directory/Employee/williamsmi|website=web.byui.edu|publisher=BYU-Idaho}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Michael|title=Blog|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626023204/http://www.michaelwilliamscounseling.com/?page_id=28|website=michaelwilliamscounseling.com|publisher=Michael Williams Counseling}}</ref> Michael Williamson on "overcoming" homosexuality through private therapy was scheduled to be held on the BYU-Idaho campus and was advertised during church meetings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rolly|first1=Paul|title=Rolly: Mormon congregation at BYU-Idaho scraps plans for gay-conversion-therapy discussion|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3196734&itype=CMSID|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=20 November 2015}}</ref> The event was cancelled, however, after receiving negative press.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Samantha|title=Conversion Therapy Event at BYU-I Axed|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/conversion-therapy-event-at-byu-i-axed|work=Daily Beast|date=16 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Lindsey|title=Local event regarding same-sex attraction canceled and not initiated by BYU-Idaho|url=http://byuiscroll.org/local-event-regarding-same-sex-attraction-canceled-and-not-initiated-by-byu-idaho/|work=BYU-I Scroll|publisher=BYU-Idaho|date=16 November 2015|quote="This event was originally planned to use a [BYU-Idaho] campus classroom ...."}}</ref> At the time BYU-I publicly hosted a video of Williams discussing ways to "treat" same-sex attraction, though, it is now accessible to students only.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview Regarding Treatment of Same Sex Attraction|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117030120/https://video.byui.edu/media/Interview+Regarding+Treatment+of+Same+Sex+Attraction/0_rvq8si0b|website=video.byui.edu|publisher=BYU-Idaho|archive-date=17 November 2015|url=https://video.byui.edu/media/Interview+Regarding+Treatment+of+Same+Sex+Attraction/0_rvq8si0b}}</ref> * '''2015''' – A survey of 1,612 LGBT Mormons and former Mormons found that 73% of men and 43% of women had attempted sexual orientation change, usually through multiple methods across many years.<ref name="SOCE2" />{{rp|5}} * '''2015''' – Counselor-led sexual orientation change efforts dwindled among Mormons.<ref name="Paradigm" />{{rp|17–20}} * '''2016''' – An update<ref>{{cite web|last1=West|first1=Camille|title=Church Updates Resources Addressing Same-Sex Attraction|url=https://www.lds.org/church/news/church-updates-resources-addressing-same-sex-attraction?lang=eng&_r=1|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=4 June 2017}}</ref> to the church's official website stated in reference to [[conversion therapy]] or [[sexual orientation change efforts]] that "it is unethical to focus professional treatment on an assumption that a change in sexual orientation will or must occur,"<ref name="Professional Help">{{cite web|title=Mormon and Gay|url=https://mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/seeking-professional-help|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 2016|quote=While shifts in sexuality can and do occur for some people, it is unethical to focus professional treatment on an assumption that a change in sexual orientation will or must occur. Again, the individual has the right to define the desired outcome.}}</ref> and that "a change in attraction should not be expected or demanded as an outcome by parents or leaders. The intensity of your attractions may not be in your control ...."<ref name="Frequently Asked Questions" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Nico|title=Mormon Church Comes Out Against LGBT Conversion Therapy in New Website|url=https://www.advocate.com/religion/2016/10/26/mormon-church-comes-out-against-lgbt-conversion-therapy-new-website|work=Advocate|date=26 October 2016|quote=The changes in the church’s rhetoric are small but profound. 'Many people pray for years and do all they can to be obedient in an effort to reduce same-sex attraction, yet find they are still attracted to the same sex,' the website reads. 'A change in attraction should not be expected or demanded as an outcome by parents or leaders.' This statement is a reference to conversion therapy, the widely condemned practice of seeking to 'change' the sexuality or gender identity of LGBT youth.}}</ref> * '''2017''' – One gay former Mormon reported his previous religiously motivated efforts to diminish his gay feelings through prayer.<ref>{{cite web|title=This is what it is like to be a closeted gay Mormon and to fall in love with your companion on your mission|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/like-gay-mormon-fall-love-companion-mission/#gs.9nE0dog|website=gaystarnews.com|publisher=Gay Star News Ltd|date=11 August 2017|quote=And over the years that have passed, I have rebuilt myself but it’s been a long road to recover from dangerous messaging. I really did try, but the Church didn’t love me as I was, as I am. And then Elder Perry’s words cut again. ... He said it was like every other temptation. If it was like every other temptation, then why did my hours of praying, my days upon days of tears and anger produce no results in diminishing my attractions? I tried to surround myself with good male role models, but then I found myself gayer than before.}}</ref> * '''2018''' – LDS Family Services states in the church's newspaper that they "do not provide what is commonly referred to as 'reparative therapy' or 'sexual orientation change efforts'" any more.<ref name="Weeds" />
==LGBT Mormon suicides and homelessness== {{Main|LGBT Mormon suicides and homelessness}}
[[File:Depression-loss of loved one.jpg|thumb|150px|left|LGBT persons are at a higher risk of [[Major Depressive Disorder|depression]] and [[suicide]].]] In society at large LGBT individuals [[Suicide among LGBT youth|especially youth]] are at a higher risk of [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] and [[suicide]]<ref>{{cite web|title=LGBT Populations: A Dialogue on Advancing Opportunities for Recovery from Addictions and Mental Health Problems|url=https://store.samhsa.gov/shin/content/SMA13-4774/SMA13-4774.pdf|website=samhsa.gov|publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration Center for Mental Health Services|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Program aims to stop suicide, homelessness in LGBT Mormon youth|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/sltrib/lifestyle/57682784-80/lgbt-ryan-youth-family.html.csp|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=15 March 2014}}</ref> due to [[minority stress]] stemming from [[Societal attitudes toward homosexuality|societal anti-LGBT biases]] and [[Homophobia|stigma]], rejection, and [[Homophobia#Internalized homophobia|internalized homophobia]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Meyer|first1=Ilan H.|last2=Northridge|first2=Mary E.|title=The Health of Sexual Minorities|date=2007|publisher=Springer|location=US|isbn=978-0-387-31334-4|pages=242–247|edition=1|url=https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007%2F978-0-387-31334-4|accessdate=15 January 2017}}</ref> Some individuals and organizations have linked church teachings against homosexuality and the treatment of LGBT Mormons by other members and leaders as contributing to LGBT Mormon suicides.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Suicide fears, if not actual suicides, rise in wake of Mormon same-sex policy|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/lds/3473487-155/suicide-fears-if-not-actual-suicides|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=28 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Parkinson|first1=Daniel|last2=Barker|first2=Michael|title=The LGBTQ Mormon Crisis: Responding to the Empirical Research on Suicide|url=http://rationalfaiths.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/LGBTQCrisis_web.pdf|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Greene|first1=David|title=Mama Dragons Try To Prevent Suicides Among Mormon-LGBT Children|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/07/07/485058737/mama-dragons-try-to-prevent-suicides-among-mormon-lgbt-children|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=NPR|date=7 July 2016}}</ref> LGBT Mormon suicides and experiences with suicidal ideation have received media coverage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jackson|first1=Lauren|title=Devotion and despair: The lonely struggle of a gay Mormon|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/16/living/gay-mormon-struggle/|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=CNN|date=19 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Samuels|first1=Diana|title=Memorial held for gay Mormon who committed suicide in Los Altos|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/02/25/memorial-held-for-gay-mormon-who-committed-suicide-in-los-altos/|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=The Mercury News|date=25 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Carrie A.|title=Alone in the fold: Many LDS gays struggle to cling to faith despite their yearnings|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/635165814/Alone-in-the-fold-Many-LDS-gays-struggle-to-cling-to-faith-despite-their-yearnings.html?pg=all|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=Deseret News|publisher=LDS Church}}</ref>
In 2013 It was estimated that among the approximately 1000 homeless Utah youths, 30% to 40% were LGBTQ with about half of those coming from LDS homes<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Ray|title=Groups team up to reach out to homeless LGBT Mormon youths|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/sltrib/news/55659498-78/homeless-youths-lgbt-youth.html.csp|accessdate=5 February 2017|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=25 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moore|first1=Chadwick|title=The Ghost Children of Mormon Country|journal=Advocate|date=29 April 2016|url=http://www.advocate.com/current-issue/2016/4/29/ghost-children-mormon-country|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> The Ogden, Utah OUTreach Resource Center has reported that over half of their often homeless youth clients identify as LGBTQ.<ref>{{cite web|title=LGBTQ Youth|url=https://www.equalityutah.org/issues/lgbt-youth|website=Equality Utah|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> In the large 2012 survey "Growing Up LGBT in America" over two-thirds of LGBT youth in Utah reported not feeling accepted in their community, compared to 42% of LGBT youth nationwide, and 3/4 said they would need to leave Utah to feel accepted.<ref>{{cite news|title=End the abuse of LGBT teens in Utah|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/765582449/End-the-abuse-of-LGBT-teens-in-Utah.html?pg=all|work=Deseret News|agency=LDS Church|date=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rogers|first1=Melinda|title=LGBT youth find safe haven at homeless drop-in center|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=54274630&itype=CMSID|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=10 June 2012}}</ref> In January 2016 the LDS church mourned over reported suicides of LGBT Mormons and stated that leaders and members are taught to "reach out in an active, caring way to all, especially to youth who feel estranged or isolated."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walch|first1=Tad|last2=Collins|first2=Lois M.|title=LDS Church leaders mourn reported deaths in Mormon LGBT community|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865646414/LDS-Church-leaders-mourn-reported-deaths-in-Mormon-LGBT-community.html?pg=all|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=Deseret News|publisher=LDS Church|date=28 January 2016}}</ref> The Affirmation website reported over 30 LGBT Mormon victims of suicide between 1971 and 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Suicide Memorial |url=http://www.affirmation.org/suicides/ |website=affirmation.org |publisher=Affirmation |accessdate=29 November 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140117055228/http://www.affirmation.org/suicides/ |archivedate=January 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Forum Discusses Suicide Prevention Among Mormons|journal=Sunstone Magazine|date=December 2002|issue=125|page=79|url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/pdf/125-75-79.pdf#page=5|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref> including five gay male BYU students who all completed suicide in 1965.<ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|156}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McQueen |first1=Robert |title=Outside the Temple Gates-The Gay Mormon |journal=The Advocate |date=13 August 1975 |page=14 |url=http://affirmation.org/suicides/1965.shtml |accessdate=29 November 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719220413/http://affirmation.org/suicides/1965.shtml |archivedate=July 19, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>
==LGBT Mormon people and organizations== {{Main|LGBT Mormon people and organizations}} {{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | total_width = 200 | width1 = 362 | height1 = 89 | image1 = | width2 = 555 | height2 = 231 | image2 = Affirmation Logo.png | width3 = 512 | height3 = 181 | image3 = MBB Logo.jpg | footer = Some principle homosexual Mormon groups }} Though there are no official numbers for how many members of the LDS Church identify their romantic orientation as gay, bisexual, or lesbian, BYU's newspaper cited two LDS therapists who stated in 2003 that the supermajority-Mormon BYU student body is "somewhere around 4 to 5 percent" homosexual.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Herbst |first1=Casi |title=Homosexuality broadcast axed |url=http://universe.byu.edu/2003/01/16/homosexuality-broadcast-axed/ |work=The Daily Universe |agency=LDS Church |publisher=BYU |date=16 January 2003 |quote=[Jeff] Robinson, a marriage and family counselor in Orem whose caseload is approximately 90 percent homosexual men ... said there are approximately 2 to 3 percent homosexual men worldwide. Mike Buxton, a counselor at BYU who deals with many of the people on campus with this tendency, said this statistic pertains to homosexual women and the number for men dealing with homosexuality is 4 to 5 percent worldwide. Both agree the number of BYU students dealing with homosexuality is somewhere around 4 to 5 percent.}}</ref> [[LDS Family Services]] estimates that there are, on average, four or five members per [[Ward (LDS Church)|church ward]] who experience same-sex attraction.<ref>{{citation |publisher= Evergreen International |url= http://www.evergreeninternational.org/Individuals.htm |title= Resources for Individuals |work= EvergreenInternational.org |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121120213658/http://www.evergreeninternational.org/Individuals.htm |archivedate= November 20, 2012}}</ref> The most recent external study, conducted in 1972, shows that between 10–13 percent of college-aged Mormon men reported past experimentation with homosexual behavior, which was similar to the percentage of non-Mormon men who similarly reported. The study did not tabulate the number of homosexuals who had never had a homosexual experience.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://content.lib.utah.edu/u?/dialogue,5495|title=Morman Sex Standards on College campusus, or Deal Us Out of the Sexual Revolution!|first=Wilford E.|last=Smith|journal=[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]|volume=10|issue=2|pages=76–81|date=Autumn 1976}}</ref> Another poll of BYU students in 1997 found that 10% had a gay family member and 69% knew someone attracted to those of the same sex.<ref name="Clayton">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher Stack|first1=Peggy|title=42 Percent At BYU Want Gays Kept Out; Gays Unwelcome, Say Many at BYU|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=9 November 1997|via=ProQuest Newsstand|quote=In the first study, BYU student Samuel Clayton, with the help of several faculty members, gave questionnaires anonymously to 420 students in randomly selected classes. ... Some of Clayton's findings include: 69 percent know someone who is same-sex oriented, 12 percent have a family member who is same-sex oriented, 24 percent would avoid befriending a same-sex-oriented student, 56 percent believe same-sex-oriented students should be allowed to attend BYU if they obey the honor code. Clayton said there was 'a significant gender gap ... Only 16 percent of women would avoid befriending a same-sex-oriented person, compared to 33 percent of men.}}</ref> Gary Watts, former president of [[Family Fellowship]], estimates that only 10 percent of homosexual Mormons remain in the church.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.insidebayarea.com/oaklandtribune/ci_6668882|title=Mormon church changes stance on homosexuality; New teachings say lifelong celibacy to be rewarded with heterosexuality in heaven|first=Rebecca Rosen|last=Lum|date=August 20, 2007|publisher=''[[The Oakland Tribune]]''|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> Others dispute that estimate, saying numbers in support groups for active Latter-day Saints and for [[Coming out|self-identified gay]] Mormons are comparable.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} There is a variety of terminology used, including "Moho", to refer to a Mormon homosexual.<ref name="CNN 2011-09-24">{{citation|url=http://religion.blogs.cnn.com/2011/09/24/church-leadership-post-for-an-openly-gay-mormon/|contribution=Church leadership post for an openly gay Mormon|title=CNN Belief Blog|first=Jessica|last=Ravitz|date=September 24, 2011|publisher=CNN}}</ref>
{{multiple image | align = vertical | total_width = 300 | width1 = 276 | height1 = 362 | image1 = | width2 = 4113 | height2 = 2742 | image2 = Tyler Glenn of Neon Trees.jpg | width3 = 1444 | height3 = 2144 | image3 = Katekendell.jpg | footer = Some nationally recognized LGBT former Mormons (from left to right: [[Leonard Matlovich]], [[Tyler Glenn]], and [[Kate Kendell]]). }} Prominent LGBT or homosexually attracted Mormons include Elder Christofferson's brother Tom Christofferson, therapist Ty Mansfield, therapist David Matheson, and therapist Josh Weed. Prominent LGBT former Mormons include writer [[Dustin Lance Black]], singer [[Tyler Glenn]], historian [[D. Michael Quinn]], gay rights activist [[Leonard Matlovich]], and attorney [[Kate Kendell]]. Organization that have supported Mormons and former Mormons that experience attractions to those of the same sex include [[Affirmation: Gay & Lesbian Mormons|Affirmation]], [[North Star (organization)|North Star]], [[Mormons Building Bridges]], [[Mama Dragons]], [[Evergreen International]], [[Understanding Same-Gender Attraction|USGA]]. Break-off churches for LGBT Mormons include the [[United Order Family of Christ]] in the 70s and the [[Restoration Church of Jesus Christ]] by [[Antonio A. Feliz|Antonio Feliz]] from the 80s to 2010.
===Depiction in pop culture and media=== {{See also|Latter Day Saints in popular culture}} LGBT Mormon characters and themes have been featured in many films, plays, and pieces of literature. Examples include the audiovisual works ''[[Latter Days]]'', ''[[Believer (2018)|Believer]]'', ''[[8: The Mormon Proposition]]'', TLC's ''My Husband's Not Gay'',<ref>{{cite news | author=Neil Genzlinger | title=Where Being in Denial Is Right at Home | work=[[New York Times]] | date=January 7, 2015 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/08/arts/my-husbands-not-gay-a-special-set-in-mormon-utah-on-tlc.html | accessdate=May 18, 2015}}</ref> the plays ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|Book of Mormon musical]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Troy|title=Welcome to the Gayborhood|url=http://slmag.com/blog/welcome-to-the-gayborhood/|website=slmag.com|publisher=Salt Lake Magazine|date=19 April 2012|quote=The destinies of Mormons and gays were becoming intertwined in the national discourse, providing creative fodder for theatrical productions including the 2011 Tony Award winner 'The Book of Mormon' in which Elder McKinnley, echoing the teachings of Boyd K. Packer, would encourage other gay Mormons to 'Turn it off' like a light switch.}}</ref> ''[[Angels in America]]'', ''[[8 (play)|8]]'', ''14'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Archive of "14"|url=https://theatre.uiowa.edu/production/past-shows/archive-14|website=theatre.uiowa.edu|publisher=University of Iowa}}</ref> ''[[G.B.F. (film)|G.B.F.]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levithan|first1=David|last2=Stein|first2=Darren|title=David Levithan and filmmaker Darren Stein in conversation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2014/may/16/david-levithan-darren-stein-ya-books-films-gay-characters|work=The Guardian|date=16 May 2014|quote=The film skewers the ridiculousness of teen girls wanting a GBF (Gay Best Friend) like an accessory or trend, but it also skewers ethnicity, religion, clique culture. I wanted the scenes where the closeted Mormon Topher seduces Tanner and Brent to be sexy and provocative; I've never thought it was fair that it's fine to have a romantic or sexual male-female kiss but when it comes to two boys kissing, it's so chaste and unsexual.}}</ref> ''Facing East'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clements|first1=Derrick|title='Facing East' explores rift in LGBT, LDS community|url=http://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/arts-and-theater/theater/facing-east-explores-rift-in-lgbt-lds-community/article_1abe9526-cc2a-55ab-ad4a-b9493e29343f.html|work=The Daily Herald|date=3 November 2016}}</ref> ''Confessions of a Mormon Boy'', ''Missa Solemnis or The Play About Henry'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fagg|first1=Ellen|title=Plays about gay Mormons attracting audiences nationally|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=8574767&itype=NGPSID|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=15 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Play Focuses on Gay Mormon Suicide|url=https://qsaltlake.com/news/2008/02/05/new-play-focuses-on-gay-mormon-suicide/|work=QSaltLake|date=5 February 2008}}</ref> and the novel ''[[Advise and Consent]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=J. Seth|title=LGBT Salt Lake: Images of Modern America|date=29 May 2017|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=9781467125857|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rlC1DgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT16&pg=PT34#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kotraba|first1=Kellie|title=Gay Mormon characters step out of the shadows|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-faith/gay-mormon-characters-step-out-of-the-shadows/2013/05/22/a04903e2-c310-11e2-9642-a56177f1cdf7_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=22 May 2013}}</ref>
==Timeline of important publications and speeches== {{Main|Timeline of LGBT Mormon history}}
===1800s to the 1950s=== [[File:MormonDoctrineCover2ndEdition1966.jpg|thumb|right|150px|This highly influential [[Mormon Doctrine (book)|publication]] was the first general-authority-authored book to explicitly contain church stances on homosexuality.]] * '''1897''' – During the October general conference, [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] member [[George Q. Cannon]] used the media attention on the 1895 conviction and two-year imprisonment of famed Irish poet [[Oscar Wilde]] as an opportunity to condemn homosexual behavior as an abominable, filthy, nameless crime. He continued stating that the only way to stop homosexuals was for God to wipe them out.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cannon|first1=George|title=Sixty-Eighth Semi-Annual Conference|date=6 Oct 1897|publisher=Deseret News Publishing Company|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=65–66|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/329715180/1897-Conference-George-Q-Cannon-Oct-6|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Immorality Deplored: President Cannon Pictures Existing Evil Conditions|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/351519819/George-Q-Cannon-October-Conference-Nameless-Crime-Salt-Lake-Tribune-7-Oct-1897|accessdate=17 June 2017|page=1|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=7 October 1897}}</ref> * '''1952''' – An increase in US public discourse around homosexuality in the [[McCarthyism|McCarthyist]] [[Lavender scare]] era contributed to the first explicit mention of the topic in general conference. Apostle [[J. Reuben Clark|Clark]] lamented homosexuality is found among men and women, and that homosexual people exercise great influence in shaping culture.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clark|first1=J. Reuben|title=Home and the Building of Home Life|journal=Relief Society Magazine|date=2 October 1952|pages=793–794|url=https://www.docdroid.net/krpGx1s/j-reuben-clark-2-october-1952-home-and-the-building-of-home-life.pdf|accessdate=3 November 2016|quote=... [T]he crimes for which Sodom and Gomorrah were destroyed—we have coined a softer name for them than came from old; we now speak of homosexuality, which, it is tragic to say, is found among both sexes. ...Not without foundation is the contention of some that the homosexuals are today exercising great influence in shaping our art, literature, music, and drama.}}</ref><ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|146}} * '''1958''' – [[General authority]] [[Bruce R. McConkie]] published ''[[Mormon Doctrine (book)|Mormon Doctrine]]'', in which he states that homosexuality is among Lucifer's chief means of leading souls to hell. In the section on Chastity he stated that it's better to be dead clean, than alive unclean.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McConkie|first1=Bruce R.|title=Mormon Doctrine|date=1958|publisher=Deseret Book}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|375}}
===1960s=== * '''1964''' – Apostle [[Spencer W. Kimball|Spencer Kimball]] called homosexuality a malady, disease, and an abominable and detestable crime against nature that was curable by self mastery.<ref name="Through the Years">{{cite news|last1=Bracken|first1=Seth|title=Through the Years|url=https://issuu.com/qsaltlake/docs/qsl110414e|publisher=Q Salt Lake|date=14 April 2011}}</ref> He cited one lay [[bishop (Latter Day Saints)|bishop]] (a businessman by trade) assigned by the church to administer a program of rehabilitation through which he claimed there had been numerous "cures." He said the police, the courts, and the judges had referred many cases directly to the church.<ref name="Counselling"/><ref name="Lavender">{{cite book|last1=Winkler|first1=Douglas A.|title=Lavender Sons of Zion: A History of Gay Men in Salt Lake City, 1950--1979|date=May 2008|publisher=University of Utah Department of History|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Lavender_Sons_of_Zion.html?id=7mMnAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>{{rp|91}} [[File:LDS_General_Handbook_1968.png|right|thumb|125px|upright|The 1968 leader handbook was the first release to explicitly mention homosexuality.]] * '''1965''' – [[Spencer W. Kimball|Kimball]] again addressed homosexuality in his BYU speech "Love vs. Lust." He called it a gross, heinous, obnoxious, abominable, vicious sin. The text states that those with homosexual desires could correct and overcome them like the cure for alcoholism. In the speech he stated BYU will never knowingly enroll nor tolerate anyone with these tendencies who fails to repent, and that it is a damnable heresy for a homosexual person to say that God made them that way. He also stated that sometimes masturbation is an introduction to homosexuality.<ref name=Kimball-1965>{{Citation|last=Kimball|first=Spencer W|chapter=Love vs. Lust|date=January 5, 1965|title=BYU Speeches of the Year|url=https://speeches.byu.edu/talks/spencer-w-kimball_love-vs-lust/}}. [https://web.archive.org/web/20030519075029/http://mentalhealthlibrary.info/library/same/samelds/samelds2001/links/kimball/kimball.htm Transcript reprint with permission by the Mental Health Resource Foundation at mentalhealthlibrary.info]. Note: References to homosexuality were removed in the reprinted version of the speech in the 1972 book compilation of Kimball's speeches "Faith Precedes the Miracle."</ref><ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|149}} * '''1965''' – [[Ernest L. Wilkinson]], addressed the BYU student body stating a ban on students with homosexual feelings since they contaminate the campus.<ref name="Make Honor Your Standard">{{cite book|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Ernest|title=Make Honor Your Standard|date=23 Sep 1965|publisher=Brigham Young University|page=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Ernest|title=Make Honor Your Standard|journal=Deseret News: Church News|date=13 Nov 1965|page=11}}</ref><ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|154}} [[File:The Miracle of Forgiveness Title Page.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Spencer W. Kimball|Kimball's]] influential book taught that homosexuality was curable and was officially recommended as a resource for homosexual members into the 90s.<ref name="lds92" />{{rp|2}}]] * '''1968''' – A version of the ''[[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]]'' was released containing the first explicit mention of homosexuality, specifying that homo-sexual (sic) acts require a [[disciplinary council|church court]].<ref>{{cite book|title=General Handbook of Instructions|date=1968|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=122|edition=20}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|380}} * '''1969''' – Kimball released his book ''[[The Miracle of Forgiveness]]'', in which he teaches that masturbation can lead to acts of homosexuality. His book was quoted in a 1979 church manual where it states that homosexuality is curable and certainly overcome as long as the person continues knocking at the door to a cure until their knuckles are bloody.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bering|first1=Jesse|title=The Devil Makes You Gay: The Mormon Church and Its Homosexual Misfits|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/bering-in-mind/the-devil-makes-you-gay-the-lds-church-and-its-homosexual-misfits/|website=blogs.scientificamerican.com|publisher=Scientific American|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Life and Teachings of Jesus and His Apostles|date=1979|publisher=LDS Church|pages=314–21|url=//www.lds.org/manual/the-life-and-teachings-of-jesus-and-his-apostles/section-8-pauls-witness-as-a-missionary/chapter-39-man-is-justified-by-faith|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> Kimball viewed many homosexuals as basically good people trapped in sin and posited that some totally conquer homosexuality in a few months, but sometimes leads to [[Zoophilia|sex with animals]].<ref name="Miracle" />
===1970s=== * '''1970''' – [[Victor L. Brown|Victor Brown]] of the Presiding Bishopric gave an April general conference address in which he states that a normal and healthy 12- or 13-year-old boy or girl could develop into a homosexual if exposed to pornographic literature and other abnormalities.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Victor L.|title=Wanted: Parents With Courage|date=April 1970|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=31–33|url=http://scriptures.byu.edu/gettalk.php?ID=1751|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=One Hundred Fortieth Annual Conference With Report of Discourses|date=April 1970|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=31–32|url=http://scriptures.byu.edu/gc-historical/1970-A.pdf}}</ref><ref name="Sympathy">{{cite journal|last1=Cragun|first1=Ryan T.|last2=Williams|first2=Emily|last3=Sumerau|first3=J. E.|title=From Sodomy to Sympathy: LDS Elites’ Discursive Construction of Homosexuality Over Time|journal=Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion|date=May 2015|volume=54|issue=2|doi=10.1111/jssr.12180|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/wol1/doi/10.1111/jssr.12180/abstract|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|297}} [[File:Spencer W. Kimball3.JPG|thumb|upright|right|[[Spencer W. Kimball|Spencer Kimball]] was assigned as a church specialist on homosexuality in 1946<ref name="Bookcraft" />{{rp|381}} and shaped church teachings on the subject through numerous speeches and publications in the '60s and '70s.]] * '''1970''' – The church produced ''Hope for Transgressors'',<ref name="Hope" >{{Cite book|last1=Kimball|first1=Spencer|author1-link=Spencer W. Kimball|last2=Petersen|first2=Mark|author2-link=Mark E. Petersen|title=Hope for Transgressors|year=1970|publisher=LDS Church|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/329822240/Hope-for-Transgressors}}</ref> in which apostles [[Spencer W. Kimball|Spencer Kimball]] and [[Mark E. Petersen|Mark Petersen]] offer ideas to leaders about how to effect a total "cure" and bring the lives of men with homosexual feelings into total normalcy. Ideas include prayer, cutting off contact with homosexual friends, dating women, marriage,<ref name="Through the Years"/> and scripture reading. He calls homosexuality a despicable, degraded, dread practice, and a perversion that would doom the world, though calling the homosexual individual an afflicted one. The guide notes that Kimball and Petersen were designated as the church specialists on homosexuality, and that homosexuality is not totally the fault of family conditions and concludes it "CAN be cured" (emphasis in the original).<ref name=KimballPetersen1970 /> [[File:Kimball 1970s Booklets on Homosexuality.png|thumb|right|140px|Booklet revisions of [[Spencer W. Kimball|Kimball's]] influential '70s discourse on homosexuality (from the top: '70, '71, '78).<ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|147}}]] * '''1971''' – Apostle [[Spencer W. Kimball|Kimball]] revised and retitled ''Hope for Transgressors'' as a 34-page letter from to homosexual men titled ''New Horizons for Homosexuals''. In it he calls homosexuality a ruinous practice of perversion that the church will never condone that begins with curiosity. He states that saying perverts are born that way is a base lie since homosexuality is curable and can be overcome and recovered from. It also calls homosexuality ugly, degenerate, unnatural, vicious, base, a waste of power, a deep sin, and an end to the family and civilization."<ref name="Obscurity" />{{rp|149}} The publication advises that for the homosexual to recover they must shun anyone associated with the transgression and pray and read the scriptures.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kimball|first1=Spencer W.|title=New Horizons for Homosexuals|date=July 1971|publisher=Deseret News Press, LDS Church}}</ref> The pamphlet would be reissued in 1978 as a 30-page pamphlet titled ''A Letter to a Friend''.<ref name="Multiply"/>{{rp|147}} [[File:Homosexuality Welfare Services Packet 1.png|thumb|140px|A 1973 church publication which taught that a passive father and domineering mother can cause homosexuality, and that conforming to gender norms will change it.]] * '''1973''' – The church published a guide for [[bishop (Latter Day Saints)|bishops]] and [[stake president]]s titled "Homosexuality: Welfare Services Packet 1", which posited that homosexual behavior begins by being molested with the note that not all who are molested become homosexual. It also suggested that homosexuality is caused by a domineering mother and a passive father. As far as changing the sexual orientation of the person, the packet says that the lesbian needs to learn feminine behavior, and the gay man must learn the manly, heterosexual, or straight way of life.<ref name="Lavender" />{{rp|91}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=White|first1=Edmund|title=States of Desire Revisited: Travels in Gay America|date=18 September 2014|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, WI|isbn=0299302644|page=106|edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9IRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA106&lpg=PA106&dq=Homosexuality+Welfare+Services+Packet&source=bl&ots=qg8IrYkDT0&sig=tNLZZmWhUV1GzhE7Cfidd21QP_w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjI0IfxnMbUAhWk6IMKHV2sDn8Q6AEIRjAH#v=onepage&q=Homosexuality%20Welfare%20Services%20Packet&f=false|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="Welfare" /> * '''1974''' – New Church president [[Spencer W. Kimball|Spencer Kimball]] gave an October [[General conference (Latter Day Saints)|general conference]] speech in which he again stated that masturbation leads to homosexuality, and also added pornography can as well.<ref name="Othering" />{{rp|342–343}}<ref name="GodWillNotBeMocked">{{Citation|last=Kimball|first=Spencer W.|author-link=Spencer W. Kimball|title=God Will Not Be Mocked|year=1974|url= //www.lds.org/general-conference/1974/10/god-will-not-be-mocked}}</ref> * '''1975''' – The Ensign published an article by Presiding bishop [[Victor L. Brown|Victor Brown]] which addressed parents stating that a "lack of proper affection in the home" can result in homosexual children.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Victor|title=Two Views of Sexuality|url=https://www.lds.org/ensign/1975/07/two-views-of-sexuality?lang=eng|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church}}</ref><ref name="Othering">{{cite journal|last1=Sumerau|first1=J. Edward|last2=Cragun|first2=Ryan T.|title="Why Would Our Heavenly Father Do that to Anyone": Oppressive Othering through Sexual Classification Schemes in the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints|journal=Symbolic Interaction|date=1 August 2014|volume=37|issue=3|doi=10.1002/symb.105|url=https://www.academia.edu/31637678/_Why_Would_Our_Heavenly_Father_Do_that_to_Anyone_Oppressive_Othering_through_Sexual_Classification_Schemes_in_the_Church_of_Jesus_Christ_of_Latter-Day_Saints?auto=download|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|339}} [[File:LDS Family Services logo.svg|thumb|upright|right|Members of [[LDS Family Services|LDS Social Services]] (renamed "LDS Family Services" in '95) were tasked with treating homosexual Mormons in 1972<ref name="Flesh">{{cite journal|last1=Swedin|first1=Eric G.|title='One Flesh': A Historical Overview of Latter-day Saint Sexuality and Psychology|journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|date=Winter 1998|volume=31|issue=4|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V31N04_17.pdf|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref>{{rp|15}} and produced several important publications on homosexuality in '73, '95, and '99.]] * '''1975''' – Robert L. Blattner of [[LDS Family Services#History|LDS Social Services]] gave an address at the Association of Mormon Counselors and Psychotherapists (AMCAP) annual conference. Blattner served as a special assistant to the LDS Commissioner of Personal Welfare Victor L. Brown Jr.<ref name="Flesh" />{{rp|15}} In the address Blattner states that the causes of homosexuality in men are a lack of relationship with peers and a disturbed family background with an absent father and controlling mother. For the causes of female homosexuality he only notes the lack of information. He said homosexual behavior and alcoholism are similar and noted that most people can be helped by [[Aversion therapy|electric shock]] behavior modification in reference to [[Brigham Young University LGBT history#Aversion therapy at BYU|BYU's aversion therapy program]].<ref name="ojs.lib.byu.edu">{{cite journal|last1=Blattner|first1=Robert L.|title=Counseling the Homosexual In A Church Setting|journal=Issues in Religion and Psychotherapy|date=1975|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1–3|url=http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/irp/vol1/iss1/2/|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="University of Illinois Press">{{cite book|last1=Swedin|first1=Eric G.|title=Healing Souls: Psychotherapy in the Latter-day Saint Community|date=17 September 2003|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=0252028643|pages=164–165|edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kPu6ngqY9R0C&pg=PA217&lpg=PA217&dq=counseling+the+homosexual+in+a+church+setting+blattner&source=bl&ots=9-jLQYCWFV&sig=qIFkZ8Pwa_F9PQroNxD2xD-8NLk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLmMev6afQAhUFsFQKHRq0DSwQ6AEIPDAE#v=onepage&q=blattner&f=false|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> * '''1976''' – A version of the [[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]] was released changing the previous grounds for a [[Disciplinary council|church court]] from "homo-sexual (sic) acts" to "homosexuality."<ref>{{cite book|title=General Handbook of Instructions|publisher=LDS CHurch|page=71|edition=21}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bush Jr.|first1=Lester E.|title=Excommunication and Church Courts: A Note From the General Handbook of Instructions|journal=Dialogue|date=Summer 1981|volume=14|issue=2|page=84|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/archive/issue-details/?in=54|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> This change seemed to make Mormons vulnerable to church punishment for having a homosexual orientation alone even without sexual activity.<ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|382}} [[File:Boyd K. Packer.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Apostle [[Boyd K. Packer|Boyd Packer]] played a large role in shaping over three decades of teachings on homosexuality through numerous speeches containing the subject.]] * '''1976''' – Apostle [[Boyd K. Packer|Boyd Packer]] gave the sermon "[[To Young Men Only]]" in the October general conference. The sermon counseled against perverse physical contact between men. Packer commended a missionary who was upset after he floored (i.e. punched so hard he fell to the ground) his assigned male companion in response to unwanted sexual advances, saying "somebody had to do it."<ref name="Through the Years"/> He further asserted that it is a lie that some are born with homosexual attractions. The sermon was published as a pamphlet by the church from 1980 to 2016.<ref name=TYMO/><ref name = "2016retired">[[Peggy Fletcher Stack]], [http://www.sltrib.com/home/4584556-155/lds-church-retires-mormon-apostles-little "LDS Church 'retires' Mormon apostle's 'little factory' pamphlet"], ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]'', November 14, 2016.</ref> [[File:ToTheOneCover.png|thumb|140px|Pamphlet containing apostle [[Boyd K. Packer|Packer's]] 1978 BYU speech on homosexuality.]] * '''1978''' – Apostle [[Boyd K. Packer|Packer]] delivered the sermon "To the One" at BYU<ref name="2the1">{{cite book|last1=Packer|first1=Boyd K.|title=To The One|date=1978|publisher=LDS Church|url=https://search.lib.byu.edu/byu/record/lee.1613807?holding=44katdaofhqrw8qd}}</ref> in response to the recent controversy generated from a widely circulated pro-gay pamphlet by a gay BYU student and gay BYU instructor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaysaltlake.com/news/2010/12/23/the-payne-papers/|title=Lamba Lore: The Payne Papers|last1=Williams|first1=Ben|date=|website=gaysaltlake.com|publisher=QSaltLake Magazine|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name="Multiply" />{{rp|157–159}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Huffaker|first1=Dean|title=Homosexuality at BYU|journal=Seventh East Press|date=12 April 1982|volume=1|issue=15|page=1|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/331797896/Homosexuality-at-BYU-1980-s-Reported-in-Seventh-East-Press-Newspaper|accessdate=21 November 2016}} Text reprinted at [https://web.archive.org/web/20080701125938/http://www.affirmation.org/memorial/homosexuality_at_byu_2.shtml affirmation.org]</ref> He characterized homosexual interaction as a perversion and presented the possibility that it had its roots in selfishness and could be cured with unselfish thoughts and acts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hansen|first1=Thayne|title=Cure for Homosexuality Discussed by Elder Packer|work=The Daily Universe|agency=Brigham Young University|date=6 March 1978}}</ref><ref name="2the1" />{{rp|6}} He stated that homosexuality was not discussed much by publicly by the church since talking about it can very foolishly cause things leaders are trying to prevent.<ref name="2the1" />{{rp|19}} * '''1978''' – The [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] released a statement outlining reasons for their opposition to the [[Equal Rights Amendment]] including unnatural consequences like an increase in the practice of homosexual and lesbian activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Presidency Reaffirms Opposition to ERA|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/1978/10/news-of-the-church/first-presidency-reaffirms-opposition-to-era|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Obscurity" />{{rp|150–151}}
===1980s=== [[File:STOP_ERA.gif|thumb|right|175px|The church opposed the [[Equal Rights Amendment|ERA]] in part from believing it would lead to same-sex marriage and parenting.<ref name="lds.org">{{cite journal|title=The Church and the Proposed Equal Rights Amendment: A Moral Issue|journal=[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]|date=March 1980|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/1980/03/the-church-and-the-proposed-equal-rights-amendment-a-moral-issue|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>]] * '''1980''' – The ''Ensign'' published an article stating that a passing of the [[Equal Rights Amendment]] would lead to legalizing same-sex marriage and children being raised in a homosexual home.<ref name="lds.org"/><ref name="Obscurity" />{{rp|151}} * '''1981''' – In an April General Conference, church Seventy [[Hartman Rector Jr.]] stated "If children have a happy family experience they will not want to be homosexual", and that homosexuality is an acquired addiction like drugs and pornography.<ref name="Turning the Hearts">{{cite web|last1=Rector Jr.|first1=Hartman|title=Turning the Hearts|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K2KLpASKc2A#t=6m47s|website=Youtube.com|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="sunstonemagazine.com">{{cite journal|last1=Geisner|first1=Joseph|title=Very Careless In His Utterances: Editing, Correcting, and Censoring Conference Addresses|journal=Sunstone Magazine|date=December 2011|issue=165|pages=14–24|url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/magazine/premium-issues/|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mormon Church Elder Calls Homosexuality an Addiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/04/06/us/around-the-nation-mormon-church-elder-calls-homosexuality-an-addiction.html|accessdate=19 July 2017|work=New York Times|agency=Advanced Press|date=6 April 1981}}</ref> * '''1981''' – The church issued a guide for [[LDS Family Services|LDS Social Services]] employees instructing them that a homosexual orientation is not inborn and there is hope of change, as well as stating that a homosexual man is afraid of the other sex and does not fully understand how to act and think like a masculine man.<ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite book|title=Understanding and Changing Homosexual Orientation Problems|date=1981|publisher=LDS Church|url=https://search.lib.byu.edu/byu/record/lee.2255698}}</ref><ref name="Flesh" />{{rp|20}} [[File:Homosexuality_LDS_Manual_1981.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Cover of a 1981 church manual which taught homosexuality wasn't inborn, but caused by masturbation or an unhealthy childhood, and was changeable through praying, and heterosexual dating.<ref name="Homosexuality">{{cite book|title=Homosexuality|date=1981|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, UT|url=https://search.lib.byu.edu/byu/record/lee.786190?holding=ey812d1gmuud6iry|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|51}}]] * '''1981''' – Another church guide was released for local church leaders which stated that homosexual inclinations are changeable and not inborn. The booklet gave guidelines for the treatment and prevention of homosexuality such as dating, praying, and reading church literature. It taught that homosexual behavior is learned and influenced by an unhealthy childhood, masturbation, and experimentation.<ref name="Homosexuality"/><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|51}}<ref name="Masturbation">{{cite news|last1=Maza|first1=Christina|title=Masturbation Will Make You Gay, Warns Leaked Mormon Church Document|url=http://www.newsweek.com/masturbation-gay-leaked-mormon-church-lgtb-religion-sex-748201|work=Newsweek|publisher=Newsweek Media Group|date=14 December 2017}}</ref> * '''1983''' – The ''[[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]]'' was updated to state that a [[Disciplinary council|church court]] may be convened to consider serious transgressions including homosexuality and lesbianism but is not required.<ref>{{cite book|title=General Handbook of Instructions|date=1983|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=51}}</ref> Some leaders punished even celibate people who confessed to experiencing homosexual feelings.<ref name="Decisions">{{cite journal|last1=Schow|first1=Ron|title=Homosexual Attractions and LDS Marriage Decisions|journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|date=Fall 2005|volume=38|issue=3|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V38N03_145.pdf|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|139}} * '''1986''' – Dallin H. Oaks commented on a CBS-TV interview that marriage is not doctrinal therapy for homosexual relations, and that he did not know if any leaders had advised homosexual individuals to enter [[mixed-orientation marriage]]s.<ref name="Brigham Young University">{{cite web|title=Encyclopedia of Mormonism: Homosexuality|url=http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/EoM/id/4391/rec/1|website=BYU HBLL Digital Collections|publisher=Brigham Young University|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Dynamics" />{{rp|393}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=LDS Policy on Homosexuality Reaffirmed during CBS TV Interview|journal=Deseret News: Church News|date=14 February 1987|page=12}}</ref> * '''1987''' – [[Gordon B. Hinckley]] of the First Presidency gave an April conference address in which he stated, marriage should not be viewed as a therapeutic step to solve problems such as homosexual inclinations or practices."<ref name="Sympathy" />{{rp|13}}<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hinckley|first1=Gordon|title=Reverence and Morality|url=//www.lds.org/general-conference/1987/04/reverence-and-morality|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref> * '''1989''' – The ''[[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]]'' was updated to clarify offenses as homosexual relations rather than just homosexuality itself.<ref name="Decisions" />{{rp|139}} Additionally the update required a [[Disciplinary council|church court]] for any homosexual activity by a member holding a prominent church position such as a bishop.<ref>{{cite book|title=General Handbook of Instructions|date=1989|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=10–4}}</ref>
=== 1990s === * '''1990''' – A version of the "[[For the Strength of Youth]]" pamphlet first mentioned homosexuality, characterizing it as an unnatural affection, a sex perversion and an abomination.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jepson|first1=Jared A.|title=A study of the For the strength of youth pamphlet, 1965-2004|date=2005|publisher=BYU Department of Religious Education|location=Provo, Utah|pages=170–198|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Study_of_the_For_the_Strength_of_Youth.html?id=Aa9HQwAACAAJ|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=For the Strength of Youth|date=1990|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|url=//www.lds.org/manual/marriage-and-family-relations-instructors-manual/part-b-parents-responsibilities-to-strengthen-families/lesson-14-teaching-gospel-principles-to-children-part-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bingham|first1=Ronald D.|last2=Potts|first2=Richard W.|title=Homosexuality: An LDS Perspective|journal=Issues in Religion and Psychotherapy|date=1 April 1993|volume=19|issue=1|page=3|url=http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1344&context=irp#page=4|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> * '''1991''' – The First Presidency sent a letter on November 14 to be read in all congregations stating homosexual thoughts and feelings can and should be overcome by sincere repentance, persistent effort, the help of others, and counsel from a bishop. The letter made a distinction between thoughts and behavior, and called for love and understanding for those struggling to overcome gay thoughts.<ref>{{cite book|title=Eternal Marriage Student Manual|date=2007|publisher=LDS Church|isbn=|page=230|url=//www.lds.org/manual/eternal-marriage-student-manual/morality-and-modesty|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Park|first1=Jason|title=Understanding Male Homosexual Problems: An Introduction for Latter-day Saints|date=1997|edition=4th|publisher=Century Publishing|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|isbn=0941846083|page=10|url=http://centurypubl.com/Understanding-Male-Homosexual-Problems-LDS.pdf#page=12|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Blackley|first1=Jared W.|title=Nothing to Hide? What it means to be gay at BYU|url=https://www.cityweekly.net/utah/nothing-to-hide/Content?oid=2129162|accessdate=20 June 2017|work=Salt Lake City Weekly|date=11 June 2007}}</ref> [[File:Understanding and Helping Those Who Have Homosexual Problems 1992.png|thumb|right|150px|Cover of a 1992 manual which marked a shift in LDS church rhetoric towards changing homosexual behavior rather than feelings.<ref name="Conservative Christian Identity" />{{rp|40–41}}]] * '''1992''' – The church published a guide for local leaders which stated that homosexual feelings can be overcome, and sometimes heterosexual feelings emerge leading to happy, eternal marriage relationships.<ref name="lds92" />{{rp|6}}<ref name="Conservative Christian Identity" />{{rp|40–41}} The pamphlet did not frame homosexuality as a disease corresponding to the recent change by the World Health Organization removing homosexuality as a mental disorder.<ref name="Through the Years"/> * '''1994''' – The First Presidency issued a statement encouraging members to contact their legislators in an effort to reject same-sex marriage.<ref name="LDS Church 2004" /><ref>{{cite thesis |last=Piazza |first=Amanda Victoria |date=Spring 2016 |title=A Non-Peculiar People: Latter-day Saints and the American Family during the Twentieth-Century |publisher=Florida State University Department of Religion |docket= FSU_libsubv1_scholarship_submission_1461268847 |url=http://purl.flvc.org/fsu/fd/FSU_libsubv1_scholarship_submission_1461268847 |access-date=18 June 2017}}</ref> * '''1995''' – First presidency member [[James E. Faust|James Faust]] wrote an article denying any biological components in the [[Homosexuality#Causes|causes of homosexuality]].<ref name="Hierarchy" />{{rp|58}} He also stated that gay relationships would help unravel society.<ref name="Faust">{{cite web|last1=Faust|first1=James E.|title=Serving the Lord and Resisting the Devil|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/1995/09/serving-the-lord-and-resisting-the-devil|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=September 1995}}</ref> [[File:The Family A Proclamation to the World.jpg|thumb|right|"The Family: A Proclamation to the World" is a 1995 LDS church statement used as a legal document in several court case amicus briefs opposing same-sex marriage.<ref name="mormonnewsroom.org">{{cite web|title=Faiths File Amicus Brief on Marriage Cases Before Tenth Circuit Court|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/faiths-file-amicus-brief-on-marriage-cases-before-tenth-circuit-court|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>]] * '''1995''' – Church president [[Gordon B. Hinckley|Gordon Hinckley]] read "[[The Family: A Proclamation to the World]]" in the Fall General Conference which states that marriage between a man and a woman is essential and ordained of God. It also teaches that gender is an essential part of one's eternal identity and purpose.<ref name="Obscurity" />{{rp|154–155}}<ref name="Proclamation" /> The document has been submitted by the church in several amicus briefs as evidence against legalizing same-sex marriages.<ref name="mormonnewsroom.org"/> * '''1995''' – Church president Hinckley condemned same-sex marriage in the October General Conference, but inviting members of the church reach out and sympathize with homosexual individuals.<ref name="Women" />{{rp|45–46}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Stand Strong against the Wiles of the World|url=https://www.lds.org/general-conference/1995/10/stand-strong-against-the-wiles-of-the-world?lang=eng&_r=1|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hinckley|first1=Gordon|title=Teachings of Gordon B. Hinckley|date=1997|publisher=Deseret Book Company|isbn=1573452629|pages=263–264|edition=1}}</ref> * '''1995''' – An article by [[Dallin H. Oaks|Dallin Oaks]] denounced [[gay bashing]] and gave a nuanced view on potential biological components of the [[Homosexuality#Causes|etiology of homosexuality]]. It also advised against using the [[sexual identity|sexual identifiers]] gay or lesbian.<ref name="Through the Years"/><ref name="SGA">{{cite web|last1=Oaks|first1=Dallin|title=Same-Gender Attraction|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/1995/10/same-gender-attraction|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 1995}}</ref> * '''1995''' – The church's [[LDS Family Services]] published a manual for practitioners which stated that dysfunctional family relationships and abuse were at the root of homosexuality, and gave advice on how to prevent and treat homosexuality.<ref name="Gay Religion">{{cite book|last1=Crapo|first1=Richley H.|title=Gay Religion|date=10 December 2004|publisher=AltaMira Press|isbn=0759103259|edition=Hardcover|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dTZuAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|107}}<ref name="LDS Social Services">{{cite book|title=Understanding and Helping Individuals with Homosexual Problems|date=1995|publisher=LDS Social Services}}</ref> [[File:Gordon B. Hinckley2.jpg|thumb|upright|right|During his 13 years as president, [[Gordon B. Hinckley|Hinckley]] brought a shift in tone towards empathy in church public discussions on homosexuality.<ref name="Women" />{{rp|45}}<ref name="Crossroads" />{{rp|62}}]] * '''1997''' – Church president [[Gordon B. Hinckley|Gordon Hinkcley]] gave an interview in which he called gay members of the church good people and said they're not reprimanded for their attractions unless involved in sexual transgressions. He affirmed that gay Mormons must live a celibate life.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lattin|first1=Don|title=Musings of the Main Mormon / Gordon B. Hinckley|journal=San Francisco Chronicle|date=13 Apr 1997|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/SUNDAY-INTERVIEW-Musings-of-the-Main-Mormon-2846138.php|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Lord" />{{rp|162}} * '''1998''' – The ''[[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]]'' was updated to ban members from full-time missionary service who had participated in "homosexual acts" from age 15 (unless it had been at least one year since the occurrence and there was strong evidence of reformation).<ref name="LDS Church 1998" />{{rp|81}} The update also included the first church policy sections on homosexuality and same-gender marriage, stating that members with homosexual thoughts, feelings, or actions should be helped to understand faith, repentance, life's purpose, and to accept responsibility for their thoughts.<ref name="Obscurity" />{{rp|166}} Additionally, the manual encourages members to appeal to government officials to reject same-sex marriage.<ref name="LDS Church 1998" />{{rp|159}} * '''1999''' – The Area Presidency of the North America West [[Area (LDS Church)|Area]] sent a May 11 letter to all area leaders directing members to donate their means and time to pass the [[California Proposition 22 (2000)|Knight Initiative]] against same-sex marriage in California.<ref>{{cite web|title=11 May 1999 Area Presidency Letter|publisher=LDS Church}}</ref> A second letter invited church members to donate money,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Callister|first1=Douglas L.|title=20 May 1999 Callister Letter|publisher=LDS Church}}</ref> and a third letter (sent a month and a half before the proposition would pass) asked members to redouble their efforts in contacting neighbors and to place provided yard signs.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Proposition 22 Dominates Wards' Attention, Divides Members|journal=Sunstone Magazine|date=April 2001|issue=118|page=92|url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/issues/118.pdf#page=90|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> * '''1999''' – The church published an Ensign article which states that homosexuality is changeable and heterosexual feelings will emerge and is caused by personality traits, sexual abuse, familial factors, and treatment by peers.<ref name="Othering" />{{rp|346}}<ref name="LDS Church"/>
===2000s=== * '''2000''' – [[Boyd K. Packer|Packer]] gave an October General Conference address in which he calls homosexuality a temptation which may lead to despair, disease, and death that begins as an innocent curiosity which leads to a pattern and then addiction. He said the idea that God created homosexual people with "overpowering, unnatural desires" is false and that they can be cured and healed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Packer|first1=Boyd K.|title=Ye Are the Temple of God|url=//www.lds.org/general-conference/2000/10/ye-are-the-temple-of-god|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=Gregory L.|title=Shattered Glass: The Traditions of Mormon SameSex Marriage Advocates Encounter Boyd K. Packer|journal=Mormon Studies Review|publisher=BYU|date=2011|volume=23|issue=1|pages=65–68, 70|url=http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1835&context=msr|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="Post-Heterosexual">{{cite journal|last1=Petrey|first1=Taylor G.|title=Toward a Post-Heterosexual Mormon Theology|journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|date=Winter 2011|volume=44|issue=4|pages=139–140|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Dialogue_V44N04_110.pdf#page=34|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> [[File:Title For The Strength of Youth 2001.png|thumb|right|The 2001 update to the youth guideline pamphlet removed the harsher language of the 1990 edition which characterized homosexual feelings as unnatural, perverse, and an abomination.]] * '''2001''' – The eighth version of the "[[For the Strength of Youth]]" pamphlet was published updating the section discussing homosexuality to only say that homosexual activity is a serious sin and that those "struggling with same-gender attraction" should talk to their parents and bishop.<ref name="FSY" /><ref name="Universe Timeline">{{cite news|last1=Olsen|first1=Jessica|title=Timeline|url=http://universe.byu.edu/2017/01/20/lgbt-byu-students-at-higher-risk-for-depression-suicide1/|accessdate=9 February 2017|agency=The Daily Universe|publisher=BYU|date=20 January 2017}}</ref> * '''2004''' – The church published ''True to the Faith'', which states that homosexual activity is contrary to the purposes of human sexuality, distorts loving relationships, and prevents people from receiving blessings. The book further says that sexual sins are more serious than any other sins except murder and denying the Holy Ghost.<ref>{{cite web|title=True to the Faith: Chastity|url=//www.lds.org/manual/true-to-the-faith/chastity|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Straight">{{cite book|last1=Bryd|first1=A. Dean|title=Setting the Record Straight: Mormons & Homosexuality|date=2008|publisher=Millennial Press Inc.|location=Orem, Utah|isbn=1932597441|url=https://read.amazon.com/nc/?kcrFree=only&asin=B0117VJS30|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|10}} * '''2004''' – The [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] issued a July 7 statement saying the church favors a constitutional amendment barring the legal status of any marriage outside one between one man and one woman.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Presidency statement: Constitutional amendment|url=http://www.ldschurchnewsarchive.com/articles/45827/First-Presidency-statement-Constitutional-amendment.html|website=LDS Church News|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Church Supports Call for Constitutional Amendment|url=//www.lds.org/ensign/2006/07/news-of-the-church/church-supports-call-for-constitutional-amendment|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref> A few months later on October 19 they expounded this stance with the ''First Presidency Statement on Same-Gender Marriage'' supporting the 2004 movement for this amendment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush calls for ban on same-sex marriages |url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/02/24/elec04.prez.bush.marriage/ |accessdate=9 November 2016 |publisher=CNN |date=25 February 2004 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515103309/http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/02/24/elec04.prez.bush.marriage/ |archivedate=May 15, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The letter states that the church reaches out with understanding and respect for homosexual persons and realizes there may be great loneliness in their lives, but defend their stance.<ref name="LDS Church 2004" /><ref name="Straight" />{{rp|10}} * '''2006''' – [[Jeffrey R. Holland]] and [[Marlin K. Jensen]] were interviewed in March with questions about various topics including homosexuality by PBS. Jensen stated that he did not think the church could ever change its position on homosexual behavior, and acknowledged that this creates a lot of pain since homosexual Mormons have no hope of falling in love in a church-sanctioned way.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Mormons: Marlin Jensen Interview|url=https://www.pbs.org/mormons/interviews/jensen.html|website=PBS.org|publisher=PBS|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> Holland stated that he doesn't anticipate a change in church stance, and affirmed that gay or lesbian inclinations disappear after death.<ref name="pbs.org"/><ref name="Universe Timeline" /><ref name="Attitudes">{{cite journal|last1=Myler|first1=Cory John|title=Latter-day Saint Religiosity and Attitudes towards Sexual Minorities|journal=Utah State University: All Graduate Theses and Dissertations|date=May 2010|url=http://digitalcommons.usu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1541&context=etd|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|36}} * '''2006''' – The ''[[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]]'' was updated again,<ref>{{cite book|title=17 Aug 2006 Letter to Local Leaders on the Church Handbook of Instructions|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=1}}</ref> stating that the church reaches out with respect and understanding to same-sex attracted individuals.<ref>{{cite book|title=Church Handbook of Instructions Book 1|date=2006|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|page=187}}</ref> * '''2006''' – A revision to the church's ''Mission Presidents Handbook'' recommended that, barring unusual circumstances, a missionary who makes a belated confession to a serious transgression like pre-mission homosexual acts should be sent home.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mission Presidents' Handbook|publisher=LDS Church|page=27}}</ref> The manual also specified that any baptismal candidate confessing to a homosexual transgression during a baptismal interview (usually with a mission district leader) needs a searching interview with the local mission president for baptism approval.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mission Presidents' Handbook|publisher=LDS Church|page=43}}</ref> [[File:Dallin H. Oaks3.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Apostle [[Dallin H. Oaks|Oaks]] has been an influential figure in church interactions with homosexual people, instituting a [[Brigham Young University LGBT history#Surveillance|system of surveillance]] to identify and expel or attempt to "cure" homosexual students as president of BYU in the '70s, and doing numerous important video interviews and articles on the topic in the '80s, '90s, and 2000s.]] * '''2006''' – The church published an extensive April interview<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /> with [[Dallin H. Oaks|Oaks]] and [[Lance B. Wickman]] to clarify the church’s stance on homosexuality.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Givens|first1=Terryl L.|last2=Neilson|first2=Reid L.|title=The Columbia Sourcebook of Mormons in the United States|date=2014|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=0231520603|pages=316–322}}</ref> In the interview, Wickman states that the church doesn't counsel against [[conversion therapy]] and that it may be appropriate for some. However, Oaks states they can't endorse the [[Aversion Therapy|aversive therapies]] recommended in the past to fix it, and they don’t accept responsibility for the abuses suffered by individuals who had experienced this now disavowed therapy method. He further stated that giving even same-sex civil unions and domestic partnerships the same government rights given to opposite-sex marriage would not be appropriate. He added that a [[mixed-orientation marriage]] would be appropriate for a gay member who could put homosexual feelings in the background and felt a great attraction to someone of the opposite sex.<ref name="Living gay in the Mormon Church"/> He compared devout homosexual Mormons to those with physical or mental disabilities who will also not be able to marry, and added that same-sex attraction did not exist in the pre-earth life and will not exist in the next life. On family acceptance he stated that parents of gay children in same-sex relationships might tell them they can't stay overnight or expect any public appearances with the couple that may imply an approval of their relationship. He further stated the Lord’s way is to love the sinner while condemning the sin.<ref name="Oaks-Wickman 2007" /><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> * '''2006''' – In April Apostle [[Russell M. Nelson|Russell Nelson]] signed a letter with other religious leaders urging the US government to pass an amendment banning same-sex marriage. On May 25 the First Presidency released another statement supporting the amendment and urging members to contact their senators.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Presidency urges support of marriage|url=http://www.ldschurchnewsarchive.com/articles/49041/First-Presidency-urges-support-of-marriage.html|website=Church News|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Straight" />{{rp|10–11}} * '''2006''' – Apostle [[Dallin H. Oaks]] gave an October General Conference address in which he stated change is possible but don't focus on the causes of same-sex attraction. Oaks then explained that if faith, prayers, and priesthood don't heal one from an affliction that the Atonement can help one bear the burden.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oaks|first1=Dallin H.|title=He Heals the Heavy Laden|url=//www.lds.org/general-conference/2006/10/he-heals-the-heavy-laden|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2007''' – The church's [[Brigham Young University|BYU]] [[Church Educational System#General administration|Board of Trustees]], under the direction of First Presidency member [[Thomas S. Monson|Monson]], revised the [[Church Educational System Honor Code|Honor Code]] in April to clarify that coming out is not an Honor Code issue, while continuing to ban all forms of physical intimacy expressing homosexual feelings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Church Educational System Honor Code|url=https://policy.byu.edu/view/index.php?p=26|website=BYU University Policies|publisher=Brigham Young University|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Morrison|first1=Jenna|title=BYU Clarifies Honor Code|url=http://universe.byu.edu/2007/04/17/byu-clarifies-honor-code/|accessdate=10 November 2016|agency=The Daily Universe|publisher=Brigham Young University|date=17 Apr 2007}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> [[File:God_Loveth_His_Children.jpg|thumb|right|150px|This was the first church publication on homosexuality produced in nearly three decades for members to read since "To the One" and "A Letter to a Friend" were released in 1978.]] * '''2007''' – In July, the church published the booklet "[[God Loveth His Children]]" summarizing church teachings on homosexuality.<ref name="Women">{{cite book|last1=Vance|first1=Laura|title=Women in New Religions|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York City, NY|isbn=1479816027|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NUSWBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|46}}<ref name="God Loveth">{{cite web|title=God Loveth His Children|url=//www.lds.org/manual/god-loveth-his-children/god-loveth-his-children?lang=eng|year=2007|website=lds.org|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> * '''2008''' – The [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] again urged California members to do all they can by giving effort and time to help pass a state amendment banning same-sex marriage in a June 29 letter.<ref name="Through the Years"/><ref>{{cite web|title=California and Same-Sex Marriage|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church}}</ref> A few months later Apostles [[M. Russell Ballard|Ballard]] and [[Quentin L. Cook|Cook]] and [[L. Whitney Clayton]] gave an October 8 satellite broadcast<ref>{{cite news|title=Excerpts from the Broadcast |url=http://broadcast.lds.org/newsroom/video/wmv/Prop_8_320x240_13Oct08.wmv |accessdate=9 November 2016 |publisher=LDS Church |date=8 Oct 2008 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081107002327/http://broadcast.lds.org/newsroom/video/wmv/Prop_8_320x240_13Oct08.wmv |archivedate=November 7, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> to all California members titled "The Divine Institution of Marriage Broadcast." In the broadcast they asked members to donate four hours per week and to set aside Saturdays morning to calling people and other efforts supporting the passage of [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Prop 8]]. They clarified that tolerance does not mean tolerating transgression, and noted the existence of temple-worthy members attracted to the same sex. Additionally, a video<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bednar |first1=David A. |title=Elder Bednar Speaks With Youth |url=http://broadcast.lds.org/newsroom/video/wmv/BednarEdit2640x480_13Oct08.wmv |website=PerservingMarriage.org |publisher=LDS Church |accessdate=9 November 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081107002327/http://broadcast.lds.org/newsroom/video/wmv/BednarEdit2640x480_13Oct08.wmv |archivedate=November 7, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> of Apostle [[David A. Bednar|Bednar]] answering youth's questions was shown from the church's official website PreservingMarriage.org.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011010124/http://www.preservingmarriage.org/ PreservingMarriage.org]</ref> Members were directed to register on the coalition website ProtectMarriage.com.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081010125329/http://www.protectmarriage.com/ ProtectMarriage.com]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Church Readies Members on Proposition 8 |url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/news-releases-stories/church-readies-members-on-proposition-8 |website=Mormon Newsroom |publisher=LDS Church |accessdate=9 November 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017191133/http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/news-releases-stories/church-readies-members-on-proposition-8 |archivedate=October 17, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ballard|first1=M. Russell|last2=Cook|first2=Quentin L.|last3=Clayton|first3=Whitney|title=The Divine Institution of Marriage Broadcast|publisher=LDS Church|date=8 Oct 2008}}</ref> * '''2009''' – On September 19 Seventy [[Bruce C. Hafen|Bruce Hafen]] promised members of [[Evergreen International|Evergreen]] that if they were faithful they may develop heterosexual attractions in this life, and would be resurrected with heterosexual attractions, citing apostle [[Dallin H. Oaks|Oaks]] and affirming that "it MUST be true" (emphasis in original).<ref name="Crossroads">{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Alan Michael|title=Mormon and Queer at the Crossroads|journal=Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|date=Spring 2011|volume=44|issue=1|url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V44N01_365.pdf|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>{{rp|79}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winters|first1=Rosemary|title=Homosexuality 'not in your DNA,' says LDS leader|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/News/ci_13377659|accessdate=19 June 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=19 September 2009}}</ref><ref name="Hafen Speaks" />
===2010 to present=== * '''2010''' – A 2010 update to the [[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]] noted that the records of adult members who had repeated homosexual activities would be permanently annotated.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook 1: Stake Presidents and Bishops|date=2010|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=28–29}}</ref> It also advised that homosexual activity during or after the last three teenage years would bar someone from missionary service.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook 1: Stake Presidents and Bishops|date=2010|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=28–29}}</ref> The Handbook 2 also stated that members who experience same-sex attraction but don't engage in homosexual behavior may receive church callings and temple recommends.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook 2: Administering the Church|date=2010|publisher=LDS Church|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|pages=195–196|url=//www.lds.org/bc/content/shared/content/english/pdf/language-materials/08702_eng.pdf|accessdate=8 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2010''' – Apostle [[Boyd K. Packer|Packer]] delivered an October conference address stating that [[The Family: A Proclamation to the World]] qualified as a revelation<ref>{{cite web|last1=Packer|first1=Boyd|title=President Boyd K. Packer - Cleansing the Inner Vessel|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2C1wUI5xuhs&t=1m|website=youtube.com|publisher=Mormon Channel - LDS Church|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> homosexual desires are not inborn since God would not do that to anyone.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Packer|first1=Boyd K.|title=Cleansing the Inner Vessel|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=2C1wUI5xuhs|website=Mormon Channel Youtube|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=3 November 2016|ref=Quote starts at 9:00}}</ref> His characterization of same-sex physical attractions as something impure and unnatural to overcome sparked an October 7 protest in which thousands surrounded [[Temple Square]].<ref name="archive.sltrib.com"/><ref name="deseretnews.com"/> He later softened his words in the speech's print version to only say there were no inborn temptations.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Geisner|first1=Joseph|title=Very Careless in His Utterances: Editing, Correcting, and Censoring Conference Addresses|journal=Sunstone Magazine|date=December 2011|issue=165|pages=14, 23|url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/magazine/premium-issues/|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Packer talk jibes with LDS stance after tweak|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/sltrib/home/50440474-76/packer-church-question-speech.html.csp|accessdate=16 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=25 October 2010}}</ref><ref name="Through the Years"/> * '''2011''' – The church's [[Brigham Young University|BYU]] [[Church Educational System Honor Code|Honor Code]] was updated to remove the ban on the advocacy and promotion of homosexual behavior as being morally acceptable.<ref name="Universe Timeline" /><ref>{{citation |url= http://gaysaltlake.com/news/2011/02/02/byu-removes-pro-gay-advocacy-from-its-honor-code/ |title= BYU removes pro-gay advocacy from its honor code |date= February 2, 2011 |newspaper= [[QSaltLake]] |publisher= QSaltLake}}</ref> * '''2012''' – In May the church released a statement approving the [[Boy Scouts of America]] (BSA) administration's decision to remove the 1991 ban on homosexual youth.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eckholm|first1=Erik|title=Boy Scouts to Continue Excluding Gay People|journal=New York Times|date=17 July 2012|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/18/us/boy-scouts-reaffirm-ban-on-gay-members.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rehnquist|first1=William H.|title=Excerpts From the Supreme Court's Ruling on Gays and the Boy Scouts|journal=New York Times|date=29 June 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/29/us/excerpts-from-the-supreme-court-s-ruling-on-gays-and-the-boy-scouts.html|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> The release stated that sexual orientation had never disqualified boys from joining LDS troops as long as they abided by church standards barring any pre-marital sexual activity,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Toone|first1=Trent|last2=Jones|first2=Morgan|title=Here's how the LDS Church has responded to changes in Scouts regarding LGBT issues|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865679716/Heres-how-the-LDS-Church-has-responded-to-changes-in-Scouts-regarding-LGBT-issues.html|accessdate=23 June 2017|work=Deseret News|agency=Deseret Digital Media|publisher=LDS Church|date=11 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Church Responds to Boy Scouts Policy Vote|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-responds-to-boy-scouts-of-america-policy-vote|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> though, the policy remains unclear for young men participating in same-sex dating without sexual activity. In 2010, Mormon scouts constituted the largest group of young men in the BSA (21% in 2010).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cloud|first1=John|title=Can A Scout Be Gay?|journal=Time Magazine|date=1 May 2000|volume=155|issue=18|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,996776,00.html|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> [[File:Mormons and Gays Website Header.jpg|thumb|This header was at the top of the LDS church's first official website on homosexuality from December 2012 until an update in October 2016.]] * '''2012''' – In December the church launched a website dedicated to the topic of homosexuality in an effort to encourage understanding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Love One Another: A Discussion on Same-Sex Attraction|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206183714/http://www.mormonsandgays.org/|website=mormonsandgays.org|publisher=LDS Church|archive-date=6 December 2012|url=http://www.mormonsandgays.org/}}</ref> The website stated that individuals don't choose to experience same-sex attractions.<ref>{{citation |chapter-url= http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-website-same-sex-attraction |contribution= New Church Website on Same-Sex Attraction Offers Love, Understanding and Hope |title= News Release |date= December 6, 2012 |publisher= LDS Church}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/12/07/15734686-new-website-from-mormon-church-sexuality-is-not-a-choice?lite|title=New website from Mormon church: 'Sexuality is not a choice'|first=Andrew|last=Mach|date=December 7, 2012|work=USNews.NBCNews.com|publisher=[[NBC News]]}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> * '''2015''' – Church leaders held a "Fairness for All" news conference on January 27 supporting LGBT non-discrimination laws for housing and employment that would also protect religious individuals.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=O'Neill|first1=Lorena|title=They Loved the Church. They Loved Each Other More.|journal=Esquire Magazine|date=24 June 2016|url=http://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a45719/gay-mormon-community/|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> Apostle [[D. Todd Christofferson|Christofferson]] called for a balance between religious freedom and LGBT rights while [[Neill F. Marriott]] of the [[Young Women (organization)|Young Women's]] presidency recognized the centuries of ridicule, persecution, and violence against homosexuals. Apostle [[Dallin H. Oaks|Oaks]] followed stating that the church rejects persecution based on gender or sexual orientation and called for legislation protecting religious freedoms and LGBT citizens in housing, employment, and public accommodations. Apostle [[Jeffrey R. Holland|Holland]] closed outlining the church's stance on religious freedom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transcript of News Conference on Religious Freedom and Nondiscrimination|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/publicstatement-on-religious-freedom-and-nondiscrimination|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mormon Leaders Call for Laws That Protect Religious Freedom|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-news-conference-on-religious-freedom-and-nondiscrimination|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The LDS Church's Statement on Nondiscrimination Laws|url=https://www.equalityutah.org/newsroom/item/196-the-lds-church-s-statement-on-nondiscrimination-laws|website=Equality Utah Newsroom|publisher=Equality Utah|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref> In answer to a press question afterwards Christofferson affirmed his love for his gay brother Tom who was in a 20-year relationship with a man.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Decker|first1=Rod|last2=Ware|first2=Doug G.|title=LDS leader uses family as example of harmony between church, gays|url=http://kutv.com/news/local/lds-leader-uses-family-as-example-of-harmony-between-church-gays|accessdate=27 November 2016|agency=KUTV|date=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Christofferson|first1=Tom|title=Tom and Clarke|url=https://voicesoflove.org/2014/06/05/tom-and-clarke/|website=voicesoflove.org|publisher=Voices of Love|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> * '''2015''' – In early March the church released a public statement<ref>{{cite web|title=Utah Lawmakers Introduce Bill Balancing Religious Freedom and Nondiscrimination Protections|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/utah-lawmakers-introduce-bill-balancing-religious-freedom-and-nondiscrimination-protections|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> and employed its lobbyists<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Davidson|first1=Lee|last2=Canham|first2=Matt|title=Mormon church lobbying in Utah’s Capitol—hardball or light touch?|journal=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=17 February 2016|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/2323383-155/mormon-church-lobbying-in-utahs-capitol?fullpage=1|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> to garner support for a proposed nondiscrimination and religious rights bill which would grant housing and employment protection for LGBT persons in Utah. Though similar bills had failed 6 times before,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dobner|first1=Jennifer|title=Little-known history behind Utah’s LGBT nondiscrimination law recounted|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/2295501-155/little-known-history-behind-utahs-lgbt-nondiscrimination?fullpage=1|accessdate=27 November 2016|agency=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=28 March 2015}}</ref> SB 296 was passed on March 11 and another statement of church approval was released.<ref>{{cite web|title=Church Applauds Passage of Utah Senate Bill 296|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-issues-statement-on-utah-house-bill-296|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> the new law (nicknamed the "Utah Compromise")<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Goodstein|first1=Laurie|title=Utah Passes Antidiscrimination Bill Backed by Mormon Leaders|journal=The New York Times|date=12 March 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/12/us/politics/utah-passes-antidiscrimination-bill-backed-by-mormon-leaders.html?partner=socialflow&smid=tw-nytimes&_r=3|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> passed and was praised by many.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=McKitrick|first1=Cathy|title=Utah's anti-discrimination bill hailed as a better way|journal=Ogden Standard Examiner|date=3 April 2015|url=http://www.standard.net/Government/2015/04/02/Utah-s-SB296-hailed-as-a-better-approach|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Romboy|first1=Dennis|title=LDS Church, LGBT advocates back anti-discrimination, religious rights bill|journal=Deseret News|date=4 March 2015|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865623399/Utah-lawmakers-unveil-anti-discrimination-religious-rights-legislation.html?pg=all|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2015''' – Three days after the US Supreme Court [[Obergefell v. Hodges|ruled]] in favor of same-sex marriage the First Presidency sent a June 29 letter to be read to every US congregation affirming changing US law would not change God's moral law. The letter clarified that leaders should not perform same-sex marriages, and that any church property cannot be used for activities related to same-sex marriages. The letter welcomed all visitors on church property as long as LDS standards of conduct were respected.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Top Mormon leaders sending letter to members, reaffirming God’s law against same-sex marriage|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/2682018-155/top-mormon-leaders-sending-letter-to?fullpage=1|accessdate=23 June 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=30 Jun 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Church Leaders Counsel Members After Supreme Court Same-Sex Marriage Decision|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/top-church-leaders-counsel-members-after-supreme-court-same-sex-marriage-decision|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2015''' – Following a Boy Scouts of America (BSA) policy change on July 27 allowing for gay scout leaders<ref>{{cite web|title=Boy Scouts of America Amends Adult Leadership Policy |url=http://scoutingnewsroom.org/blog/boy-scouts-of-america-amends-adult-leadership-policy/ |website=Scouting Newsroom |publisher=BSA |accessdate=23 November 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902071556/http://scoutingnewsroom.org/blog/boy-scouts-of-america-amends-adult-leadership-policy/ |archivedate=September 2, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> (though allowing for churches to continue banning them)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dobner|first1=Jennifer|title=LDS Church ‘deeply troubled’ by Boy Scouts ending ban on gay adult leaders, will re-evaluate relationship with program|journal=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=27 July 2015|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/2774464-155/boy-scout-board-approves-end-to?fullpage=1|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> the church stated that it had always welcomed gay youth, but that allowing openly gay leaders was inconsistent with church doctrine. The official press release (preceded by one on May 21<ref>{{cite web|title=Church to Monitor BSA Policy Discussion|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-monitor-bsa-policy-discussion|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> and July 13<ref>{{cite web|title=Church Comments on Boy Scouts of America Resolution on Adult Leader Standards|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/church-comments-on-boy-scouts-of-america-resolution-on-adult-leader-standards|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=LDS Church|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>) alluded to a potential change in church-BSA relations. Despite the majority of church members wanting to drop relations with the BSA,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Francis|first1=JaNae|title=Poll shows Mormons want church to leave Boy Scouts|journal=Standard Examiner|date=18 August 2015|url=http://www.standard.net/Faith/2015/08/17/Poll-shows-Mormons-want-church-to-leave-Boy-Scouts|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> however, no change in relations occurred.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Noyce|first1=David|last2=Stack|first2=Peggy Fletcher|title=Mormon Church Sticks With The Boy Scouts But Still Will Ban Gay Troop Leaders|journal=The Huffington Post|date=26 August 2015|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-mormon-church-is-sticking-with-the-boy-scouts-as-long-as-it-can-still-ban-gay-troop-leaders_us_55ddf7d1e4b08cd3359e3fd4|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2015''' – On November 5 an updated letter to leaders for the [[Handbook (LDS Church)|Church Handbook]] was leaked. A new policy banned a child of a parent living in a same-gender relationship from [[Naming and blessing of children|baby blessings]], [[Baptism in Mormonism|baptism]], [[Confirmation (Latter Day Saints)|confirmation]], [[Priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood ordination]], and [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary service]] until the child was not living with their homosexual parent(s), was of legal age, and disavowed same-gender cohabitation and marriage, in addition to receiving approval from the [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]]. The policy update added that entering a same-sex marriage was a type of "apostasy", mandating a [[disciplinary council]].<ref name="ReferenceC"/><ref name="The Washington Post"/> The next day, apostle [[D. Todd Christofferson|Christofferson]] stated that the policy was about love and protecting children from difficulties, challenges, and conflicts between parents and the church.<ref>{{cite web|title=Church Provides Context on Handbook Changes Affecting Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/handbook-changes-same-sex-marriages-elder-christofferson|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> On November 13, the First Presidency released a letter clarifying that the policy only applied to children who lived mostly with the parent in a same-sex relationship, and that those who had already received ordinances before the change could continue with further ordinances.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Otterson|first1=Michael|title=Understanding the Handbook|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org/article/commentary-understanding-the-handbook|website=Mormon Newsroom|publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First Presidency Clarifies Church Handbook Changes|url=https://www.lds.org/pages/church-handbook-changes?lang=eng|website=lds.org|publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> The next day around 1,500 members gathered across from the Church Office to submit their resignation letters in response to the policy change, with thousands more resigning online in the weeks after.<ref name="washingtonpost.com"/><ref name="nytimes.com"/><ref name="theguardian.com"/> Two months later, apostle [[Russell M. Nelson|Nelson]] stated that the change was revealed to President Monson in a sacred moment when the Lord inspired him to declare the will of the Lord.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Russell M.|title=Becoming True Millennials|url=https://www.lds.org/broadcasts/article/worldwide-devotionals/2016/01/becoming-true-millennials?lang=eng|website=lds.org|publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> * '''2016''' – The church released a statement through spokesman Dale Jones on January 28 mourning the reported suicides of 32 LGBT Mormons. The release stated that leaders and members are taught to reach out in an active, caring way to all, especially to youth who feel estranged or isolated.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walch|first1=Tad|last2=Collins|first2=Lois M.|title=LDS Church leaders mourn reported deaths in Mormon LGBT community|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865646414/LDS-Church-leaders-mourn-reported-deaths-in-Mormon-LGBT-community.html?pg=all|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=Deseret News|publisher=LDS Church|date=28 January 2016}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> * '''2016''' – On February 17 church spokesperson Dale Jones spoke against passing any LGBT-related laws which could affect the balance of religious liberty and gay rights.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Romboy|first1=Dennis|title=LDS Church seeks to maintain balance of anti-discrimination law|journal=The Deseret News|date=17 February 2016|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865647932/LDS-Church-weighs-in-on-proposed-Utah-hate-crimes-law.html?pg=all|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> The statement was in reference to proposed Utah hate crime bill SB107 which would add sexual orientation to the current list of characteristics protected from hate crimes in Utah.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dobner|first1=Jennifer|title=Mormon church warns against upsetting ‘careful balance’ of LGBT anti-discrimination law|journal=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=17 February 2016|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/3549669-155/mormon-church-warns-against-upsetting-careful|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> The bill failed as it had in past years and its Mormon Republican sponsor criticized his church for its opposition to the bill citing the church's press release as the reason for its failure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullahy|first1=Brian|title=Mormon Senator criticizes LDS church, apologizes to state|url=http://kutv.com/news/local/mormon-senator-criticizes-lds-church-apologizes-to-state|accessdate=11 December 2016|agency=KUTV|publisher=CBS Television Sinclair Broadcast Group|date=18 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dobner|first1=Jennifer|last2=Gehrke|first2=Robert|title=Senate kills hate-crimes bill; LGBT advocates blame Mormon church|journal=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=2 March 2016|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/3608491-155/senate-kills-hate-crimes-bill-lgbt-advocates?fullpage=1|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> * '''2016''' – Apostle [[David A. Bednar]] answered a members question in a February 23 broadcast stating that there are no homosexual members of the Church since we are not defined by sexual attraction or behavior. He compared homosexuality to a physical handicap.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=Curtis M.|title=Mormon Leader: ‘There Are No Homosexual Members Of The Church’|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/mormon-leader-homosexuality_us_56d5c8a3e4b03260bf782ee5|accessdate=29 November 2016|agency=The Huffington Post|date=1 Mar 2016}}</ref> * '''2016''' – Church spokesman Eric Hawkins stated on March 15 that the church denounces any therapy that subjects an individual to abusive practices and hopes LGBT Mormons find compassion and understanding from family members, professional counselors and church members.<ref name="kutv.com">{{cite news|last1=Woodruff|first1=Daniel|title=New book details LDS teen's 'humiliating' gay conversion therapy in Utah|url=http://kutv.com/news/local/new-book-details-lds-teens-humiliating-gay-conversion-therapy-in-utah|accessdate=3 December 2016|agency=KUTV|publisher=CBS Television Sinclair Broadcast Group|date=15 March 2016}}</ref> The statement was in response to media inquiries around the experiences of a lesbian Mormon teen subjected to physically abusive therapy attempting to change her attractions which lead to a suicide attempt.<ref name="huffingtonpost.com">{{cite journal|last1=Wong|first1=Curtis M.|title=Mormon Woman Exposes Barbaric And ‘Humiliating’ Treatment For Being Gay|journal=The Huffington Post|date=17 March 2016|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/saving-alex-mormon-teen_us_56ead60ee4b09bf44a9c9152|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> [[File:Mormon and Gay Website.png|thumb|right|The 2016 website update contained the first church disavowal of all therapy focusing on changing sexual orientation.]] * '''2016''' – In June the Mexican area authority presidency had a letter read in congregations around the country urging members to oppose the national legalization of same-sex marriage and pointed them to the political organization ''Conciencia Nacional por la Libertad Religiosa''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Leaders urge Mexico's Mormons to fight against push for same-sex marriage|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3957702&itype=CMSID|accessdate=12 October 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Presidente del Área México se pronuncia ante propuesta de ley de matrimonio del mismo sexo|url=http://www.saladeprensamormona.org.mx/articulo/presidente-de-la-iglesia-en-mexico-se-pronuncia-ante-propuesta-de-ley-de-matrimonio-del-mismo-sexo|website=saladeprensamormona.org.mx|publisher=LDS Church|language=Spanish|trans-title=Area President of Mexico Makes Announcement Before Proposed Same-Sex Marriage Law|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> * '''2016''' – In October, the official ''Mormons and Gays'' website was revised and moved to ''mormonandgay.lds.org''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|title=Mormon and gay: church says you can be both, but activists say it isn't enough|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/25/mormon-church-gay-lgbt-transgender-policy-website|accessdate=23 June 2017|work=The Guardian|agency=Guardian News and Media Ltd.|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> The update supported members in identifying as gay<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jackson|first1=Lauren|title=Mormon and gay: Church says you can be both|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/10/25/living/mormon-gay-website/index.html|accessdate=23 June 2017|work=CNN|agency=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|date=26 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions|url=//mormonandgay.lds.org/articles/frequently-asked-questions|website=Mormon and Gay|publisher=LDS Church|date=October 2016}}</ref><ref name="Universe Timeline" /> and noted that [[Conversion therapy|therapy]] focusing on changing sexual orientation is unethical.<ref name="Seeking Professional Help"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|last2=Dobner|first2=Jennifer|title=LDS Church’s new ‘Mormon and Gay’ website wins cheers and some jeers for ignoring controversial policy|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4504773-155/lds-churchs-new-mormon-and-gay?fullpage=1|accessdate=23 June 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> * '''2017''' – The Pacific area presidency sent a letter to be read in September in all Australian congregations which reemphasized the church's position against same-sex marriage and parenting and urged members to "vote their conscience" in the upcoming national referendum on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pacific Area Presidency Sends Letter to Australian Latter-day Saints on Marriage and Family|url=http://www.mormonnewsroom.org.au/article/pacific-area-presidency-sends-letter-to-australian-latter-day-saints-on-marriage-and-family|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref> * '''2017''' – The apostle Oaks stated that the [[The Family: A Proclamation to the World|Family Proclamation's]] teachings on same-sex marriage were not changeable policies but statements of eternal truth, the will of God, and the basis for church teachings and practice over the last two decades. He lamented the increase in public acceptance of same-sex marriage and acknowledged the conflicts with friends and family that opposing this acceptance could cause. He further stated that despite the conflict church members should choose God and the LDS Church's plan and way.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stack|first1=Peggy Fletcher|title=Mormon opposition to gay marriage will never change, says apostle Oaks, citing ‘statement of eternal truth’|url=http://www.sltrib.com/religion/local/2017/09/30/mormon-general-conference-resumes-for-the-first-time-monson-will-not-be-attending-any-sessions/|accessdate=30 September 2017|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=30 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Top Mormon Leader Reaffirms Faith’s Opposition to Gay Marriage|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/religion/top-mormon-leader-reaffirms-faith-s-opposition-gay-marriage-n806226|accessdate=30 September 2017|work=NBC News|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NBC News Digital|date=30 September 2017}}</ref>
