{{Forms of government}}
'''Kritarchy''', also called '''kritocracy''' or '''dikastocracy''', is a system of rule by [[Biblical judges|judges]] ({{lang-he-n|שופטים}}, ''shoftim'') in the tribal confederacy of [[History of ancient Israel and Judah|ancient Israel]] during the period of time described in the [[Book of Judges]], following [[Joshua]]'s conquest of [[Canaan]] and prior to the united monarchy under [[Saul]].<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/kritarchy Dictionary.com]</ref> 

Because it is a compound of the [[Greek language|Greek]] words [[:wikt:κριτής|κριτής]], ''krites'' ("judge") and [[:wikt:ἄρχω|ἄρχω]], ''árkhō'' ("to rule"), its use has expanded to cover rule by [[judge]]s in the modern sense as well, as in the case of [[Somalia]], ruled by judges with the [[polycentric law|polycentric  legal]] tradition of [[xeer]],<ref>[http://www.independent.org/publications/article.asp?id=126 A Peaceful Ferment in Somalia: Publications: The Independent Institute<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and arguably the [[Islamic Courts Union]]{{citation needed|date=May 2011}} and in the fictional regime of [[Mega-City One|Mega-city One]], the focus of setting for the [[Judge Dredd]] franchise.



