{{redirect|New Socialism|the ideology of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation|Communist Party  of the Russian Federation#Ideology|the ideology of the Russian political party A Just Russia|A Just Russia#Platform}}
{{Fascism sidebar}}
'''Neosocialism''' was the name of a [[political faction]] that existed in [[French Third Republic|France during the 1930s]] and in [[History of Belgium|Belgium]] around the same time and which included several [[Revisionism (Marxism)|revisionist]] tendencies in the [[French Section of the Workers' International]] (SFIO). Step by step, the fraction distanced it self from [[revolution]]ary [[Marxism]] and [[reformist socialism]], instead advocating a "constructive revolution", or [[revolution from above]]. Neosocialists came to oppose the majority of the [[Socialism|socialists]] in [[National Assembly (France)|France National Assembly]] and the faction was expelled from SFIO. 

Originally linked to [[Fascism|fascist]] politics in France, neosocialists expressed admiration for [[Italian Fascism|Italian fascism]]. This ideological orientation later emerged in a newly formed party, the [[Neosocialist Party]], which advocated [[authoritarianism]] and [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]] policies as well as intimate cooperation with the [[Nazi Party|Nazis]].

== History ==
In the wake of the [[Great Depression (France)|Great Depression]], a group of [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] members, led by [[Henri de Man]] in Belgium (the founder of the ideology of ''[[planisme]]'', i.e. planism meaning [[economic planning]]) and in France by [[Marcel Déat]], [[Pierre Renaudel]], [[René Belin]], the "neo-Turks" of the [[Radical Party (France)|Radical-Socialist Party]] ([[Pierre Mendès-France]]), opposed themselves to both gradual [[reformism]] and the idea of a Marxist-inspired popular revolution. Instead, influenced by Henri de Man's planism, they promoted a "constructive revolution" headed by the [[State (polity)|state]] and [[Technocracy (bureaucratic)|technocrats]] which would institute planification—the establishment of a technocratic [[planned economy]]. Such ideas also influenced the [[Non-conformists of the 1930s|non-conformist movement]] on the [[Political history of France#The Right|French right]].

Marcel Déat published in 1930 ''Perspectives socialistes'' (''Socialist Perspectives''), a revisionist work closely influenced by Henri de Man's planism. Along with over a hundred articles written in ''La vie socialiste'' (''The Socialist Life''), the review of the SFIO's right-wing, ''Perspective socialistes'' marked the shift of Déat from [[History of socialism|classical socialism]] to neosocialism. Déat replaced [[class struggle]] with [[class collaboration]] and [[Nationalism|national solidarity]], advocated [[Social corporatism|corporatism]] as a model of social organisation, replaced the notion of "[[Socialist mode of production|socialism]]" with "[[anti-capitalism]]" and supported a technocratic state which would plan the economy and in which [[parliamentarism]] would be replaced by political [[technocracy]].<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Zeev Sternhell]]|chapter=Les convergences fascistes|pages=533&ndash;564|title=Nouvelle histoire des idées politiques|editor=Pascal Ory|publisher=Pluriel Hachette|year=1987|language=French|isbn=2-01-010906-6}}</ref>

The neosocialist faction inside of the SFIO, which included Marcel Déat and Pierre Renaudel, were expelled during the November 1933 Congress because of their revisionist stances and admiration for Italian fascism. The neosocialists advocated alliances with the middle classes and favoured making compromises with the "[[bourgeois]]" [[Radical Party (France)|Radical-Socialist Party]] to enact the SFIO's program one issue at a time. After having been expelled from the SFIO, Marcel Déat and his followers created the [[Socialist Party of France – Jean Jaurès Union]] (1933–1935) which was one of the main expression of neosocialism in France. Inside the [[General Confederation of Labour (France)|General Confederation of Labour]]  trade union, neosocialism was represented by René Belin's ''Syndicats'' (then ''Redressements'')'s faction.{{citation needed|date=December 2007}}

On the other hand, Henri de Man's planism influenced the [[Politics of France#The Left|left-wing]] of the Radical Party, called "Young Turks" (among them Pierre Mendès-France). ''Planisme'' would later influence [[dirigisme|dirigism]] (''dirigisme''), the postwar [[Indicative planning|semi-planned economy]], [[Regionalism (politics)|regionalism]], [[spatial planning]] as well as [[Pierre Mendès France|Mendesism]], "left-wing [[Gaullism]]" ([[Louis Vallon]]) and socialist clubs in the 1960s (Club Jean Moulin).{{citation needed|date=December 2007}}

The neosocialists eventually evolved toward a form of participatory and [[national socialism]] which led them to join with the [[Reactionary|reactionary right]] and support the collaborationist [[Vichy Regime]] during the [[Second World War]] (René Belin and Marcel Déat became members of the [[Vichy France|Vichy government]]). As a result, Déat's neosocialism was discredited in France after the war.{{citation needed|date=December 2007}}

